  ('ip485', 'Island Packet 485', 'Island Packet Yachts · USA', 'Bob Johnson', '#2c6072', '2002–c.2017', 'GRP (solid hull)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center cockpit', '51''7" (15.72 m)', '43''2" (13.16 m)', '15''4" (4.67 m)', '5''3" (1.60 m, shoal)', '5''3" (1.60 m, shoal)', '17,690 kg / 39,000 lb (light; ~44,150 lb loaded)', '16,000 lb lead', '~41%', '1,267 ft²', '63''6" (19.35 m)', 'Yanmar 100 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Integral one-piece "Full Foil" shoal keel (internal lead, no keel bolts) · keel-protected counterbalanced spade rudder', 'Deep, high, dry center cockpit (an "all-weather sanctuary"); usually full-enclosed', '1,135 L / 300 gal', '1,287 L / 340 gal', 15.72, 43.17, 15.33, 39000, 1.6, '~17.6', '~216', 1135, 1287, 100, 250000, 500000, 'fit', 1, 'The returning Island Packet hand who wants a maximally protected center cockpit, idiot-proof short-handed handling, go-anywhere shoal draft and cavernous storage — a true liveaboard home well under budget.', 'A deep, high, dry center cockpit two steps up from the deck — Cruising World called it an "all-weather sanctuary" with commanding views and 7-ft seats, routinely fitted with a full enclosure. Excellent in cold/wet high latitudes and shaded in the tropics.', 'Cutter — in-mast furling main, a roller-furling genoa, and a self-tacking roller-furling staysail on a Hoyt jib boom (self-tacking + furling, no club-foot hassle). Double backstay.', 'Designed expressly for couple/family operation without crew: all furling controls lead to the cockpit, a self-tacking staysail, electric primary/main winches and an optional bow thruster; forgiving, well-balanced, tracks hands-off. (Tacks ~100° — comfort over pointing.)', 'Good central engine access (insulated engine box); the multi-use forward third cabin converts to an L-shaped counter/desk with cabinets — explicitly marketed as office/laundry/workshop space.', 'Typically a genset, reverse-cycle A/C-heat, an inverter/charger, a watermaker, keel-cooled Frigoboat fridge+freezer, VacuFlush heads and an isolation transformer — all conventional, well-documented marine systems.', 'Exceptional — a huge full-width lazarette ("the size of a studio apartment") accessed from the deck and the aft cabin (holds a second dinghy/dive gear), a divided anchor locker, a companionway wet locker and under-berth bins.', 'Big 300-gal fuel / 340-gal water — long motoring range and months of self-sufficient liveaboard provisioning.', 'True liveaboard volume — an open panoramic raised-deck saloon, a full nav station (SAIL: "the best-equipped nav station we saw"), 3 cabins / 2 heads with separate showers. Big secure side decks, a low transom/swim platform and the protected center cockpit make dog handling easy; shoal draft eases beaching/shore runs.', 'Credible — a heavily-built solid-glass hull, CE Cat A, an enclosed protected cockpit and reverse-cycle heat; but it''s a warm-water Florida design, so add diesel/forced-air heating and good ground tackle. The moderate shoal draft is a real asset in poorly-charted southern channels.', 'Ideal — the 5''3" Full Foil keel opens the BVI, Bahamas, ICW, Polynesian lagoons and South American shoals deep-fin boats can''t reach, while the integral keel + keel-protected rudder/prop tolerate the inevitable grounding far better than a bolt-on fin.', '$250k–$500k (used)', 'Out of production (sailaway ~$600k in 2003)', 'Used ~$250k–$500k', 'Fits with huge headroom — even the best examples sit around half the budget, leaving substantial room for a refit, heating, electronics and reserve. A strong value play, especially for a returning IP hand.', '"Karma" (2006) has crossed the Atlantic single-handed; "Sweet Dream" circumnavigated; the IP 485 has a strong owner-cruising record. Island Packet has won 7 Cruising World Boat of the Year awards as a brand.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4,"workshop":4,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":4,"tropical":5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Shoal Full Foil keel', 'Center cockpit', 'Huge tankage + storage', 'Loyal owner community']::text[], array['Hull #1 "Dancing in the Dark" took 2nd in class in the 2002 Caribbean 1500 straight from the factory.', 'The full-width lazarette is big enough to swallow a second dinghy, dive gear and surfboards.', 'The self-tacking Hoyt jib boom makes day-sailing genuinely lazy — sheet it and let go of the wheel.']::text[], array['2005 IP 485, Fort Pierce FL — $398,000 (S&J Yachts)', '2004 IP 485, Hilton Head SC — $344,000 (Knot 10)', '2006 "Karma," Canaries (EU VAT paid) — €299,000 (Grabau)']::text[], '[{"name":"Cruising World review","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/island-packet-485-voyager-thats-true-form/"},{"name":"SailboatData (IP 485/525)","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/island-packet-485525/"},{"name":"Wikipedia — Island Packet","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Island_Packet_Yachts"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"IP 485 \"Rula Bula\" — walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LsfGn15onOQ","note":"David Walters Yachts tour & review"},{"name":"IP 485 — refit walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tFi519vU0-0","note":"Post-refit example"},{"name":"IP 485 haul-out / hull review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J2P4vAIlqcA","note":"Ian Van Tuyl design/inspection"},{"name":"IP 485 owner tour (2006)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8Ysxs9YBWY","note":"Owner walkthrough"}]'::jsonb, array['Bulletproof solid-glass build, CE Cat A, grounding-tolerant integral keel — a strong owner-reported offshore track record.', 'Outstanding short-handed package: cockpit-led furling, self-tacking Hoyt staysail, electric winches, optional thruster.', 'A deep, dry, very protected center cockpit — superb in cold/wet weather and a safe space with dogs aboard.', 'Enormous storage (a studio-apartment lazarette) plus a dedicated convertible office/workshop cabin.', 'Big tankage (300 gal fuel / 340 gal water) and easy long-range motoring.', 'Shoal 5''3" draft unlocks gunkholing, the tropics, the ICW and shallow southern cruising grounds.']::text[], array['Moderate-heavy, low-aspect rig — modest windward performance (tacks ~100°) and light-air sluggishness; a comfort cruiser, not a flyer.', 'In-mast furling main is convenience over performance (jam/reefing-shape compromises).', 'Warm-water Florida design — needs added heating/insulation for serious high-latitude work.', 'Center cockpit raises boom/handhold ergonomics; early boats had engine-noise and a propane-drain issue (since corrected).', 'Older boats: aging genset/A/C/electronics and chainplate/port-bedding items to budget for.', 'Out of production with a modest fleet — fewer comps and slower resale.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World (Darrell Nicholson)","note":"Praised its balance, payload and seakeeping — \"a true liveaboard long-range cruiser\"; judge Carol Hasse: \"obviously set up with long passages in mind.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/island-packet-485-voyager-thats-true-form/"},{"who":"SAIL Magazine — Best Boats judges","note":"On the nav station: \"Any offshore navigator would love to call this nerve center home. This is the best-equipped nav station we saw this year.\"","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Island_Packet_Yachts"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (two-spreader rig)","keelRudder":"Integral one-piece molded \"Full Foil\" shoal keel with internal lead ballast — no keel bolts · counterbalanced spade rudder connected to the keel''s trailing edge (protected)","complexity":"Moderate–High when fully outfitted (genset, multiple A/C, watermaker, in-mast furling, electric winches, thruster) — but all conventional, well-documented marine systems, not exotic.","maintain":"Good — a conventional accessible Yanmar, standard marine gear, a famously thorough factory-manual culture, and the convertible workshop cabin help the hands-on owner.","partsText":"Builder is alive — Island Packet (Largo, FL) was acquired by Darrell & Leslie Allen in 2017 and \"reborn\" (50+ staff, veteran craftsmen), still building and supporting legacy models; the Allens'' San Diego roots help West-Coast owners. Strong US parts/knowledge base.","problems":"Aging electronics/genset/A/C on early boats; chainplate inspection (the IPYOA keeps a chainplate database); port/window bedding (screwed frames — IP cites zero field failures); in-mast furling maintenance; early engine-noise + propane drain-loop issues (factory-corrected).","sentiment":"Strongly positive and famously loyal — Island Packet has \"one of the most enthusiastic and loyal followings in cruising-boat history\"; values held well on build quality and reputation.","communities":[{"name":"Island Packet Owners Assoc. (IPYOA) forum","url":"https://www.ipyoa.com/forum"},{"name":"IPYOA (Facebook)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/IPYOA/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum — IP 485 thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/island-packet-485-a-17768.html"}],"risks":["Out of production + a modest fleet — fewer comps, slower resale","In-mast furling + shoal-keel pointing won''t suit performance-minded sailors","Warm-water Florida design — add heating/insulation + ground tackle for serious high latitudes","Budget a systems refresh (genset/A/C/electronics) on 15–20-yr-old boats"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3,"parts":4,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('pure42', 'Pure 42', 'Pure Yachts · Germany', 'Berckemeyer (Martin Menzner)', '#1f6f7a', '2024–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aluminium deck saloon', '45''3" (13.80 m)', '40''4" (12.30 m)', '13''8" (4.20 m)', '3''11" (1.20 m up)', '9''10" (3.00 m down)', '9,800 kg / 21,600 lb', '3,300 kg lead bulb', '~34%', '99 m² / 1,065 ft²', '18.2 m / 59''9"', 'Yanmar 4JH57 (57 hp)', 'Saildrive', '2 cabins / 2 heads', 'Hydraulic lifting T-keel (lead bulb) in a welded aluminium keel box — no fixed-keel option · twin rudders', 'Deep protected cockpit under a deck-saloon overhang; near-360° glazed inside lounging/steering', '400 L / 106 gal', '300 L / 79 gal', 13.8, 40.4, 13.68, 21600, 1.2, '~22.1', '~147', 400, 300, 57, 1270000, 1500000, 'over', 3, 'The well-funded couple who want the newest, best-built aluminium go-anywhere boat that also sails fast — high latitudes to tropics — and can stretch past $1M.', 'Deep, well-protected crew cockpit with high coamings and a cuddy-like coachroof overhang that keeps two crew "almost fully protected while outside" (Yachting World); the deck saloon gives near-360° glazed shelter. No standard sprayhood — the overhang substitutes.', 'Two-spreader aluminium rig standard (carbon + square-top optional); a solent-ish genoa + staysail; all lines led aft under deck to two electric Andersen winches at the helms; a retractable bow thruster is standard.', 'Engineered for a couple — an uncluttered cockpit, push-button keel, electric winches, standard autopilot; genoa + staysail give an easily-managed split inventory; reviewers praised one-handed handling. The big performance rig adds running backstays.', 'A standout — no aft cabins, so the whole stern is engine room + stowage with excellent multi-side access; the modular starboard space can be a workbench/workshop, office or pilot berth.', 'Deliberately simple but high-end: twin LiFePO4 banks, charger, shore power, diesel heating, big solar (the prototype carried ~2,000 W); composite seacocks on welded above-WL standpipes (replaceable afloat).', 'Exceptional — the stern is dedicated to machinery + lockers, ~2.5–3 m³ under the galley sole, 80 kg-rated drawers, "lockers in every nook and cranny."', 'Modest standard tankage (2×200 L fuel) — augment with jerry cans/watermaker for the longest Pacific/Patagonia legs.', 'Two large doubles + a flexible third space, an owner''s bath + day-heads, and a light-flooded deck saloon. Dog-friendly low walk-around side decks (two steps, no climbing) + grippy SeaDek; but a high-topside alloy boat with hard surfaces — plan a boarding ramp.', 'Strong — 15 mm bottom plating, 80 mm Armaflex insulation, diesel heat, CE-A, deck-saloon inside steering, dry-out on the keel + twin rudders, above-WL seacocks. Explicitly marketed for high-latitude journeys.', 'Capable — big solar, shoal keel for reefs/atolls; but the glazed saloon needs ventilation/shade in the heat, and alloy demands anode/electrical discipline in warm marinas. Modest tankage limits Pacific range.', '~$1.27M–$1.5M (new)', 'Base €1,129,310 ex-VAT (~$1.27–1.32M); performance pkg ~€1.32M', 'Brand-new (2024) — no used market yet', 'Over budget — base alone is ~$1.27M+ and there''s no used market yet. Included as the aspirational new benchmark (EYOTY 2026); the in-budget cousins are the Ovni 430 and the used aluminium centreboarders.', 'Too new for voyages; sibling Pure 49 "Gorre" raced the doublehanded Baltic 500 (2026).', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":5,"tankage":3,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":1.5}'::jsonb, array['EYOTY 2026 winner', 'Aluminium + fast', 'Lifting T-keel', 'Over budget (new)']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2026 (Best Bluewater Cruiser) — beat the Boréal 56 and Kraken 58.', 'Will plane and surf to 11–15 kn downwind — extraordinary for an "explorer."', 'The prototype "Tom Kyle" wears a signal-orange coachroof; lift the keel and dry out on a beach.']::text[], array['New base €1,129,310 ex-VAT (~$1.27–1.32M)', 'EYOTY test boat (carbon rig) €1,316,750', 'No used market — the design is ~1 year old']::text[], '[{"name":"Yachting World review","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/pure-42-review-why-this-alloy-cruiser-is-the-new-benchmark-for-bluewater-cruising"},{"name":"YACHT test","url":"https://www.yacht.de/en/yachts/cruising-yachts/pure-42-blue-water-yacht-made-of-aluminium-is-tough-and-faster-to-the-finish-line/"},{"name":"Pure Yachts","url":"https://www.pure.yachts/pure42"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Yachting World — we sail the Pure 42","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uGrEQB-Xxow","note":"Full sea-trial"},{"name":"Pure 42 — lift-keel performance cruiser","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vzsI6YnM2ec","note":"Overview"},{"name":"100% aluminium 2026 — Pure 42","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zND_bzXERW0","note":"Walkaround"},{"name":"Pure Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@pure.yachts","note":"Tours/launch clips"}]'::jsonb, array['Award-winning, exceptional build (EYOTY 2026; reviewers struggled to find faults).', 'True go-anywhere aluminium with dry-out capability and superb crew protection.', 'Rare combination of explorer ruggedness AND genuine performance (light, fast, fun to helm).', 'Outstanding engine/systems access and stowage; a modular workshop/office option.', 'Deliberately simple, top-tier standard systems (LiFePO4, electric winches, bow thruster all standard).', 'Deck-saloon liveaboard comfort with panoramic light.']::text[], array['Price well over the $1M budget; no used market.', 'Modest fuel/water tankage limits true long-passage range without add-ons.', 'Brand-new startup yard — limited track record, no global service/parts network yet.', 'Lifting-keel hydraulics + twin-rudder steering add complexity (prototype steering felt stiff).', 'The performance rig brings running backstays — extra short-handed workload.', 'A hard, performance-tuned hull gives a firmer motion than a heavy traditional cruiser.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2026']::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (EYOTY jury)","note":"\"Superb crew protection, light and views, stowage galore, comfort and formidable quality.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/pure-42-review-why-this-alloy-cruiser-is-the-new-benchmark-for-bluewater-cruising"},{"who":"Lars Reisberg · No-Frills-Sailing","note":"\"The current pinnacle of available 40-something-footers of alloy go-anywhere yachts.\"","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/tag/pureyachts/"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2026', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Hydraulic lifting T-keel (lead bulb) — no bolt-on fixed keel · twin welded-aluminium-tube rudders (Jefa, dual-redundant)","complexity":"Moderate — intentionally simple top-tier systems (LiFePO4, electric winches, thruster standard), but the hydraulic lifting keel + dual-redundant twin-rudder steering are bespoke.","maintain":"Good design intent (above-WL replaceable seacocks, excellent engine/systems access) but aluminium care + keel hydraulics favour competent owners/yard support.","partsText":"Brand-new German startup (founded ~2022, ~20 staff) — no established global dealer/parts network yet. Off-the-shelf systems (Yanmar, Andersen, Jefa, NKE) are serviceable; Pure-specific items tie you to Kiel.","problems":"Prototype only — acrylic saloon windows glared (corrected to ESG glass from hull #2); steering felt stiff with some rudder vibration; minor first-hull snags. No fleet reliability data yet.","sentiment":"No owner base yet; expert/media sentiment is exceptionally high (EYOTY 2026, reviewers struggled to find faults).","communities":[{"name":"Pure Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.pure.yachts/"},{"name":"No-Frills-Sailing (Pure tag)","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/tag/pureyachts/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum (metal boats)","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/"}],"risks":["Price — well over $1M, no used market","New marque — resale/warranty depth unproven, no global service network","Modest standard tankage limits long-passage range","Bespoke keel hydraulics + twin-rudder steering need specialist familiarity"],"scores":{"maintain":3.5,"simplicity":3.5,"parts":2.5,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('bestevaer49', 'Bestevaer 49ST', 'KM Yachtbuilders · Netherlands', 'Dykstra Naval Architects', '#2a5566', '2009–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Pilothouse (inside helm)', '49''1" (14.97 m)', '45''0" (13.72 m)', '14''5" (4.40 m)', '6''11" (2.10 m fin)', '6''11" (2.10 m; lifting-keel option avail.)', '17,000 kg / 37,479 lb', '5,900 kg lead', '~35%', '104.7 m² / 1,127 ft²', '~23 m / 75''', 'Yanmar 4JH4-TE75 (75 hp)', 'Shaft', '2 cabins / 1 head', 'Aluminium fin keel with bulb (lifting-keel option on some hulls) — no bolt-on lead keel · single spade rudder; round-bilge alloy hull', 'Fixed aluminium pilothouse with inside steering/chart station + a long sheltered cockpit', '750 L / 198 gal', '720 L / 190 gal', 14.97, 45, 14.4, 37479, 2.1, '~16.2', '~183', 750, 720, 75, 550000, 850000, 'fit', 1, 'The short-handed couple who want a genuine Dykstra/KM aluminium pilothouse expedition boat — Spitsbergen to the tropics — achievable used under $1M.', 'The defining Bestevaer trait — a true fixed aluminium pilothouse with inside steering, a chart station and saloon-level glazing, plus a long, low, sheltered cockpit. Stand watch protected; ideal for cold, wet high latitudes.', 'Fractional sloop-cutter (yankee + staysail), carbon or aluminium mast; furling headsails, a fully-battened main with one-line slab reefing, a retractable bowsprit for an asymmetric.', 'Designed for single/double-handed sailing — electric primary winches, all lines aft, a simple performance sail plan, autopilot + windvane fits; tiller steering gives direct feel and frees cockpit movement.', 'Excellent — a gas-strut cockpit-bench panel opens directly to the machinery space, with more access via the aft-cabin bulkhead; built around serviceability with accessible tankage and generous lockers.', 'Victron/Mastervolt inverter/charger, 3 house banks, MPPT solar (often + a wind gen), Webasto/Refleks hydronic heating, a Spectra watermaker, an electric bow thruster and B&G/Simrad electronics — robust, mostly mainstream gear.', 'Strong — under-berth drawers, hanging lockers, a forepeak behind a watertight collision bulkhead and a big lazarette; the optional third-cabin-as-storage is popular with long-haul couples.', 'Big tanks, long legs — ~1,200–1,400 nm motoring; a watermaker makes water range effectively unlimited.', '2 cabins / 1 head (owner + guest doubles), a mahogany-and-white classic interior, a proper forward-facing nav station. The pilothouse gives dogs a sheltered indoor ride; flat wide side decks with bulwarks aid safety; a fold-down platform helps dog ingress. Only 1 head is the liveaboard limit.', 'Native habitat — unpainted alloy (ice/impact tolerant, no gelcoat to chip), a watertight collision bulkhead, a sheltered pilothouse, diesel hydronic heat, an optional lifting keel to dry out. Routinely in Spitsbergen, Greenland, Patagonia, the Antarctic Peninsula.', 'Equally at home — designed "for cold climates but equally at home in the tropics"; good ventilation, awnings, a watermaker. Alloy can run hot in the tropics but is manageable; disciplined anode/galvanic care needed.', '$550k–$850k (used)', 'New customs run €1.0M–€2M+', 'Used 49ST ~$550k–$850k; a used 45ST sister verified at ~$450k', 'Fits used — a 49ST lands ~$550k–$850k, the smaller 45ST sister from ~$450k. New customs and 53ft+ boats are over $1M. Scarce, mostly in Europe (relocation logistics).', 'Bestevaer 56 "Tranquilo/Falcon Spirit" — Northwest Passage ×2, Patagonia, Antarctic Peninsula, 150,000+ nm; the line is a high-latitude icon.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4,"budget":3.5}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium pilothouse', 'Dykstra/KM expedition', 'Polar-proven', 'Tiller-simple']::text[], array['The boat the designer Gerard Dijkstra built for himself (Bestevaer II) — a near-cult of go-anywhere alloy purists.', 'A sister 56, "Tranquilo," sailed the Northwest Passage solo TWICE and logged 150,000+ miles in both polar circles.', 'Lift the keel (where fitted) and walk around your boat at low tide in Patagonia or Scotland.']::text[], array['2011 Bestevaer 45ST "Oliver 3" — $450,000 (Swiftsure, Seattle)', '2016 45ST Pure — ~€495,000 (Netherlands)', '2014 49ST "Mate" — De Valk (sold)']::text[], '[{"name":"SailboatData — 49ST","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/bestevaer-49st/"},{"name":"De Valk listing","url":"https://www.devalk.nl/en/yachtbrokerage/252316/BESTEVAER-49-ST.html"},{"name":"Swiftsure — 45ST","url":"https://swiftsureyachts.com/2011-bestevaer-45st-oliver-3/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Bestevaer 49ST \"Katharos\" — full tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvm_7YqTwHQ","note":"Interior & exterior walkthrough"},{"name":"Bestevaer 45ST \"Oliver 3\" (Swiftsure)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mAaYISObFRk","note":"Tour of the $450k 45ST"},{"name":"KM Yachtbuilders — Bestevaer playlist","url":"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL7fVKEUZ_SFlYflGOTSgyVUWASQYphur5","note":"Builder build/sail videos"}]'::jsonb, array['Aluminium hull — immensely strong, impact/ice-tolerant, repairable anywhere there''s a welder, no osmosis.', 'Pilothouse with inside steering — genuine protected watch-keeping; transforms high-latitude comfort.', 'Designed from the keel up for single/double-handed sailing (electric winches, lines aft, autopilot/windvane).', 'Big tankage and long range; lifting-keel option for shoal/drying anchorages.', 'Proven expedition pedigree (Dykstra design, KM build) — and stable resale value.', 'Excellent engine access and owner-maintainable systems.']::text[], array['Scarce on the market — few built, mostly in Europe; finding/relocating the right one takes patience.', 'Custom/semi-custom — every boat differs; survey and spec each individually.', 'Higher entry cost than equivalent-length GRP production cruisers.', 'Only 1 head and (45ST) 2 cabins — tight for guests + two dogs; the 49 helps.', 'Aluminium demands electrical/galvanic discipline (bonding, isolation, anodes).', 'Tiller + minimalist ethos won''t suit those wanting a push-button, fully enclosed cockpit.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"De Valk Yacht Brokers","note":"The 49ST is \"one of the best tough sailing yachts in the world… a very comfortable boat for long trips\" (the pilothouse).","url":"https://www.devalk.nl/en/yachtbrokerage/252316/BESTEVAER-49-ST.html"},{"who":"Lars Reisberg · No-Frills-Sailing","note":"Bestevaers are \"synonymous for high quality, classy-styled pilot-house sloops… go-anywhere yachts.\"","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/bestevaer-45-pure/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (carbon or alloy Seldén)","keelRudder":"Aluminium fin keel with bulb (lifting-keel option on some hulls), no bolt-on lead keel · single spade rudder; tiller steering","complexity":"Moderate — simpler than a luxury production boat by design (\"Pure\" ethos), but watermaker, hydronic heat, solar/wind, thruster and electronics add up; manageable for a returning skipper.","maintain":"High by intent — superb engine access, accessible tankage, a rugged alloy interior and conventional brand-name components; alloy welding repairs need a specialist but are straightforward where alloy yards exist.","partsText":"KM Yachtbuilders (Makkum, NL) still active and maintains/refits its own boats; parts mostly standard marine kit (globally supportable). Anything hull/structural/custom routes through KMY or a competent alloy yard. Two related brand entities now exist — confirm who supports a given hull.","problems":"Galvanic/stray-current corrosion is the perennial alloy concern (bonding, isolation, anodes). Custom variation — verify each boat''s exact spec, tankage, keel type and rig on survey.","sentiment":"Strongly positive in the alloy-expedition community; brokers call them \"one of the best tough sailing yachts in the world,\" prized for sailing and pilothouse comfort, with stable resale value.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — 49ST thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/bestevaer-49st-147499.html"},{"name":"KM Yachtbuilders","url":"https://kmyachtbuilders.com/"},{"name":"Bestevaer fleet","url":"https://bestevaer.com/fleet/"}],"risks":["Scarce — few built, mostly in Europe (relocation/survey logistics)","Custom/semi-custom — every boat differs; survey & spec individually","Aluminium galvanic/electrical discipline required","Only 1 head / 2 cabins — tight for guests + two dogs (the 49 helps over the 45)"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":4,"parts":3,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('alliage45', 'Alliage 45', 'Alliage Yachting · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#357065', '~2000s (defunct 2011)', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft (watertight companionway)', '47''7" (14.5 m)', '~41''8" (12.7 m est.)', '14''5" (4.41 m)', '3''7" (1.10 m up)', '9''2" (2.80 m down est.)', '15,000 kg / 33,069 lb', 'n/a', 'n/a', '~110–120 m² (cutter)', 'n/a', 'Volvo D2-75 (75 hp)', 'Shaft', '~3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Integral aluminium centreboard (lifting board in a watertight case) — no bolt-on keel · protected/skeg rudder (varies by hull)', 'Deep central cockpit with two helm stations + a watertight companionway door', '~500 L / 132 gal (est.)', '~500 L / 132 gal (est.)', 14.5, 41.7, 14.5, 33069, 1.1, 'n/a', '~200', 500, 500, 75, 280000, 450000, 'fit', 1, 'The returning skipper who wants genuine go-anywhere aluminium capability (high latitudes + tropics + lifting board) at well under new-Garcia money — and is comfortable owning an orphaned but well-built French boat.', 'Deep, large central cockpit with two steering positions and a sprayhood-protected companionway; the watertight companionway door (a Berret-Racoupeau signature also on Garcia/Boréal) makes it a genuinely sheltered, high-latitude-grade station.', 'Cutter — staysail + genoa on an inner-forestay arrangement for easy reefing and balanced sail; an aluminium mast, slab or in-mast reefing depending on the hull.', 'Designed (per the builder) "to sail around the world short-handed, with no north or south limits" — a cutter with manageable sail areas, two helm stations and a lifting board for easy anchoring. Well-suited to two.', 'Engine under the companionway/cockpit sole with good all-round access; semi-custom builds typically include a workshop/tool area and big engine-room volume — but the exact layout varies by hull.', 'Heavily-equipped semi-custom blue-water fit-outs (the cited 2010 hull was "ready for world cruising"); expect a substantial house bank, watermaker, heating and nav suite — but systems are bespoke and 2000s-era, so survey each boat.', 'A roomy aluminium hull with generous stowage; the lifting board frees bilge volume. Semi-custom layouts vary.', 'Class-typical ~800–1,000 nm motoring (exact tankage not in the public record — verify per hull).', 'A roomy aluminium interior; the lifting board lets you beach/anchor in thin water for easy dog access; a flat alloy deck and protected cockpit are practical. Two dogs are workable on the 14.5 m hull. Layouts vary (semi-custom).', 'Strong — an aluminium hull (ice/debris tolerant), a watertight companionway, a protected cockpit and a lifting board for gunkholing/drying out — the Patagonia/Chile/Scandinavia toolkit. Heating/insulation are owner-fit; verify.', 'Capable — the lifting board is a plus for reefs/beaches; but the 2000s layout favours protection over tropical ventilation, and alloy needs good airflow + galvanic discipline in the heat.', '$280k–$450k (used)', 'Out of production (builder liquidated 2011)', 'Used ~$280k–$450k; a 2010 hull listed €390,000', 'Fits with huge headroom — a well-found Alliage 45 leaves six figures for refit, watermaker and a high-latitude heating package. The catch is the orphaned builder + tiny owner base + Europe-only inventory.', 'No verifiable celebrity expedition (tiny fleet, sparse record) — the type was privately world-cruised; documented high-latitude voyages exist for the closely-related Allures/Garcia.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4,"dogs":4,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium centreboard', 'Berret-Racoupeau pedigree', 'Lifting board', 'Orphan builder']::text[], array['The founders launched Alliage in 1995 because no one built high-end aluminium 12–15 m cruisers.', 'Alliage and Alubat (Ovni/Cigale) briefly shared the same Arthub holding — the "obscure cousin" is literally a corporate sibling of the Ovni dynasty.', 'Same Berret-Racoupeau designers as the Allures/Garcia-era aluminium boats.']::text[], array['2010 Alliage 45, France — €390,000 (~$420k, AYC)', '2006 Alliage 48 CC "Vagabond" (refit 2021) — €480,000', '2009 Alliage Azzuro 53 — ~$824k (YachtWorld)']::text[], '[{"name":"Course au Large — history","url":"https://www.courseaularge.com/une-nouvelle-ere-pour-alliage-yachts.html"},{"name":"DailyBoats/AYC listing","url":"https://dailyboats.com/boat/171867-buy-alliage-45-for-sale"},{"name":"ActuNautique — liquidation","url":"https://www.actunautique.com/article-le-chantier-naval-alliage-yachts-56-place-en-liquidation-judiciaire-87280719.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Alliage 53 — builder presentation (FR)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5vREc-C4JPs","note":"Closest first-party Alliage video"},{"name":"Allures 45.9 guided tour (comparable)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iKoENKdoZyk","note":"Berret-Racoupeau aluminium 45 cousin"},{"name":"Garcia Exploration 45 (comparable)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GTG4oP5wNX0","note":"Benchmark go-anywhere 45"}]'::jsonb, array['True dual-climate go-anywhere aluminium with a lifting centreboard (beach it, dry out, gunkhole).', 'Protected deep cockpit, two helm stations, a watertight companionway — short-handed and high-latitude friendly.', 'Berret-Racoupeau pedigree (same designers as Allures/Garcia-era boats) — a proven, well-mannered cutter.', 'Excellent value — substantially cheaper than an equivalent Garcia Exploration 45 or Allures.', 'Semi-custom, heavily-equipped blue-water fit-outs are common on the used market.', 'A manageable 75 hp / shaft drivetrain — simple, robust, parts-available propulsion.']::text[], array['Builder is defunct — no factory, warranty, or first-party parts/hull-specific support.', 'Very rare — a tiny owner base, almost no public spec data, few comparables for valuation.', 'Aluminium demands disciplined galvanic/electrical management (bonding, isolation, no stray current).', 'Each boat is semi-custom with 2000s-era bespoke systems — a survey-heavy purchase.', 'Most/all boats are in Europe — likely import, delivery and survey logistics for a US buyer.', 'Resale liquidity is poor; you buy it for use, not for easy flipping.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"A&C Yacht Brokers","note":"\"A French builder specialising in robust, elegant integral aluminium blue-water centreboarders.\"","url":"https://www.boats-caribbean.com/shipyards/alliage"},{"who":"Course au Large","note":"A specialist in high-end aluminium 50–60 ft cruisers — and (briefly) a corporate sibling of the Alubat/Ovni aluminium dynasty.","url":"https://www.courseaularge.com/une-nouvelle-ere-pour-alliage-yachts.html"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (keel-stepped on some hulls — varies)","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium centreboard (lifting board in a watertight case) — no bolt-on keel · protected/skeg rudder (varies by hull)","complexity":"Moderate — a simple hull/rig, but bespoke 2000s systems vary by boat; a full systems survey is essential.","maintain":"Good for a competent owner who understands aluminium (bonding, anodes, isolation, no copper antifoul); the hull itself is tough and low-maintenance.","partsText":"Builder DEFUNCT (Alliage liquidated 2011) — no factory, warranty or first-party parts. Generic systems (Volvo, standard rig/gear) are well-supported; anything Alliage-specific relies on surveyors, French alloy yards (Alubat-network, Meta, JFA) and the used market.","problems":"Galvanic corrosion if electrical isolation is neglected; an orphaned-builder support gap; thin valuation data + poor resale liquidity; ageing bespoke systems; almost all boats in Europe.","sentiment":"Sparse — forums note \"very little information online,\" though the boats are regarded as well-built, high-finish aluminium cruisers. The data vacuum itself is the recurring complaint.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Alliage thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/alliage-aluminium-sailboats-any-experience-64931.html"},{"name":"Allures–Garcia Owners forum","url":"https://alluresgarciaowners.discussion.community/"},{"name":"AluminumAlloyBoats forum","url":"http://www.aluminumalloyboats.com/viewforum.php?f=4"}],"risks":["Builder defunct — no factory/warranty/first-party parts","Very rare — tiny owner base, little public data, hard to value","Aluminium galvanic/electrical discipline required","Europe-only inventory — import/delivery/survey logistics; poor resale liquidity"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":2,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('sirius40ds', 'Sirius 40 DS', 'Sirius-Werft · Germany', 'Marc-Oliver von Ahlen', '#3a5a72', '2015–present', 'GRP (foam-cored)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Deck saloon (inside helm)', '42''3" (12.90 m)', '36''8" (11.17 m)', '13''5" (4.08 m)', '4''9" (1.45 m twin keel)', '7''7" (2.30 m fin)', '11,600 kg / 25,574 lb', '~3,450 kg', '~30%', '81.3 m² / 875 ft²', '~19.8 m / 65''', 'Volvo D2-50 (50 hp)', 'Saildrive', '2–3 cabins / 1–2 heads', 'Fin (2.30/2.00/1.75 m), twin bilge keel (1.45 m, dries out) or true swing keel (0.95–2.50 m) · partial-skeg rudder', 'Deep protected cockpit at saloon level + an INTERIOR helm/steering station inside the 360°-glazed deck saloon', '200 L / 53 gal', '400 L / 106 gal', 12.9, 36.65, 13.39, 25574, 1.45, '~16.2', '~232', 200, 400, 50, 450000, 800000, 'fit', 1, 'A liveaboard couple — one experienced, one beginner — who prize protection, comfort, build quality and shelter, and want one bespoke boat for both Scandinavian cold and the tropics.', 'A deep, protected cockpit at saloon ("eye") level, plus the standout: an INTERIOR helm/steering station inside the 360°-glazed deck saloon — steer dry and warm (the reviewer rode out a 30-kt squall from inside). A genuinely weather-protected boat for a nervous crew member.', 'A two-spreader fractional/Solent rig; a standard self-tacking jib + a twin single-line-reefed main; optional genoa/gennaker/drifter/spinnaker. Adjustable backstay; all lines led aft.', 'Designed for short-handing — a self-tacking jib (tack and forget), all lines aft, an electric windlass + Rocna standard, and a hinged centreline wheel so a solo helm can drive from either side. A forgiving, deliberate motion suits a beginner spouse.', 'A defining feature — a hidden technical/workshop room (hinge-out saloon bench) with a workbench, engine/electrical/plumbing access and space for a genset/laundry; the raised sole gives genuinely good standing engine access. Among the best owner-maintainability in class.', 'A full nav centre, a ~900 Ah house bank, a 50A shore charger, heating standard and pressurized water; readily expanded in the custom build (lithium, watermaker, genset).', 'Class-leading — four ~3-ft-deep under-sole compartments, ~1,600 L of galley shelving, a huge oilskin locker behind the helm seat, and two big cockpit lockers (to 4,500 L). The designer lived aboard 7 weeks to refine stowage.', 'Modest standard tankage (200 L fuel / 400 L water) — the one mission gap; spec larger tanks + a watermaker for long passages.', 'Two-level living — a raised saloon (galley + dinette + interior helm) over lower cabins; a quiet mid-ship cabin makes the best sea berth. For two + two dogs: the protected level saloon gives dogs a secure spot out of the weather; a fold-down transom/bathing platform eases boarding; cavernous stowage for dog gear. The twin-keel version dries out daily for dog runs ashore.', 'Strong — CE Cat A, a stout build, standard heating, an enclosed warm deck saloon you can steer from, a deep cockpit and robust ground tackle; a reviewer called it "uniquely perfect" for Alaska/the Inside Passage. Upsize fuel/water for the longest legs.', 'Good with care — the big glasshouse saloon needs ventilation/shade in the tropics (opening windows, 6 skylights, hatches; consider awnings/AC). Light decks help; the twin/shoal keels open up thin water.', '$450k–$800k (used)', 'New base ~€850k (~$920k); fully-kitted new at/over $1M', 'Used ~$450k–$800k+ depending on spec', 'Fits used; tight-to-over on new (Sirius''s all-inclusive base is ~€850k, so an equipped new build is at/over $1M). Buy a used twin-keel/fin example and upgrade tankage.', 'The first North American 40 DS sailed Germany→Vancouver and was tested in the San Juans/Salish Sea (48° North, 2020); owners cruise the Baltic, North Sea, Atlantic and Med.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4,"workshop":5,"storage":5,"tankage":3,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Interior-helm deck saloon', 'Hidden workshop room', 'Versatile keels', 'Beginner-friendly']::text[], array['The "secret" mid-ship cabin and a hinge-out passage to a hidden workshop are genuine wow-factor surprises.', 'A hinged centreline canting wheel lets you drive from either side and walk through.', 'The twin-keel version dries out on tidal flats so you can walk off the back at low water.']::text[], array['Used average asking ~$500k (sailboat-cruising)', 'New base ~€850,850 (YACHT 2024 group test)', 'Inventory thin — demand outstrips supply']::text[], '[{"name":"Sirius-Yachts spec","url":"https://www.sirius-yachts.com/yachts/40ds/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/sirius-40-ds/"},{"name":"48° North test","url":"https://48north.com/boats-and-gear/boat-reviews/sirius-40-ds-boat-test/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sirius 40 DS — full tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RMcxA5mDPwg","note":"Builder walkthrough"},{"name":"Sirius 40 DS boat test (48° North)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U7Qby0MZ6m4","note":"Independent test"},{"name":"2019 Sirius 40 DS twin-keel liveaboard","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgXE6oi7wKg","note":"Broker tour"},{"name":"Sirius 40 DS at the 2020 Seattle show","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MQgRIVw-kPg","note":"Show walkthrough"}]'::jsonb, array['Enclosed, heated deck saloon with an INTERIOR helm — steer in shelter; superb for cold/wet sailing and a nervous crew.', 'Outstanding storage and a dedicated workshop/technical room with genuine engine access — rare on a 40-footer.', 'Exceptional build quality — "structurally a beast," "dead quiet," superb fit/finish.', 'Hugely versatile keels (fin/shoal/twin/swing) — including a daily dry-out twin keel.', 'Easy, forgiving short-handed handling (self-tacking jib, lines aft, electric windlass standard).', 'True semi-custom — build the layout, tankage and systems to the exact mission.']::text[], array['Modest standard tankage (200 L fuel / 400 L water) — must be upsized for long-range passage-making.', 'Premium price — new base ~€850k; a fully-kitted new build pushes over $1M.', 'Not a strong light-air upwind performer (~25,000 lb is deliberate, not fast).', 'The big-glass saloon is a greenhouse in the tropics without good shade/ventilation.', 'Thin used market — few come up, and they hold value (hard to negotiate).', 'Small bespoke builder — superb yard support, but a limited dealer network and parts route through Germany.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"48° North (Joe Cline)","note":"\"A stout bluewater sailor… one of the most customizable production boats… structurally, the Sirius 40 is a beast.\"","url":"https://48north.com/boats-and-gear/boat-reviews/sirius-40-ds-boat-test/"},{"who":"Sailing Today","note":"\"If I was planning to sail around the world and live aboard, the Sirius 40 DS is the yacht I would go for.\"","url":"https://www.sailboat-cruising.com/Sirius-40.html"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (2-spreader Selden)","keelRudder":"Fin (2.30/2.00/1.75 m) / twin bilge keel (1.45 m, dries out) / true swing keel (0.95–2.50 m), bolted + glued · pre-balanced rudder on a half-skeg","complexity":"Moderate–High — semi-custom layouts mean long individualized plumbing/electrical runs; the swing-keel option adds real complexity (twin-keel/fin versions are simpler).","maintain":"Above average for the size — the workshop room and excellent engine/systems access are a deliberate design goal.","partsText":"Active, healthy family yard (~50 craftsmen) with excellent direct factory support; parts mostly mainstream (Volvo, Selden) so serviceable worldwide, but Sirius-specific items route through Plön, Germany.","problems":"No systemic faults surfaced; the chief practical limits are standard tankage and the tropical greenhouse effect. Build-quality complaints are essentially absent.","sentiment":"Very high — owners cite comfort, quiet, quality and versatility, and keep them long-term (which is why so few come up for sale).","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Sirius 40 DS","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/sirius-40-ds-161812-2.html"},{"name":"Sirius Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.sirius-yachts.com/"},{"name":"SailboatData forum","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/forums/topic-tag/sirius-40-ds/"}],"risks":["Buy used to stay under $1M (new is at/over budget)","Upgrade fuel & water for real range","If a swing-keel boat, budget for its maintenance","Thin resale supply — hard to find (but strong value retention)"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3,"parts":3,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('pogo1250', 'Pogo 12.50', 'Pogo Structures · France', 'Finot-Conq', '#4a5a66', '2010–2022', 'GRP (foam-cored)', 'Aft-cockpit bluewater', 'Open aft (exposed)', '41''0" (12.50 m)', '41''0" (12.50 m)', '14''9" (4.50 m)', '3''11" (1.20 m up)', '9''10" (3.00 m down)', '5,500 kg / 12,125 lb (light)', '2,000 kg', '~36%', '107 m² up / 218 m² down', '~19 m', 'Volvo D1-30 (30 hp)', 'Saildrive', '2–3 cabins / 1 head', 'Lifting swing keel (lead bulb on a vinylester fin); fixed-fin option · twin spade rudders; tiller', 'A wide, open aft cockpit optimised for tiller helming — no doghouse/pilothouse; minimal standard shelter', '60 L / 16 gal', '400 L / 106 gal', 12.5, 41, 14.76, 12125, 1.2, '~35', '~78', 60, 400, 30, 150000, 450000, 'fit', 1, 'A fit, competent couple who want a blisteringly fast, shoal-draft trade-wind/Caribbean/Pacific cruiser and will accept Spartan comfort and an exposed cockpit.', 'An honest weakness for this mission — a wide, open aft cockpit built for tiller helming, with no hardtop/doghouse and minimal standard sprayhood. No inside steering; the helmsman is exposed. For Scandinavia/Patagonia you''d depend on a robust aftermarket cockpit tent.', 'A carbon mast, a square-top fully-battened main (no backstay), a self-tacking solent + a removable inner staysail, plus a big downwind wardrobe (asym ~155 m², gennaker/Code 0) off a retractable carbon sprit. A true downwind weapon.', 'A genuine strength — easy to sail two-up or solo, all lines aft, forgiving and never out of control "even in 40+ kt gusts" (owners). But it''s a long tiller in an exposed cockpit — not push-button-from-shelter sailing.', 'Limited — the ~30 hp is accessed via the companionway steps; no stand-up engine room and no dedicated workshop. A no-frills racer-cruiser interior, not a systems/expedition layout.', 'Deliberately minimal (Pogo''s ethos: "cruising means sailing") — modest electrical demands, basic systems. Simplicity aids owner-maintainability but it''s not set up out of the box for a liveaboard power budget (heating/watermaker/freezer/big bank).', 'Surprisingly roomy for 40 ft (4.5 m beam, full headroom) — but the swing-keel case eats saloon space, and payload discipline matters: pile on cruising weight and the planing magic fades.', 'A tiny 60 L fuel tank = only ~150–250 nm motoring — a real liability for high-latitude calms/ice or long windless tropical passages; it''s a sailor''s boat, not a motorer.', 'Open-plan, light, airy, full headroom — two dogs would have floor space and the low transom eases boarding; but only 1 head, a Spartan finish, and a fast, jerky, noisy ride underway (no sound insulation). Not a calm, cosseting liveaboard for a beginner.', 'A poor fit — a light, flat, beamy planing hull gives a slammy, low-inertia ride into cold head seas; an exposed cockpit, no factory insulation/heating and a tiny fuel tank for motoring near ice. The opposite of a sheltered alloy expedition boat (though the lifting keel + Cat A/unsinkable build help).', 'Its natural habitat — effortless planing, surfing 12–20 kt, double-digit averages; Class-40 trade-wind DNA, and the lifting keel opens gin-clear lagoons (Bahamas, Tahiti, BVI). The trade-wind milk run is what this hull was born for.', '$150k–$450k (used)', 'New base was ~€241k ex-VAT (2020); out of production 2022', 'Used ~$150k–$450k', 'Fits with room to spare — the constraint is fit-for-mission, not price. (If you love the ethos, the newer Pogo 44 adds shelter + a 50 hp engine and is the stronger compromise.)', 'A club/fast-cruising fleet — many Atlantic crossings/ARC deliveries; no single famous high-latitude expedition (it''s a trade-wind/performance boat).', '{"protection":2,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":2,"storage":3.5,"tankage":1.5,"highlat":2,"tropical":5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Ultralight & fast', 'Lifting keel', 'Exposed cockpit', 'Trade-wind weapon']::text[], array['Surfs at 15–24 kn downwind — "Volvo Ocean Race feeling on a cruiser."', 'Foam-cored and unsinkable (ISO Cat A) despite the racing-light displacement.', 'European Yacht of the Year 2012 (Performance Cruiser).']::text[], array['New base ~€241,000 ex-VAT (2020)', 'Used early hulls ~$150k–$220k', 'Late 2018–2022 boats ~$350k–$450k+']::text[], '[{"name":"Boat-Specs","url":"https://www.boat-specs.com/sailing/sailboats/pogo-structures/pogo-12-50-swing-keel"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/pogo-125/"},{"name":"No-Frills-Sailing owner review","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/dream-yachts-the-ultrafast-pogo-12-50/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing Pogo 12.50 — review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aWriPxJOoTI","note":"On-water review"},{"name":"Pogo 12.50 heavy-air sailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1IyZTsRIQo","note":"Breeze-on footage"},{"name":"Pogo 12.50 \"Raceberry\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ucd80SvAmSI","note":"Sailing"},{"name":"Pogo 12.50 transatlantic delivery","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qO_gGwqVL2w","note":"Ocean passage (OPEN SAIL)"}]'::jsonb, array['Exceptional, easy short-handed performance — planes effortlessly, very fast.', 'Lifting keel = 1.2 m shoal draft for gunkholing and drying out.', 'Excellent build quality — vacuum-infused, unsinkable, CE Cat A.', 'Strong factory after-sales support.', 'Simple systems = owner-maintainable.', 'Big interior volume and headroom for 40 ft.']::text[], array['Exposed open cockpit, no pilothouse/shelter — wrong for cold/wet high latitudes.', 'Tiny 60 L fuel tank — minimal motoring range (~150–250 nm).', 'Slammy, noisy, jerky motion to windward in a seaway.', 'Only 1 head, Spartan finish — modest liveaboard comfort.', 'No factory insulation/heating provision.', 'Performance degrades as you load cruising weight (it punishes payload).']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2012']::text[], '[{"who":"Interesting Sailboats","note":"\"One of the more innovative 40 ft fast cruisers… very quick, generally very easy to handle, huge stability\" (notes the wetted-surface/head-sea drawback).","url":"https://interestingsailboats.blogspot.com/2014/03/eric-pogo-1250-very-fast-cruiser.html"},{"who":"Owner (No-Frills-Sailing)","note":"\"You can absolutely go around the world… with your family\" — but Spartan and noisy (\"you are going to need earplugs at night\").","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/dream-yachts-the-ultrafast-pogo-12-50/"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2012', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (carbon mast)","keelRudder":"Lifting swing keel (lead bulb on a vinylester fin); fixed-fin option · twin spade rudders; tiller steering","complexity":"Low by design — minimalist, sail-focused; good for DIY owners. The swing-keel mechanism is the one specialised item.","maintain":"High for the simple systems; the swing keel needs periodic inspection/service and adds maintenance vs a fixed keel.","partsText":"Pogo Structures active and healthy (~55 boats/yr); the model was discontinued 2022 but the yard supports the range; standard components (Volvo, North Sails, common deck gear) ease parts.","problems":"Swing-keel cost/complexity/space; flat-bow slamming + high interior noise (no sound insulation); the standard 30 hp can feel marginal pushing the beamy hull into head seas — some owners upsize.","sentiment":"Strongly positive on performance, build quality and yard support; buyers self-select for the Spartan, loud, fast character. Owners cruise and even circumnavigate them.","communities":[{"name":"YBW — Pogo 12.50 thread","url":"https://forums.ybw.com/threads/pogo-12-50-super-quick-cruiser.602963/"},{"name":"SailNet — Pogo","url":"https://www.sailnet.com/threads/pogo-structures-30-10-50-and-12-50.216202/"},{"name":"Pogo Structures","url":"https://www.pogostructures.com/"}],"risks":["Exposed cockpit + tiny 60 L fuel + no heating/insulation provision — pushes against the high-latitude requirement","Light-displacement motion is slammy and noisy upwind in a seaway","Single head, Spartan finish — modest liveaboard comfort","Performance degrades as you load cruising weight"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":5,"parts":4,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('enksail49', 'Enksail Orion 49', 'Gebr. van Enkhuizen · Netherlands', 'Kees van de Stadt (Satellite)', '#246b74', '2017–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Pilothouse (inside helm)', '49''1" (15.05 m)', '46''6" (14.20 m)', '14''9" (4.50 m)', '4''11" (1.50 m up)', '11''6" (3.50 m down)', '17,000–19,000 kg / 37,500–41,900 lb', '6,200 kg', '~36%', '~107–120 m² up', 'n/a', 'Yanmar 4JH (75–80 hp)', 'Saildrive', '2–3 cabins / 1 head', 'Welded aluminium keel stub with an integrated hydraulic ballasted centreboard (variable draft) — no bolt-on keel · single rudder (triple-rudder on the explorer hull)', 'Raised aluminium deck-saloon/pilothouse with an inside helm/watch station (360° view) + a low secure aft cockpit', '700–850 L / 185–225 gal', '600–650 L / 159–172 gal', 15.05, 46.6, 14.76, 39683, 1.5, '~16.5', '~200', 750, 620, 75, 650000, 900000, 'tight', 2, 'The couple who want the Distant Shores boat — a bare-aluminium, heated-pilothouse, variable-draft go-anywhere yacht for Norway-to-Tahiti — and can find one used under $1M.', 'The headline feature — a full raised deck-saloon/pilothouse with 360° visibility, double-glazed alloy-framed windows and an inside helm/watch station; "during bad weather everyone can sit inside dry, warm and safe." The outside aft cockpit is kept low for security. Watch entirely from inside — ideal for high latitudes.', 'Cutter/sloop on an aluminium mast + a fixed bowsprit; a self-tacking high-aspect jib (easy short-handed), a removable inner forestay for a storm jib, and a Code/Furlström downwind suite.', 'Excellent short-handed — a self-tacking jib, all lines led aft, four electric Andersen winches, an electric windlass, bow + retractable stern thrusters, and an autopilot operable from the inside helm. Built around "a boat suitable for a small crew."', 'Strong — a defined engine room/technical area aft of the head and partly under the pilothouse for engine/wiring/filter access, doubling as workshop/storage; aluminium lets owners weld/fabricate fittings.', 'Victron-based, often lithium (the used hull has 2× 24V/200Ah lithium), a 3 kW inverter, solar + wind, Webasto central heating PLUS a Dickinson diesel cabin heater, a 60 L boiler — well set up for cold climates.', 'Generous — a technical area, deep bilges and a high-volume alloy hull; four watertight compartments. Wide side decks on the explorer hull.', 'Big tankage (700–850 L fuel / ~600 L water) sized for extended off-grid passages; ~800–1,200+ nm motoring.', '2–3 cabins / 1 head with a washing machine; a U-shaped galley open to the saloon + a big pilothouse social/watch space. Dog-friendly — Enksail will build a two-berth "hondekooi" (dog berth) under the pilothouse, and the transom scoop eases dog/shore-boat transfers. Two dogs are very workable; only 1 head is the liveaboard limit.', 'Excellent — the original brief was "a robust, fast family cruiser for cold regions": bare aluminium (ice/impact tolerant), an enclosed heated pilothouse with inside watch, twin diesel heating, watertight compartments, CE Cat A. Distant Shores built theirs "for the rigors of high-latitude sailing in ice and snow."', 'Very good — low-maintenance bare alloy (no antifoul-blister/teak-bake worries), a shaded/ventilated pilothouse, variable shallow draft (1.5 m) for reefs/atolls, big water + (often) a watermaker. Aluminium needs galvanic discipline in warm salt water.', '$650k–$900k (used)', '"Request price" — realistically >$1M new fully outfitted', 'Used ~$650k–$900k (scarce)', 'Fits used but tight near the top (~$650k–$900k); new is over $1M, and it''s a tiny, Europe-centric used market. (There''s no Orion 425/435/50 — the Orion range is just the 49 and 54.)', 'Distant Shores IV (Paul & Sheryl Shard''s Orion 49, launched 2024) — the flagship reference for this exact model and mission; the Shards have ~110,000 miles and nine ocean crossings.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4,"budget":3}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium pilothouse', 'Variable draft', 'The Distant Shores boat', 'Van de Stadt design']::text[], array['It''s literally the Distant Shores boat — bingeable build/sail episodes show your exact platform.', 'A hydraulic ballasted centreboard takes a 50-footer into 1.5 m of water (and can dry out).', 'Enksail will build in a two-berth dog berth ("hondekooi") under the pilothouse.']::text[], array['Orion 49 "Kofschip" (explorer, lithium refit) — sold VAT-paid via Atlantic Yachts', '2027 new-build Orion 49 — request price (boats.com)', 'Distant Shores IV (2024) — the Shards'' own Orion 49']::text[], '[{"name":"Satellite Yacht Design — Orion 49","url":"https://www.yacht-design.nl/designs/169-orion49-cruiser/"},{"name":"Enksail (official)","url":"https://enksail.gebrvanenkhuizen.nl/en/enksail-orion/"},{"name":"Atlantic Yachts listing","url":"https://www.atlanticyachts.nl/en/brokerage/242247/orion-49-pilothouse/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Distant Shores — Orion 49 interior tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v3tFFLbKkg0","note":"Full INTERIOR layout walkthrough"},{"name":"Launching Distant Shores IV","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z__NZi4pR00","note":"The Shards'' Orion 49 launch"},{"name":"Sea trials — Enksail Orion 49","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QFUcZ1xTNoY","note":"First sails"},{"name":"Boat tour: Enksail Orion 49","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_d_CcTbstwM","note":"Aluminium expedition walkthrough"}]'::jsonb, array['Enclosed 360° pilothouse with inside helm/watch — exceptional protection and the standout for cold/wet passages.', 'Aluminium hull: impact/grounding/ice tolerant, no osmosis, low cosmetic maintenance (bare finish).', 'Variable draft 1.5–3.5 m — ocean-capable deep, then shallow for anchorages/reefs/drying out.', 'Genuinely short-handed: self-tacking jib, all lines aft, electric winches, thrusters, inside autopilot helm.', 'Big tankage + CE Cat A — real long-range, all-latitude capability.', 'Semi-custom — layout, a dog berth and systems all tailorable; designed for a small crew.']::text[], array['New price almost certainly over $1M fully outfitted; used examples are scarce.', 'Very small builder, very few hulls — limited resale comps, brand recognition and global service footprint.', 'Aluminium requires diligent galvanic/electrolysis discipline, especially long-term in tropical salt water.', 'A single head on a 49-footer is modest for a long-term liveaboard couple + guests.', 'Bare aluminium topsides are an acquired aesthetic.', 'Systems (lithium, thrusters, hydraulic centreboard, central heating) add complexity to maintain remotely.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Distant Shores (Paul & Sheryl Shard)","note":"Experienced bluewater cruisers who chose the Orion 49 after three prior boats — built \"for the rigors of high-latitude sailing in ice and snow.\"","url":"https://distantshores.ca/"},{"who":"Satellite Yacht Design (Kees van de Stadt)","note":"From the respected Dutch Van de Stadt design lineage; the Orion is Enksail''s sportier, more performance-oriented line.","url":"https://www.yacht-design.nl/designs/169-orion49-cruiser/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (lines led aft)","keelRudder":"Welded aluminium keel stub with an integrated hydraulic ballasted centreboard (variable draft) — no bolt-on keel · single rudder (triple-rudder on the explorer hull)","complexity":"Moderate–high — lithium, twin thrusters, a hydraulic centreboard, central + diesel heating (and a watermaker on some). Well-equipped, not simple.","maintain":"Aluminium is owner-weldable/repairable and the bare hull is easy to touch up; offset by systems complexity. A defined engine room aids access.","partsText":"Active, established yard (Gebr. van Enkhuizen, Makkum, NL; also a Yanmar engines arm). Core hardware is mainstream (Yanmar, Victron, Andersen, Raymarine, Webasto) so parts are global; boat-specific aluminium/structural parts come from one small Dutch yard — a risk far from Europe.","problems":"None documented publicly (very few hulls, very new). General aluminium caution: stray-current/galvanic corrosion if bonding/anodes are neglected.","sentiment":"Positive but a tiny sample — Distant Shores'' extensive video record is overwhelmingly favourable on the pilothouse, build quality and all-latitude capability.","communities":[{"name":"Enksail (official)","url":"https://enksail.gebrvanenkhuizen.nl/en/"},{"name":"Distant Shores TV","url":"https://distantshores.ca/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum (metal boats)","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/"}],"risks":["Niche brand, minuscule production — few comps, Europe-centric support, scarce used market","New pricing opaque and likely >$1M","Aluminium galvanic/electrolysis discipline required","Single head + systems complexity for remote regions"],"scores":{"maintain":3.5,"simplicity":2.5,"parts":3,"community":2.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('passport545', 'Passport Vista 545', 'Passport Yachts · USA/China', 'Bill Dixon', '#2d5a6e', '2012–present', 'GRP (solid hull)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + glass windshield', '54''6" (16.61 m)', '45''6" (13.86 m)', '15''2" (4.62 m)', '5''7" (1.70 m shoal)', '6''6" (1.98 m deep)', '17,463 kg / 38,500 lb', '6,668 kg lead (encapsulated)', '~38%', '~1,045 ft² (100% FT)', '~63''6" (ICW rig)', 'Yanmar 110 hp', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Encapsulated/integral lead keel (no keel bolts) · partial-skeg balanced rudder · forward collision bulkhead', 'Center cockpit with a fixed laminated-glass stainless windshield (standard)', '946 L / 250 gal', '946 L / 250 gal', 16.61, 45.47, 15.15, 38500, 1.7, '~19.5', '~183', 946, 946, 110, 690000, 850000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a two-handable, heirloom-quality semi-custom 54-footer with a hard glass windshield, a real workshop and superb engine access — and buy used to stay under budget.', 'Center cockpit with a fixed laminated-glass stainless windshield as standard (it anchors the dodger/awning) — robust forward protection well beyond a soft dodger, with excellent visibility. An optional hard dodger gives full hardtop shelter. A standout for cold, wet high-latitude watches.', 'Masthead sloop, double-headed Solent rig (genoa/reacher + self-tacking inner jib, both on Furlex furlers); Selden in-mast furling main; tall or ICW rig.', 'Engineered as "a bluewater cruiser for a couple" — in-mast furling main + twin furling headsails mean no going forward; the self-tacking inner jib makes tacking a turn of the wheel. Harken (often electric) winches. A genuinely two-handable 54-footer.', 'A signature strength — excellent all-sides engine access in a foam-insulated engine room with labelled wiring/plumbing; Passport will build in a dedicated workshop/utility room with a workbench.', 'Big standard house bank (configurable ~700–1,355 Ah), Balmar alternators, a 3 kW inverter/charger, keel-cooled fridge/freezer, optional genset; cleanly installed, labelled, serviceable mainstream gear.', '"Lockers abound" — deep bilge, locking floorboards, a big lazarette, a dedicated LPG locker and large sail/gear lockers, plus the customizable utility/workshop space; full 7''2" headroom.', 'Big 250/250 gal tankage with a 110 hp Yanmar; a genuine ocean-passage boat with a watermaker fitted.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads (each en-suite with shower), a walk-through galley, a nav station + washer/dryer. The walk-through center-cockpit layout, low companionway steps and fully-custom interior (pet provisions buildable) + sugar-scoop stern make it genuinely dog-friendly.', 'Good — a fixed glass windshield + optional hard dodger for cold/wet protection, a solid uncored hull below the WL, an encapsulated keel (no bolts), a forward collision bulkhead, a skeg-protected rudder and a heavy build (comfort 33, capsize 1.80). GRP (not alloy) and a tall furling rig are the caveats vs a dedicated expedition boat.', 'Excellent — a shoal-draft option (5''7"), big tankage, keel-cooled fridge/freezer, A/C, a sugar-scoop stern and a big reaching-sail wardrobe; a bright, airy interior.', '$690k–$850k (used)', 'New base ~$975k (2012); current build $1M+', 'Used ~$690k–$850k', 'Fits — a clean used 545 lands comfortably under $1M with room to outfit. A brand-new optioned build runs $1M+.', 'A privately-cruised couple''s boat with a strong build/resale reputation; a limited published long-voyage record.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Fixed glass windshield', 'Semi-custom quality', 'Great engine access', 'CW Boat of the Year 2016']::text[], array['Cruising World 2016 overall Boat of the Year — "art you can leave out in the rain."', '~32,000 man-hours per hull — about 5× a typical production boat.', 'Fully semi-custom: owners have had pet-litter nooks and left-handed cabinets built in.']::text[], array['2018 "Solitude" CC, Annapolis — $690,000 (David Walters)', '2012 CC, Warwick RI — $845,000', '2014 CC, Fort Lauderdale — ~$849,999']::text[], '[{"name":"Cruising World — BOTY 2016","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/boat-year-2016-winner-passport-545/"},{"name":"SAIL review","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/passport-vista-545-cc/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/vista-545-passport/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Passport 545 — full walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DgGDKbGbelA","note":"\"Ocean Eyes\" 545 CC tour"},{"name":"545 — Annapolis walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WFWW1_XR9uQ","note":"Boat-show walkaround"},{"name":"Passport 545 — review & tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F5Ka2ovs-6s","note":"Full tour"},{"name":"Passport 545 vs Hylas 56","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3BJUK8W0WhA","note":"Head-to-head"}]'::jsonb, array['Fixed glass windshield + dodger = exceptional cockpit protection for cold, wet high-latitude watches.', 'Engineered for short-handed couple sailing (in-mast furling main, twin furling headsails, self-tacking inner jib).', 'Outstanding all-sides engine access + a buildable workshop/utility room.', 'Encapsulated keel (no bolts), forward collision bulkhead, solid uncored hull below the WL.', 'Fully semi-custom — workshop, third cabin, pet provisions, all buildable to spec.', 'Strong tankage, big house bank, a shoal-draft option, and a reputation for very high resale.']::text[], array['Expensive — used entry ~$690k (near the top of budget); new is $1M+.', 'In-mast furling main trades sail shape/performance for ease and adds a failure mode.', 'GRP hull (not alloy) — capable but not a dedicated ice/grounding expedition platform.', 'A big, muscular 54-footer — heavy loads; rewards a knowledgeable skipper.', 'Boutique single-source builder + a small owner community for peer support.', 'Verify rig service and gelcoat on 10+ year boats.']::text[], array['Cruising World Boat of the Year 2016', 'SAIL Best Boats 2012']::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World (Alvah Simon)","note":"\"Every part, every piece, every detail of the Passport is special. It''s art you can leave out in the rain.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/boat-year-2016-winner-passport-545/"},{"who":"boats.com (Zuzana Prochazka)","note":"\"Muscular elegance\" — ~32,000 man-hours per boat; comparables named are the Oyster 54 and Hylas 56.","url":"https://www.boats.com/reviews/passport-vista-545-gold-and-butter/"}]'::jsonb, 'CW BOTY 2016', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (Seldén in-mast)","keelRudder":"Encapsulated/integral lead keel — no keel bolts · partial-skeg balanced rudder · forward collision bulkhead","complexity":"Moderate–High — a big inverter/charger bank, A/C, keel-cooled refrigeration and electric heads; installed cleanly with labelled wiring and good access.","maintain":"Above average for the size — removable joinery, labelled systems, all-sides engine access and mainstream serviceable gear make DIY feasible.","partsText":"Active boutique builder (Passport Yachts, est. 1979); semi-custom, single-source for hull/custom parts, but high-quality mainstream components (Yanmar, Seldén, Harken, Balmar, Furlex) are globally serviceable. Moderate parts risk.","problems":"No systemic defects surfaced. Minor setup niggles on a test boat (steering cables, slightly springy helm, engine noise ~77 dBA); verify rig service + gelcoat on 10+ yr boats.","sentiment":"Strongly positive in press — a reputation for build quality and unusually high resale. Direct owner-forum chatter is thin (niche, boutique boat).","communities":[{"name":"Passport Yachts","url":"https://passportyachts.com/"},{"name":"SailboatData forum","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/forums/topic-tag/vista-545-passport/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/"}],"risks":["Boutique single-source builder; small owner community for peer support","In-mast furling reliance (jam/maintenance)","High purchase/refit cost — used entry ~$690k","GRP hull (not alloy) for the hardest high-latitude grounding/ice work"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3,"parts":3.5,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('tayana58', 'Tayana 58 Deck Salon', 'Ta Yang · Taiwan', 'Pieter Beeldsnijder', '#3a5566', '~2000–present', 'GRP (solid hull)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Deck saloon (inside steering)', '58''0" (17.68 m)', '45''11" (14.0 m)', '16''1" (4.91 m)', '6''6" (1.98 m shoal)', '7''2" (2.18 m deep)', '21,953 kg / 48,400 lb', '7,983 kg cast iron', '~36%', '1,399 ft² (100% FT)', '~76''', 'Yanmar 160 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Bolted fin keel (deep/shoal/CB options) · semi-skeg-hung rudder', 'Center cockpit + raised deck saloon; often a fully enclosed cockpit with an inside steering station', '568 L / 150 gal', '946 L / 250 gal', 17.68, 45.9, 16.1, 48400, 1.98, '~16.9', '~223', 568, 946, 160, 300000, 500000, 'fit', 1, 'The returning skipper + novice crew who want a heavy, sea-kindly liveaboard with a serious onboard workshop and big self-sufficiency — Patagonia to Polynesia in comfort, well under budget.', 'Center cockpit, deep and well-protected; the raised deck-saloon coachroof + a common hard dodger give excellent shelter, and many boats add a fully enclosed cockpit with an INSIDE steering station in the heated saloon — a major plus for cold Patagonian/Chilean watches.', 'Cutter (ketch optional) — a Yankee + staysail split foretriangle for easily-managed, balanced sail in a blow; many add an in-boom or in-mast furling main + electric winches.', 'Rigged for a cruising couple — a generous Lewmar winch package (often electric), a Leisure Furl boom or in-mast main, an electric windlass and a bow thruster; the heavy hull is steady and forgiving, which suits a novice second crew.', 'A standout — a full STAND-UP engine room WITH a workbench (rare at this size), sound-insulated with 360° access around the engine. One of the strongest workshop/engine-access setups in the class.', 'Newmar AC/DC panels, 110/240V shore power, internal bonding; cruising boats add solar, big lithium/AGM banks, watermakers, diesel heating and 3-zone A/C. Conventional, serviceable, non-proprietary.', 'Very large — a deep lazarette, the big engine-room/workshop volume, coaming/chain/propane lockers and extensive teak-lined interior stowage. Excellent for two-handed liveaboard + dog gear + spares.', 'Modest 150 gal fuel but a heavy, efficient displacement hull; big 250 gal water + watermaker give long autonomy.', 'Lavish teak joinery; the raised saloon floods light and gives 360° sightlines (great for watching a novice crew or dogs). The cutaway transom + swim platform + boarding ladder ease dog boarding; wide side decks with high bulwarks give safe footing. The 7''2" deep draft limits the shallowest beach landings.', 'Very well suited — heavy displacement, a solid-glass hull, a skeg-protected rudder and (where fitted) an enclosed inside steering station make a warm, dry, sea-kindly platform; comfort ratio ~38. Add diesel heat and the saloon is a warm watch room.', 'Capable — deck-saloon glass + good ventilation (8 dorades) help; big saloon windows can gain heat (A/C is common). Big water tankage + watermaker suit remote atolls; a shoal option for thin water.', '$300k–$500k (used)', 'Semi-custom, build-to-order (sporadic)', 'Used ~$300k–$500k', 'Fits with huge margin — even a top-spec, fully-outfitted 58DS lands around half the budget, leaving room for refit and high-latitude prep.', '"Moonshadow" cruised the world (70,000+ nm); the family appears in Baja Ha-Ha, ARC and Salty Dawg rally records.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4,"dogs":4,"workshop":5,"storage":5,"tankage":4,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Stand-up engine room + workbench', 'Inside steering option', 'Heavy bluewater', 'Great value']::text[], array['The raised saloon is a panoramic "sun room at sea."', 'A cutaway transom + swim platform makes a great dog-and-dinghy launchpad.', '"Moonshadow" has logged 70,000+ nm around the world.']::text[], array['2006 "Majestic" (San Diego) — ~$459k–$494k (enclosed cockpit, inside helm)', '2003 Tayana 58 — Florida (Dave Townley)', '"Moonshadow" — Contest Brokerage (70,000+ nm world-cruised)']::text[], '[{"name":"Tayana T58 spec (PDF)","url":"http://tayana.co.uk/downloads/T58_SPEC.pdf"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/tayana-58ds/"},{"name":"Keel Index — Tayana 58","url":"https://keelindex.com/boat/tayana-58"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Tayana 58 Deck Saloon — cruising","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hb58tz6bdt8","note":"On-water/overview"},{"name":"Touring a Tayana 58DS (2025)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NQa0U9nqlXg","note":"Owner tour"},{"name":"Tayana 58 — walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pTtEEvL_aow","note":"Interior/exterior"},{"name":"Tayana 54 \"Seeker\" (sister) tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n4oI7lxmZnw","note":"Close sister walkthrough"}]'::jsonb, array['A full stand-up engine room WITH a workbench — best-in-class workshop/engine access.', 'Big storage + 250 gal water for self-sufficient long-leg cruising far from services.', 'Rigged for short-handed couple sailing (cutter + electric winches/thruster/windlass).', 'Protected center cockpit + raised saloon (often an enclosed inside helm) — excellent high-latitude comfort.', 'Heavy, sea-kindly motion (comfort ratio ~38) and a proven Ta Yang solid-glass build.', 'Strong value — turnkey examples land around half the budget.']::text[], array['Teak decks (common) are a long-term core-leak/maintenance liability — survey carefully.', 'Tayana-family chainplate crevice corrosion is a known issue to inspect/replace.', 'Skeg-rudder bushings wear under load over time.', 'Only 150 gal fuel — motoring range is moderate (mitigated by the efficient hull + watermaker).', 'Low production = a thin market, fewer comps, longer waits for the right boat.', 'Heavy teak-intensive interior + big saloon glass mean upkeep and tropical heat-gain.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Tayana Owners Group (TOG)","note":"An active owners'' network rates Ta Yang''s solid-glass construction among the best in the class; the 58 is praised as a heavy, sea-kindly liveaboard.","url":"https://www.tognews.com/"},{"who":"Brokerage consensus","note":"Described as \"completely rigged for short-handed sailing by a cruising couple\" while being \"big, heavy, fast and powerful\" (seller-side).","url":"https://keelindex.com/boat/tayana-58"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Bolted fin keel (deep/shoal/CB options) · semi-skeg-hung rudder · bronze rudder shoe","complexity":"Moderate — core systems conventional and serviceable; complexity rises with owner add-ons (genset, A/C, watermaker, lithium). Nothing proprietary that locks you in.","maintain":"High for a 58-footer — a stand-up engine room/workshop and all-around engine access are deliberate advantages; mainstream serviceable gear.","partsText":"Ta Yang still operates (semi-custom on request); mainstream systems (Yanmar, Lewmar, Maxwell, Vetus, Newmar) are globally available; yard-specific custom parts are slower. Moderate parts risk.","problems":"Teak-over-core decks — water intrusion/core rot if fastenings leak (the key survey item). Tayana-family chainplate crevice corrosion — inspect/budget replacement. Skeg-rudder bushing wear. Bonding/tankage on older hulls.","sentiment":"Strongly positive on build quality and seaworthiness (Ta Yang construction widely regarded as among the best); owners value the engine room and liveaboard comfort. Caveats centre on teak-deck and chainplate upkeep.","communities":[{"name":"Tayana Owners Group (TOG)","url":"https://www.tognews.com/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Tayana","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f129/tayana-owners-group-72058.html"},{"name":"TOG list archive","url":"https://www.ftp.tognews.com/"}],"risks":["Survey teak decks for core moisture (the #1 item)","Verify chainplate condition (Tayana-family crevice corrosion)","Check skeg rudder-bearing condition","Thin resale market; 7''2\" deep draft limits gunkholing"],"scores":{"maintain":5,"simplicity":4,"parts":3,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('farr56', 'Farr 56 Pilot House', 'BSI Marine · Sweden', 'Farr Yacht Design', '#34607a', '2000–c.2008', 'GRP (cored)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Pilothouse (inside helm)', '57''9" (17.60 m)', '50''2" (15.30 m)', '16''7" (5.06 m)', '7''5" (2.26 m wing)', '8''2" (2.50 m deep)', '20,500 kg / 45,195 lb', '~6,600 kg lead', '~33%', '146 m² / 1,572 ft²', '25.4 m / 83''', 'Yanmar 160 hp', 'Shaft (Aquadrive)', '3 cabins / 3 heads', 'Fin with lead wing keel (shoal option) · keel-stepped mast · spade rudder', 'Genuine pilothouse with an internal helm/nav station + factory structural doghouse over the cockpit', '1,200 L / 317 gal', '800 L / 211 gal', 17.6, 50.2, 16.6, 45195, 2.26, '~19.7', '~159', 1200, 800, 160, 400000, 650000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a fast Bruce Farr pilothouse with a warm inside helm for Patagonia and push-button hydraulics — a lot of capable, protected boat well under $1M used.', 'A genuine pilothouse with an internal helm + nav station (engine & autopilot control inside) and 360° visibility; most bluewater boats add the factory structural doghouse over the cockpit plus a bimini. Stand watch warm and dry — ideal for high latitudes.', 'Sloop or cutter, a 3-spreader swept rig; typically an in-mast furling main + hydraulic furling genoa + staysail/Code 0; a full hydraulic winch package — close to push-button.', 'Its core design brief — all rig controls reachable from the pilothouse, hydraulic furling + hydraulic winches make a 57-footer feel like a 40, with redundant autopilots common. Realistic for two where one is a beginner.', '"Great machinery access" is a signature of the range, with a dedicated forepeak workshop plus deck-accessed watertight fore/aft lockers (and a collision-bulkhead bonus).', 'High-end and systems-heavy: generator, watermaker, Mastervolt charger/inverter + isolation transformer, a ~690–800 Ah 24V bank, Eberspächer hydronic heating, reverse-cycle A/C, solar/wind and full electronics.', 'Cavernous deck storage; a large lazarette (bigger than the 50 PH), deep deck lockers and the forepeak workshop/sail stowage.', 'Big ~317 gal fuel for a strong motoring range; effectively unlimited under sail with the watermaker.', 'A light oak/leather deck saloon, a full galley + washer/dryer, en-suite owner''s + VIP cabins (3 cabins/3 heads). Dog-friendly — broad protected side decks, a flat saloon sole, a walk-through layout and a swim platform; the heated enclosed pilothouse shelters dogs in the cold.', 'Strong on comfort/protection — a heated enclosed pilothouse with inside helm = warm, dry watchkeeping; CE Cat A; a cutter option; wing-keel shoal draft helps in poorly-charted channels. The GRP hull is the main caveat vs an aluminium expedition boat for ice/grounding.', 'Good — big tankage, a watermaker, a fast light-air hull and a shade-friendly cockpit; the pilothouse can run hot in sun (open the aft end / A/C / awnings).', '$400k–$650k (used)', 'Out of production (builder BSI Marine defunct)', 'Used ~$400k–$650k', 'Fits comfortably under $1M — even a turn-key refit example leaves margin. (No 54/55 pilothouse was ever built; the 56 PH is the couple''s sweet spot.)', '"Moonshadow Star" cruised to New Zealand under two experienced couples; the range has a liveaboard-circumnavigation reputation. (A widely-repeated Robin Knox-Johnston link is unverified broker copy.)', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":5,"highlat":4,"tropical":3.5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Pilothouse + inside helm', 'Bruce Farr performance', 'Big tankage', 'Orphan builder']::text[], array['A genuine Bruce Farr design — it sails like a performance boat, not a barge.', 'Push-button hydraulic sail handling makes a 57-footer feel like a 40.', 'No Farr 54 or 55 pilothouse was ever built — the range is the 50, 56, 60 and 63.']::text[], array['2002 "Moonshadow Star" — turn-key (Grabau International)', '2004 Farr 56 PH, Med — UK VAT paid (De Valk; comps €449k–€585k)', 'European market aggregate ~$386k–$543k']::text[], '[{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/farr-56-pilot-house/"},{"name":"Farr Yacht Design #425","url":"http://www.farrdesign.com/425.htm"},{"name":"De Valk listing","url":"https://www.devalk.nl/en/yachtbrokerage/806637/FARR-56-PILOT-HOUSE.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"FULL TOUR: Farr 56 bluewater sailboat","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pm-KQ_A7G2U","note":"Detailed walkthrough"},{"name":"\"Banana Wind\" — 56 Farr Pilothouse","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1qlZPx9idyU","note":"Owner boat"},{"name":"Farr 60 Pilothouse (sister)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kbK_e7mg4ts","note":"Berthon tour of the larger sister"},{"name":"Farr 50 \"Solstice\" (predecessor)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nec5rVozGaE","note":"Sailing & walkthrough"}]'::jsonb, array['A genuine pilothouse with an inside helm — superb warm, dry watchkeeping for Patagonia.', 'Designed for the short-handed cruising couple; hydraulic furling + winches are near push-button.', 'Excellent machinery access + a forepeak workshop (the skipper''s priorities).', 'Big fuel/water tankage and cavernous storage.', 'A genuinely fast Bruce Farr hull — 200 nm days; sails like a performance boat.', 'Sits well under $1M used with room for a refit.']::text[], array['Orphan builder (BSI Marine defunct) + a tiny fleet — no class spares pool, slow resale, hard to value.', 'Systems-heavy (hydraulics everywhere) — complexity to maintain/repair far from support.', 'GRP hull (not alloy) for the hardest high-latitude grounding/ice work.', 'Pilothouse can overheat in the tropics without A/C/awnings.', 'Teak-deck age/leaks on early hulls; verify standing-rigging (rod) replacement dates.', '8.2 ft deep draft (7.4 ft wing option) limits gunkholing.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"boats.com","note":"\"Sells for well below a million dollars but looks and sails better than others costing far more\"; the raised saloon avoids the \"greenhouse effect.\"","url":"https://www.boats.com/reviews/elegant-deck-saloon/"},{"who":"Farr Yacht Design","note":"\"The ideal yacht in the range for the long-term cruising couple… light and airy pilothouse, great machinery access and a palatial aft cabin.\"","url":"http://www.farrdesign.com/425.htm"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Fin with lead wing keel (shoal option) · spade rudder · CE Cat A","complexity":"High — hydraulic winches/furling/vang/backstay, a bow thruster, plus generator/watermaker/heating; a systems-dense boat.","maintain":"Moderate — mechanically conventional and well-laid-out with great machinery access, but the dense hydraulics/systems stack rewards a hands-on, technically capable owner.","partsText":"ORPHAN BUILDER — BSI Marine / Boat Sales International is defunct (no factory parts/support). Offsetting: the engine (Yanmar), hydraulics (Andersen/Lewmar/Reckmann) and electronics (Raymarine/Mastervolt) are mainstream and globally serviceable.","problems":"Teak-deck age/leaks on early hulls; hydraulic seal/pump servicing; in-mast furling jams if neglected; verify standing-rigging (rod) replacement dates. A thorough survey + rig inspection are essential.","sentiment":"Owners and brokers consistently praise the sailing performance, the warm/dry pilothouse and short-handed ease — a \"turn-key blue-water couple''s boat.\"","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — pilothouse","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/pilothouse-boats-again-141581.html"},{"name":"SailboatData — Farr 56","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/farr-56-pilot-house/"},{"name":"Sailing Anarchy — cruising","url":"https://forums.sailinganarchy.com/forums/cruising-anarchy.22/"}],"risks":["Defunct builder + tiny fleet — no class spares pool, slow resale, hard to value","Systems-heavy (hydraulics everywhere) — complexity to maintain far from support","GRP hull (not alloy) for the hardest high-latitude grounding/ice work","Pilothouse can overheat in the tropics without A/C/awnings"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":2,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('amel54', 'Amel 54', 'Chantiers Amel · France', 'Amel (in-house)', '#27506e', '2005–2011', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + enclosed', '56''4" (17.20 m)', '50''4" (15.35 m)', '15''9" (4.80 m)', '6''11" (2.10 m fixed)', '6''11" (2.10 m fixed)', '17,500 kg / 38,580 lb', '5,100 kg', '~29%', '139.9 m² / 1,506 ft²', 'n/a (ketch)', 'Volvo 110 hp', 'C-Drive (geared leg)', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Fixed fin keel · full-skeg-hung rudder · 4 watertight bulkheads', 'Fully enclosed, protected center cockpit (hard dodger + bimini)', '900 L / 238 gal', '900 L / 238 gal', 17.2, 50.4, 15.75, 38580, 2.1, '~21', '~135', 900, 900, 110, 350000, 650000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want Amel''s fully-protected, push-button ketch — sail-anywhere safety for an inexperienced crew — at roughly half the price of a new Amel 50.', 'Amel''s hallmark fully-enclosed, protected center cockpit with hard dodger/windscreen, bimini and high bulwarks — sail it in foul weather without leaving the sheltered helm. A top pick for a timid or inexperienced second crew.', 'Staysail ketch — electric in-mast furling main AND mizzen, electric furling genoa + staysail (Bamar); twin downwind poles for hands-off trade-wind running.', 'Built expressly for a couple: electric furling on every sail, electric winches, cockpit-controlled retractable bow thruster, hydraulic-lift berths. The Amel maxim: "if you can lift 50 lb you can do everything yourself." Everything leads to the protected cockpit.', 'A standout — a fully separate, walk-in, acoustically-isolated engine room that doubles as a real workshop/utility space. Best-in-class access.', 'Factory-integrated 24V system, Onan genset, watermaker, reversible A/C, Webasto heating — coherent but proprietary (C-Drive, Amel furlers, hydraulic passerelle).', 'Voluminous — hydraulic-lift berths over cavernous stowage, big insulated freezers, a large mixed-use bow locker (also houses systems); pack thoughtfully to keep it accessible.', '~1,000–1,400 nm motoring (≈7+ kt at low rpm); 238 gal fuel + watermaker = genuine long-range self-sufficiency.', '3 cabins / 2 heads, big aft owner''s suite, two stall showers, washer/dryer, real galley + nav station. High bulwarks/rails make side decks dog-secure and the enclosed cockpit shelters dogs; the hydraulic passerelle is finicky, so plan a dog-boarding ramp.', 'Strong on protection/structure — enclosed heated cockpit, Webasto heat, 4 watertight bulkheads, skeg-hung rudder. But it''s a GRP, 6''11" fixed-keel tropical-bias cruiser pressed into high latitudes, not a dedicated expedition boat.', 'Its native habitat — shaded enclosed cockpit, A/C, twin downwind poles, watermaker, big freezers, a conservative easily-reefed ketch rig.', '$350k–$600k (used)', 'Out of production (2005–2011)', 'Used ~$350k–$600k; good examples ~$500k–$600k', 'Fits comfortably — even a top example leaves margin for a C-Drive service and high-latitude prep. The affordable route into Amel''s enclosed-cockpit philosophy.', 'Amel ketches are circumnavigation icons; the 54 was a Cruising World 2020 BOTY runner-up (45–55 ft) and a staple globe-girdling couple''s boat.', '{"protection":5,"handling":5,"dogs":3,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":3,"tropical":5,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['Enclosed center cockpit', 'Push-button ketch', 'Walk-in engine room', 'Affordable Amel']::text[], array['Twin downwind poles set a butterfly twin-headsail rig for hands-off trade-wind running.', 'Berths lift on hydraulic rams to reveal cavernous stowage.', 'Widely called "the best world-cruising boat Amel ever built" — the Super Maramu''s refined successor.']::text[], array['2009 Amel 54, France — €440,000 inc. VAT (~$475k, Sizun & Charpentier)', '2008 Amel 54, Port-Saint-Louis — ~$475k', '2009 Amel 54, Athens — via Denison']::text[], '[{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/amel-54/"},{"name":"fetchinketch — 54 vs Super Maramu","url":"https://fetchinketch.net/2020/05/17/compare-and-contrast-the-amel-54-vs-the-super-maramu/"},{"name":"Sailboat-Cruising — Amel 54","url":"https://www.sailboat-cruising.com/Amel-54.html"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing Aquarius — Amel 54 tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oqYSy8_KjaY","note":"Owner-style boat tour"},{"name":"Amel 54 interior walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8yuyPrrpIIs","note":"Detailed interior"},{"name":"Amel 54 listing video","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d-sozDtSnI8","note":"2009 boat (Sizun & Charpentier)"},{"name":"Amel (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCYAbSsQcVxNKUHZyBOtCx2Q","note":"Builder channel"}]'::jsonb, array['Fully enclosed, protected center cockpit — outstanding for an inexperienced/timid crew member and for sheltering dogs.', 'Engineered top-to-bottom for short-handed couple sailing (electric furling everything, electric winches, cockpit-controlled thruster).', 'Walk-in, isolated engine room that doubles as a real workshop — best-in-class engine access.', 'Big 238 gal fuel + 238 gal water + watermaker = genuine long-range self-sufficiency.', 'Sea-kindly hull, a staysail for heavy weather, full-skeg rudder and four watertight bulkheads.', 'Exceptional owner community + a dedicated Amel school for newcomers — ideal for a returning skipper and a beginner crew.']::text[], array['Proprietary, complex systems (C-Drive, Amel furlers, hydraulic passerelle) — not a simple boat to DIY blind.', 'The Volvo D3 engine has a mixed reliability reputation among owners.', 'Bamar genoa/staysail furlers were problematic from the factory — confirm the fix on any boat.', 'Hydraulic passerelle + flush deck hatches are known weak points (corrosion/leaks).', 'GRP hull + fixed 6''11" keel — less ideal than alloy for rock/ice high-latitude work.', 'Tight pre-owned supply; the best boats trade privately.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World","note":"\"The 54 logged an effortless 9 knots… because safety is Amel''s paramount concern, the boat has four watertight bulkheads.\"","url":"https://www.sailboat-cruising.com/Amel-54.html"},{"who":"Bill Kinney (Amel delivery skipper)","note":"People who know the line call the 54 \"the best world-cruising boat Amel ever built,\" with a hull smoother upwind than the Super Maramu.","url":"https://fetchinketch.net/2020/05/17/compare-and-contrast-the-amel-54-vs-the-super-maramu/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (ketch — main + mizzen)","keelRudder":"Fixed fin keel, encapsulated/bolted ballast · full-skeg-hung rudder · 4 watertight bulkheads","complexity":"High — proprietary, factory-integrated systems (C-Drive leg, Amel electric furlers, hydraulic passerelle, 24V electrics, genset, watermaker, A/C). Wonderful when working; not a simple DIY boat.","maintain":"Moderate — superb walk-in engine-room access, but the proprietary drivetrain/furlers mean a learning curve; the strong owner community + Amel School close the gap.","partsText":"Amel (La Rochelle), Beneteau-owned since 2017, still supports older models. Many systems proprietary (C-Drive, furlers, thruster) via Amel; sub-components are standard brands. Moderate parts risk.","problems":"Volvo D3 engine reputation; C-Drive needs correct alignment + seal/oil service (neglect = costly); Bamar furlers were problematic from the factory (check the fix); hydraulic passerelle corrosion; flush-hatch leaks.","sentiment":"Strongly positive overall — sea-kindly, superbly built, couple-friendly; called Amel''s best world cruiser. Criticism centres on the engine choice and a few detail changes vs the Super Maramu.","communities":[{"name":"Amel Owners Group (groups.io)","url":"https://amelyachtowners.groups.io/g/main"},{"name":"Amel Owners Yacht School","url":"https://www.amelschool.com/"},{"name":"Amel Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/amelyachtowners/"}],"risks":["Verify C-Drive service/alignment history and the Bamar furler fix on the specific boat","Proprietary systems — not a simple DIY boat (lean on the Amel community + school)","Hydraulic passerelle + flush hatches are known weak points","GRP fixed 6''11\" keel — less ideal than alloy for rock/ice high-latitude work"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('hylas54', 'Hylas 54', 'Hylas Yachts · Taiwan', 'German Frers', '#2f6576', '1999–2010', 'GRP (solid, Twaron-reinforced)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + dodger', '54''0" (16.48 m)', '46''0" (14.02 m)', '15''9" (4.80 m)', '7''2" (2.18 m std)', '7''2" (2.18 m; rare shoal CB option)', '21,400 kg / 47,200 lb', '~9,080 kg lead', '~42%', '132.9 m² / 1,431 ft²', '~19.5 m / 64''', 'Yanmar 125 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Fin keel with bulb (rare shoal centreboard option) · partial-skeg spade rudder · forward collision bulkhead', 'Deep, secure center cockpit; most owners add a hard dodger/bimini', '946 L / 250 gal', '946 L / 250 gal', 16.48, 46, 15.75, 47200, 2.18, '~17.4', '~221', 946, 946, 125, 350000, 650000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a luxurious, strongly-built, push-button center-cockpit world cruiser that crosses oceans in comfort — at roughly half the price of an Oyster or Swan.', 'Deep, secure center cockpit (a reviewer called it "comfortable, well-thought-out and secure") with primaries and sail controls within reach of the helm — unusually good for a 54-footer. Most owners add a hard dodger/bimini; there''s no fixed windscreen.', 'Masthead cutter — electric in-mast Seldén furling main + furling genoa + a permanently-rigged inner staysail (the go-to depowering sail). In-boom and slab-main boats also exist.', 'Strong short-handed: electric primary/halyard winches, furling main + jib + staysail make sail reduction push-button; bow thruster + shaft-aligned prop make docking benign. Owners log 200-mile days. In-mast furling can jam in 40+ kt — furl early.', 'Engine under the galley/cockpit well with adequate access (tighter once a genset is fitted). The port cabin can be factory-fitted as a dedicated workbench/workshop.', 'Well-engineered, redundant, neatly-labelled wiring; big house bank, dual alternators; most carry genset, watermaker, fridge+freezer and A/C. Mainstream serviceable brands.', 'Large aft lazarettes + a deep step-down forward sail locker (part of a watertight collision bulkhead); abundant finished lockers and a huge galley counter.', '>1,000 nm motoring at ~7–8 kt; ~550 gal combined under the sole, splittable between fuel and water.', '3 cabins / 2 heads, 7''+ headroom, a light-filled raised saloon, two private cabins, two stall showers, a vast galley; optional workshop/office cabin. High freeboard means a custom ramp helps for dogs; wide (slightly slick when wet) side decks.', 'Strong hull (Twaron-reinforced solid glass, heavy, low capsize number) + protected center cockpit favour cold work; add a hard dodger + heating. Caveats: GRP (not alloy) and a deep 7''+ fixed keel limit gunkholing (the rare centreboard version suits Patagonia better).', 'Its natural habitat — big tankage, fridge/freezer, watermaker-friendly, A/C-ready; a proven Caribbean rally veteran.', '$350k–$650k (used)', 'Out of production (replaced by the Hylas 56)', 'Used ~$350k–$650k', 'Fits comfortably — even a top, fully-outfitted RS sits well under $1M, leaving margin for a rigging/sails/electronics refit and high-latitude prep.', 'A World Cruising Club rally regular (ARC, Caribbean 1500); John Kretschmer reviewed it as "a complete package… a luxurious world cruiser."', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['German Frers design', 'Center cockpit', 'Big tankage', 'Great value']::text[], array['The raised-saloon (RS) version outsold the standard 3-to-1 — "people can''t resist all that light below."', 'Builder Queen Long also built the famous Peterson 44.', 'Delivery skipper/author John Kretschmer logged ~40,000 miles on Hylas boats, riding out three hurricanes aboard them.']::text[], array['~2001 standard — $389,900 (Waukegan, IL)', '~2006 — $525,000 (Fort Lauderdale)', '~2005-06 — $599,000 (Portsmouth, RI)']::text[], '[{"name":"Sailing Magazine (Kretschmer)","url":"https://sailingmagazine.net/article-466-hylas-54-rs.html"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/hylas-54/"},{"name":"SV Rover owner review","url":"https://svrover.com/2020/08/18/hylas-54-yacht-review/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Hylas 54 \"Lizzie\" — walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=unbgEstTwLk","note":"1999 boat tour & review"},{"name":"Hylas 54 walkthrough (2006)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2GNyQgfCKk","note":"$649,900 Charleston listing tour"},{"name":"Hylas 54 \"Acadia\" (hull #56)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8hnWeYESkyw","note":"One of the last built"},{"name":"SV Rover — Hylas 54 sailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9LhQeEO23cw","note":"Owner sailing footage"}]'::jsonb, array['Exceptional build (Twaron-reinforced solid hull, superb Queen Long joinery, through-bolted hardware).', 'Designed for short-handed ocean passages — controls at the helm, electric winches, furling main/jib + permanent staysail.', 'Huge, light, comfortable liveaboard interior with two private cabins, two stall showers and an optional workshop cabin.', 'Big combined tankage (~550 gal) and >1,000 nm motoring range.', 'Strong Frers sailing performance — sure-footed and fun reaching in a breeze.', 'Excellent value and deep owner support — far cheaper than equivalent European pedigree yachts.']::text[], array['Deep 7''+ standard draft limits high-latitude/thin-water gunkholing (the centreboard version is rare).', 'Engine access tightens significantly once a genset is installed.', 'In-mast furling main can jam in heavy air; it''s a small, low-roach sail (modest light-air drive).', 'The 125 hp Yanmar has heavy turbo lag and notable oil use when pushed.', 'Survey the rudder/skeg carefully (two 2005-rally boats lost rudder sections — grounding-related).', 'High freeboard — boarding two dogs wants a custom ramp/setup.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"John Kretschmer · Sailing Magazine","note":"\"A swift and capable passagemaker… spacious, comfortable, capable and fast — the boat delivers on its promise as a luxurious world cruiser.\"","url":"https://sailingmagazine.net/article-466-hylas-54-rs.html"},{"who":"SV Rover (owners)","note":"Long-term owners say it meets expectations for extended liveaboard and ocean passages and recommend the design.","url":"https://svrover.com/2020/08/18/hylas-54-yacht-review/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (Seldén)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead fin keel with bulb (rare shoal centreboard option) · partial-skeg spade rudder · forward collision bulkhead","complexity":"Moderate–High — a fully-loaded luxury cruiser (genset, A/C, watermaker, electric winches, in-mast furling, thruster) but all mainstream and serviceable.","maintain":"Good — neat labelled wiring, an accessible panel, finished cabinet interiors; a handy owner does most work. The genset-crowded engine space is the main friction.","partsText":"Builder Queen Long + Hylas brand still active (building the 56/57/60/63/70); the 54 shares DNA with the in-production 56, and most parts are standard brands. Low parts risk.","problems":"Two 2005-rally boats lost rudder sections (attributed to prior groundings — survey the rudder/skeg). Anchor-roller/stemhead not suited to rope rode (chafe). Yanmar 125 turbo lag + oil use. In-mast furling jams in heavy air.","sentiment":"Very positive — long-term owners say it meets expectations for extended liveaboard and ocean passages and recommend it; a strong, loyal owner base.","communities":[{"name":"Hylas Owners Association","url":"https://www.hylasyachts.org/"},{"name":"Hylas Yacht Club","url":"https://www.hylasyachts.club/"},{"name":"Hylas Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/71332985122/"}],"risks":["Survey the rudder/skeg carefully (2005-rally rudder failures, grounding-related)","Budget for standing-rigging replacement on 2000s boats","Prefer the rare shoal centreboard for Patagonia thin water","Plan engine access before adding a genset"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3,"parts":4,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('outbound52', 'Outbound 52', 'Outbound Yachts · USA/China', 'Tim Kernan', '#3f4d5c', '2008–present (now 521)', 'GRP (solid, no liner)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + hard dodger', '52''0" (15.85 m)', '47''10" (14.58 m)', '15''4" (4.67 m)', '6''6" (shoal)', '7''6" (deep)', '40,000 lb / 18,144 kg (42,000 lb on the 521)', '14,000 lb lead', '~35%', '1,312 ft²', '~72''', 'Yanmar 110 hp', 'Shaft (Aquadrive)', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Bolted-on external lead bulb keel · spade rudder (Jefa) · keel-stepped rig · watertight bulkheads fore & aft', 'Deep, narrow, seamanlike center cockpit with an integral hard dodger', '946 L / 250 gal', '852 L / 225 gal', 15.85, 47.83, 15.33, 40000, 1.98, '~18', '~163', 946, 852, 110, 650000, 997000, 'tight', 2, 'The performance-minded couple who want a fast, sea-kindly, owner-maintainable passagemaker with a real engine room and a private aft master — the bigger sibling to the Outbound 46.', 'A deliberately deep, narrow, seamanlike center cockpit (sole ~16" lower than typical) with an integral hard dodger (roof cutout so you don''t stoop), 16" seatbacks, foot braces and four clip-in padeyes. Secure offshore; no inside steering.', 'Cutter (or Solent option); in-mast furling main with full vertical battens, furling genoa + inner staysail; the current 521 ships North Sails, electric furlers and a hydraulic backstay.', 'Designed as a couple''s boat — waist-high self-tailing winches reach from the helm, electric main-furling winch standard, light Lewmar direct-drive steering (one-handed even when pressed). Testers: easily handled by a knowledgeable couple.', 'A standout — a dedicated stand-up engine room (insulated door, labelled manifolds, accessible filters) PLUS an adjacent midship workroom with a stainless-topped workbench and tool drawers. Excellent for a self-maintaining owner.', 'Large AGM (up to 900 Ah) or modern lithium (521), genset, watermaker and A/C commonly fitted; tankage low under the sole for a low CG. Mainstream serviceable gear (Yanmar, Seldén, Lewmar).', 'Voluminous — quarter lockers, two aft lazarettes, an under-foredeck gear locker, a divided chain locker, plus under-sole space freed by low-mounted tankage.', '~1,000+ nm motoring (≈8 kt on the 110 hp Yanmar); the light-moderate hull is also a strong light-air performer, extending range under sail.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads; a private aft master (island queen, lift-up berth), a forward guest, and a midship utility/workshop cabin. The deep cockpit + stepped sugar-scoop transom ease dog boarding from a dinghy; wide side decks + high bulwarks keep dogs aboard.', 'Strong hull (solid glass, watertight bulkheads, bonded structure, grounding-tolerant external lead keel), hard dodger, deep secure cockpit. Caveats: GRP (not alloy), a fixed deep fin (6''6" shoal min) limits Patagonian gunkholing, and there''s no standard insulation/heating (add it).', 'Excellent — fast passages dodge weather, big tankage + watermaker for remote atolls, a hard dodger for shade, good ventilation, and a genuinely fun light-air trade-wind hull.', '$650k–$997k (used)', 'New 521 well over $1.4M', 'Used ~$650k–$997k', 'Tight but fits — a good used 52 lands inside $1M, though the best late-model boats sit at the very top, leaving thin margin for cold-climate outfitting. New is over budget.', 'Outbound owners have completed circumnavigations; the 52/46 line has a high proportion of hulls mid- or post-major-ocean-cruise.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4,"workshop":5,"storage":5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":5,"budget":3}'::jsonb, array['Stand-up engine room + workbench', 'Fast & sea-kindly', 'Center cockpit', 'Owner-maintainable']::text[], array['Designer Tim Kernan apprenticed under Bob Perry and was praised as a student by Olin Stephens.', 'The cockpit sole sits ~16" lower than a typical center-cockpit boat — Kernan''s antidote to the "wedding-cake" look.', 'Founder Phil Lambert, an ex-tanker officer, lives in Xiamen to personally supervise every build.']::text[], array['2020 Outbound 52 — $997,000 (Newport, RI, Anchor Yachts)', 'Outbound 52 — ~$785,000 (Barrington, RI)', 'Earlier 2008–2016 hulls ~$650k–$785k']::text[], '[{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/outbound-52/"},{"name":"Cruising World review (2008)","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/outbound-52-bound-open-ocean/"},{"name":"SAIL review (2009)","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/outbound-52/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Outbound 52 — overview","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xApn_5UfAy0","note":"On-water/overview"},{"name":"Outbound 52 fly-by (2020)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cPe-NKHEn5A","note":"Sailing footage"},{"name":"Outbound Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@OutboundYachts/videos","note":"Builder channel"},{"name":"Outbound 46 full tour (sister)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1913iFwSXj8","note":"Build/layout reference"}]'::jsonb, array['Genuinely fast, sea-kindly hull that lets you outrun weather — a stated safety philosophy.', 'Outstanding stand-up engine room + dedicated workshop with a stainless workbench — rare at this size.', 'Deep, narrow, seamanlike center cockpit with an integral hard dodger — secure offshore, comfortable on the hook.', 'Robust no-liner solid-glass construction with watertight bulkheads and a grounding-tolerant external lead keel.', 'Easily handled two-handed (electric/self-tailing winches, in-mast furling, light direct-drive steering).', 'Mainstream serviceable gear + a stepped transom that eases dog boarding.']::text[], array['Best used boats push the very top of a $1M budget — thin margin for cold-climate outfitting.', 'China-built (excellent quality, but less resale ''story'' and you must verify each boat).', 'Fixed deep fin + spade rudder are less Patagonia-friendly than aluminium centreboarders.', 'Fiberglass hull lacks the ice/rock abrasion tolerance of alloy expedition boats.', 'In-mast furling main is a convenience/redundancy compromise.', 'Low-volume, semi-custom — used examples are scarce and configurations vary.']::text[], array['SAIL Best Boats 2009']::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World (Andrew Burton)","note":"\"The boat was doing what it was meant to do: get where it''s going quickly while giving its crew a comfortable ride.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/outbound-52-bound-open-ocean/"},{"who":"SAIL Magazine","note":"\"Built for serious offshore work and can be easily handled in those conditions by a knowledgeable couple.\"","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/outbound-52/"}]'::jsonb, 'SAIL Best 2009', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (Seldén, triple-spreader)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on external lead bulb keel · high-aspect spade rudder (Jefa) · watertight bulkheads fore & aft","complexity":"Moderate — conventional diesel + shaft, standard furling/electrical; no exotic lifting keel. Modern 521 options (lithium, joystick) add complexity if specified.","maintain":"High for a 52-footer — a stand-up engine room, labelled manifolds, accessible through-hulls/filters, fold-down panels, no-liner hull access, and an onboard workbench.","partsText":"Active builder (now under Collection Yachts, FL); mainstream marine gear (Yanmar, Seldén, Lewmar, North) is globally serviceable. The China yard (Hansheng) also builds Passport. Low–moderate parts risk; low-volume/semi-custom.","problems":"No systemic defect reputation. Verify the in-mast furling main; survey rig age/chainplates; boats are semi-custom so confirm spec; budget heating/insulation + heavier ground tackle for the Patagonia leg.","sentiment":"Strongly positive in reviews and testimonials; an active far-cruising owner base, though independent forums are thinner than European brands given the small fleet.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Outbound","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/outbound-46-a-208523.html"},{"name":"SailboatData forum","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/forums/topic-tag/outbound-52/"},{"name":"Outbound owner hub","url":"https://outboundyachts.com/get-outbound"}],"risks":["Best late-model boats sit at the very top of budget — thin margin for cold-climate kit","GRP fixed deep fin + spade rudder — less Patagonia-friendly than alloy centreboarders","Small, semi-custom fleet — configurations vary, used examples scarce","In-mast furling main is a convenience/redundancy compromise"],"scores":{"maintain":5,"simplicity":4,"parts":4,"community":2.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('garcia52', 'Garcia Exploration 52', 'Garcia Yachts · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau w/ Jimmy Cornell', '#1f6b5e', '2016–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + hardtop / deck saloon', '54''6" (16.65 m)', '47''11" (14.59 m)', '15''9" (4.80 m)', '4''2" (1.27 m up)', '9''10" (3.00 m down)', '19,500 kg / 42,990 lb (light)', '6,574 kg', '~34%', '121.8 m² / 1,311 ft²', '21.5 m / 70''6"', 'Volvo D3-110 (150 opt)', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads (+workshop)', 'Integral aluminium centreboard (no bolt-on keel) · twin skeg-protected rudders · ice-reinforced forefoot', 'Deep protected cockpit with a forward watch position under the hardtop + an interior deck-saloon helm', '1,000 L / 264 gal', '800 L / 211 gal', 16.65, 47.9, 15.75, 42990, 1.27, '~17.1', '~175', 1000, 800, 110, 1000000, 2000000, 'over', 3, 'The couple who want the most capable, comfort-equipped go-anywhere aluminium expedition yacht in this size — and have the budget to exceed $1M.', 'Best-in-class — a deep cockpit with a forward watch position under the overhanging hardtop (enclosable into a pilothouse) PLUS a fully sheltered interior deck-saloon steering/nav position. A test called it "the best cockpit position from which to stand a watch, no matter the weather."', 'Sloop (61 m² battened main + furling Solent) or optional cutter with self-tacking staysail; code-zero/gennaker fittings; a conservative rig keeps loads manageable.', 'Strong — all lines led aft to the protected cockpit, inboard primaries forward of the twin wheels (a safe working spot), a self-tacking staysail option, optional electric winches; bow thruster optional.', 'A dedicated workbench/workshop locker under the deck saloon (bench, storage, 220V/12V) PLUS an insulated engine room with two-sided access — directly answers the workshop priority.', '24V house system; options for a Fischer Panda genset, Watt&Sea hydrogenerator, wind/solar, Victron chargers, isolation transformer, 60–100 L/h watermaker; PSM battery monitor.', 'Exceptional — central under-floor tankage frees volume; two 400 L dry transom lockers, a big bow sail locker, generous lockers. The length gives "all the space and stowage you could wish for."', 'Big tankage (1,000 L fuel / 800 L water, both expandable); tanks are port/starboard ballast-pumpable. ~900–1,200 nm motoring (estimate).', 'Deck-saloon liveaboard with 270° views, a big galley and nav station; cork decks (grippy, dog-friendly, washable) + a low swim platform aid dog boarding; the workshop cabin gives space for two dogs.', 'Best-in-class — built to Jimmy Cornell''s Northwest-Passage brief: ice-reinforced forefoot, watertight bulkheads, welded above-WL seacocks, heavy insulation, watertight doors, optional heating. Proven Svalbard–Patagonia–Antarctica.', 'Very good — shoal 1.27 m board-up draft for reefs/lagoons, a 270° shaded saloon, coachroof shade, big watermaker/tankage and good ventilation.', '$1.0M–$2.0M (used)', 'New from ~€1.3M (~€1.5–1.8M outfitted)', 'Used ~$1.0M–$2.0M (median ~$1.75M)', 'Over budget — even the cheapest used hulls sit at/above $1M, and a properly outfitted example runs $1.5M+. Included as the aspirational aluminium benchmark; the Exploration 45 is the in-budget Garcia.', 'Concept lineage from Jimmy Cornell''s Exploration 45; ''Lifexplorer'' ran a ~10-year Svalbard-to-Antarctic program; sailing-friendliness demonstrated publicly by Pete Goss.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":5,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":1.5}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium expedition', 'Best protected cockpit', 'Workshop + deck saloon', 'Over budget']::text[], array['Fuel/water tanks pump port-to-starboard to act as trim/heel ballast.', 'The bow has a welded towing/ice-breaking eye so a tractor can drag her ashore.', 'Hull #1 ''Aquarius'' left the factory loaded with pallets of medical supplies for Senegal en route to a five-year world tour.']::text[], array['New from ~€1.3M (ex-options)', '2018/2019 used examples ~$1.35M–$1.56M', 'Used median asking ~$1.75M']::text[], '[{"name":"Yachting World test","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/garcia-exploration-52-jimmy-cornell"},{"name":"Garcia spec (PDF)","url":"https://www.garciayachts.com/en/sailsboats/exploration-52"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/exploration-52-garcia/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Garcia Exploration 52 — 360° tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8udVkbaJDtc","note":"Builder 360 tour"},{"name":"Exploration 52 — guided tour (ENG)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VrGSZNHR-as","note":"Narrated walkthrough"},{"name":"Exploration 52 \"Aysha\" walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yKQdmQ-RLgs","note":"Owner boat tour"},{"name":"Pete Goss — Exploration 52 sailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CZ93MsZd7Xk","note":"Sailing session"}]'::jsonb, array['The benchmark protected cockpit + interior deck-saloon helm — ideal for an inexperienced co-skipper in cold/wet/remote conditions.', 'Genuinely short-handed: all lines to the cockpit, a self-tacking staysail option, twin wheels with inboard primaries.', 'Standard workshop + engine room with two-sided access — exactly the maintainability priorities.', 'Huge tankage (1,000 L fuel / 800 L water, both expandable) and class-leading stowage.', 'Shoal 1.27 m board-up draft + dry-out ability — superb for Patagonian gunkholing AND tropical reefs.', 'Unmatched dual-climate engineering: ice-reinforced/insulated for the cold, shaded/shoal/ventilated for the tropics.']::text[], array['Price — over the $1M budget (used $1.0–2.0M); the single biggest disqualifier here.', 'Modest sail area (SA/D ~17.1) — sluggish in light air under white sails; needs a downwind sail.', 'Aluminium demands disciplined galvanic/corrosion management — a learning curve for the crew.', 'Complex, system-rich expedition boat (genset, watermaker, multiple charging sources) — more to maintain.', 'Deliberately short twin rudders can lose grip if over-pressed.', 'Deck-stepped mast + centreboard case add inspection items; the bare-alloy aesthetic is polarising.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (Toby Hodges)","note":"\"The sailing equivalent of a 4×4 off-roader… the ultimate go-anywhere yacht that also caters for the crew that has no wish to rough it.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/garcia-exploration-52-jimmy-cornell"},{"who":"Jimmy Cornell (concept originator)","note":"Champions aluminium centreboarders as the best choice for serious explorers — the Exploration line is his concept.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium centreboard, internal ballast (no bolt-on keel) · twin NACA rudders, each skeg-protected · ice-reinforced forefoot","complexity":"High — genset/hybrid-capable power, watermaker, multiple charging sources, 24V architecture; an expedition-grade systems boat.","maintain":"Moderate — excellent physical access (two-sided engine room, dedicated workshop, welded above-WL seacocks), but aluminium corrosion management + system depth require diligence.","partsText":"Active within the well-capitalised Grand Large Yachting group + the Grand Large Services refit network (aluminium specialists). Mainstream sourcing (Volvo, B&G, JEFA, Victron, Fischer Panda). Strong support.","problems":"No widespread defect pattern. Recurring themes: galvanic-corrosion control (anode discipline, electrical isolation) and routine centreboard-mechanism attention. Modest sail area = light-air sluggishness; short twin rudders can lose grip if over-pressed.","sentiment":"Very high among expedition owners; reviewers rate it a benchmark ''4×4 of the sea.'' Trade-off acknowledged: comfort/strength over speed.","communities":[{"name":"Allures–Garcia Owners forum","url":"https://alluresgarciaowners.discussion.community/"},{"name":"YBW — Garcia thread","url":"https://forums.ybw.com/threads/garcia-yachts.622900/"},{"name":"Garcia journeys hub","url":"https://www.garciayachts.com/en/journeys/somesjourneys/"}],"risks":["Price — over the $1M budget (the biggest disqualifier here)","Aluminium galvanic/corrosion discipline required","Complex, system-rich expedition boat — more to maintain","Light-air sluggishness; short twin rudders if over-pressed"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":5,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('boreal52', 'Boréal 52', 'Boréal Yachts · France', 'Jean-François Delvoye', '#234f6b', '2014–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + hard doghouse', '52''0" (15.86 m)', '45''3" (13.82 m)', '15''3" (4.65 m)', '3''9" (1.14 m up)', '10''3" (3.13 m down)', '16,500 kg / 36,376 lb (light); ~19,000 kg loaded', '4,800 kg lead', '~29%', '130 m² / 1,399 ft²', '~23 m / 75''', 'Volvo D2-75 (Nanni 85 opt)', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Lifting NACA centreboard in a flat "keel embryo" (dries out upright); integral internal lead ballast (no bolt-on keel) · single NACA rudder + two aft daggerboards', 'Permanent welded aluminium doghouse with wraparound glazing + watertight door — a heated all-weather sanctuary', '879 L / 232 gal (+378 opt)', '1,470 L / 388 gal', 15.86, 45.3, 15.26, 36376, 1.14, '~20.5', '~174', 879, 1470, 75, 750000, 1050000, 'tight', 2, 'The couple who want a go-anywhere, dry-out aluminium expedition cruiser with a heated pilothouse-style doghouse — the bigger sibling to the Boréal 47.2.', 'A defining feature — a permanent welded alloy doghouse with wraparound tinted glazing, a solid "bye-bye weather" door and handrails; the mainsheet leads to the doghouse top so the cockpit stays clear. Standing watch inside the heated, near-360° doghouse is a foul-weather sanctuary.', 'Cutter (masthead) — self-tacking/hanked staysail on a releasable inner forestay + a furling genoa, a fully-battened 3-reef main; optional taller "Dominique Wavre" rig.', 'Designed for short-handed: lines led aft, well-placed (optionally electric) winches, two aft daggerboards reduce autopilot load, and a central mast-base windlass doubles as the main-halyard winch. A 2015 test called her "a very easy boat to handle" and "surprisingly nimble" at ~18 t.', 'Engine and batteries centralised over the keel; access via the aft cabins/companionway (good, not a walk-in room). The owner-configurable forward zone is commonly speced as a workshop with big drawers and a bench.', '12V + 220V circuits, shore power, charger, a 5-battery bank, a 40 L water heater and a Refleks heater provision; later world-cruise boats add redundancy and dual 220V+110V electrics.', 'Strong — a large aft cargo locker, a dedicated forward sail locker, a separate compartment for two 13 kg gas bottles, an optional built-in liferaft cradle, plus the owner-configurable workshop/stowage area forward.', 'Huge tankage — up to ~1,257 L fuel and 1,470 L water; ~1,000–1,200+ nm under power (estimate).', 'Deck-saloon layout — see out from the seats, abundant handholds, short bracing distances; longitudinal galley, a forward double + two aft cabins. The sheltered watertight doghouse is a safe indoor space for two dogs and the dry-out keel eases beach access. Interior volume is a touch smaller than a typical 52 (security prioritised over space).', 'Excellent and intended — 50/80 mm hull/deck insulation, a heated enclosed doghouse, a Refleks provision, robust unpainted alloy that shrugs off ice/grounding, and a dry-out keel. Documented in Patagonia, Labrador, Svalbard and Antarctica (sisters).', 'Capable — large opening hatches, a cockpit shower, big water tankage and a 100 L fridge; but the dark-tinted doghouse + alloy topsides run hot in the tropics and need ventilation/awnings.', '$750k–$1.0M (used)', 'New base ~€725k (2020); new fully-outfitted well over €1M', 'Used ~$750k–$1.0M+', 'Tight/borderline — a clean used 52 fits under $1M if lightly speced; a fully world-cruise-outfitted boat sits right at or just over the cap. A used Boréal 44/47.2 is the comfortable in-budget alternative.', 'European Yacht of the Year 2015. ''Bravo'' did a transatlantic + two Labrador iceberg cruises; sister Boréal 55 ''Bushpoint'' reached 80°N at Svalbard; Boréal 47 ''Sir Ernst'' to Antarctica.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":4,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4,"budget":3}'::jsonb, array['Hard doghouse', 'Aluminium centreboard', 'Huge tankage', 'Dries out']::text[], array['Cabin lights come on red first (white on a second press) to protect watchkeepers'' night vision.', 'Two small aft daggerboards flank the rudder to balance the helm and cut autopilot load.', 'Delvoye designed in "a desk in every cabin where bluewater children can do homework" after his own 6-year family voyage.']::text[], array['2020 ''Bravo'' — €885,000 + VAT (~$950k–$1.0M, Berthon)', '2020 Boréal 52 — ~$813,000 (Boatshop24/YachtWorld)', 'New base ~€725,000 ex-VAT (2020)']::text[], '[{"name":"Boréal 52 spec (PDF)","url":"https://www.boreal-yachts.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/Specifications_Bor%C3%A9al_52_sep2017.pdf"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/boreal-52/"},{"name":"Yachting World test","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/boreal-52-boat-test-62368"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Boréal 52 ''Bravo'' — full tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Rc-fFVcqko","note":"Broker tour with Sue Grant"},{"name":"Boréal 52 ''Lena'' — owner conversation","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w7G6cLZEppc","note":"Owner perspective"},{"name":"\"Boreal 52 — Thoughts\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JXy39bmYJys","note":"Buyer''s-eye view"},{"name":"Bushpoint (Boréal 55) channel","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@bushpoint","note":"High-latitude sister to 80°N"}]'::jsonb, array['Permanent welded alloy doghouse = exceptional all-weather cockpit/watch protection for a learning crew.', 'Aluminium hull tolerates ice, groundings and remote-coast abuse; a dry-out keel for beaching/inspection.', 'Genuinely easy short-handed handling (lines aft, balancing daggerboards, central windlass).', 'Huge fuel (up to ~1,257 L) and water (1,470 L) for long-range autonomy.', 'An owner-configurable forward zone for a real workshop/office.', 'Strong build reputation and resale; European Yacht of the Year 2015.']::text[], array['Price sits at the very top of (or just over) a $1M budget once outfitted.', 'Smaller interior volume than other 52-footers (security prioritised over space).', 'Engine access is good but not a walk-in engine room.', 'Dark tinted doghouse + alloy topsides can run hot in the tropics.', 'Bare-aluminium maintenance discipline (anodes, antifouling, no stray current) is non-negotiable.', 'Niche French builder — parts/service network is thinner in the Americas/Pacific.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2015']::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (Matthew Sheahan)","note":"\"The Land Rover Discovery of sailing\"… \"at 18 tonnes she was surprisingly nimble… a very easy boat to handle. Impressed.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/boreal-52-boat-test-62368"},{"who":"Attainable Adventure Cruising","note":"Long-running endorsement of the Boréal concept for high-latitude/offshore couples.","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2021/12/28/test-sail-and-review-of-the-boreal-47-2/"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2015', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium keel structure with internal lead ballast (no bolt-on keel) · single NACA spade rudder + two balancing aft daggerboards","complexity":"Moderate — deliberately simpler/more robust than a comparable production 52, but a world-cruise boat layers on redundancy/dual-voltage.","maintain":"Good for a hands-on owner — accessible systems and an alloy hull any competent welder can repair; aluminium electrolysis/anode management demands discipline.","partsText":"Active, growing builder (now up to a 56/70). Mainstream marine gear is easy worldwide; boat-specific/alloy support routes back through France — plan ahead in the Americas/Pacific.","problems":"No widespread defect pattern; the main risk themes are aluminium galvanic/electrolysis management and the niche service footprint, not build faults.","sentiment":"Strongly positive — owners and reviewers praise the build (''immaculate''), seaworthiness and resale; called ''the Land Rover Discovery of sailing.''","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Boréal","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/boreal-sailboats-165018.html"},{"name":"AAC — Boréal review","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2021/12/28/test-sail-and-review-of-the-boreal-47-2/"},{"name":"Boréal blog","url":"https://www.boreal-yachts.com/boreal-blog/?lang=en"}],"risks":["Price at/over budget when outfitted","Thin parts/service network outside Europe","Aluminium electrolysis/anode discipline required","Dark doghouse + alloy topsides run hot in the tropics"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":4,"parts":3,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('boreal', 'Boréal 47.2', 'Boréal Yachts · France', 'Jean-François Delvoye', '#1d4e6b', '2020–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + hard doghouse', '47''3" (14.39 m)', '41''9" (12.73 m)', '14''5" (4.39 m)', '3''7" (1.08 m) up', '8''2" (2.48 m) down', '13,650 kg / 30,093 lb (light)', '3,850 kg lead', '~28%', '93.8 m² / 1,010 ft²', '~21 m / 69''', 'Volvo D2-60/75 or Yanmar', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 1–2 heads', 'Aluminium centreboarder with a broad "keel embryo" grounding base + twin daggerboards', 'Aft cockpit (twin wheels) with a hard, full-height doghouse coachroof', '600 L / 158 gal', '638 L / 168 gal', 14.39, 41.75, 14.4, 30093, 1.08, '~16.7', '~184', 600, 638, 75, 590000, 930000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who put cold-weather shelter and proven expedition pedigree first, and want a hard doghouse without going to a full pilothouse.', 'Class-leading. A hard, secure doghouse with a deep bucket seat, full-height watertight door and a roof that shelters the forward cockpit — keep warm watch and con the boat from inside via autopilot remote. Exactly what cold, wet Patagonia demands.', 'Cutter-ready sloop: slightly-overlapping genoa plus a furling (or hanked) staysail on a removable inner forestay; slab main with single-line reefing led aft; powerful vang instead of a traveller; granny bars at the mast.', 'Built around a powerful (electric on test) central cockpit winch reachable from the helm; single-line slab reefing led aft, easy genoa-to-staysail change as wind builds. Every sheet can route to the big electric winch — a real asset for a smaller crew. You still step into the working cockpit to reef.', 'Good central engine access; the starboard aft cabin can be optioned as a dedicated technical/workshop room. Not a full walk-in engine room, but sensibly engineered with everything low and central.', 'Expedition norms: lithium bank, 500 W+ flexible solar on the doghouse/coachroof, watermaker, diesel heating and a below-deck protected windlass. Two 13 kg gas bottles give months of cooking autonomy.', '"A mass of stowage everywhere" — lockers under every bunk and settee, a cavernous forward sail locker, a massive twin-opening aft lazarette, plus a gas locker holding months of cooking fuel.', '~800–1,200 nm motoring (estimate); tankage upgrades offered. Watermaker standard on expedition spec.', 'Owner''s cabin forward with en-suite, saloon offset to port, two configurable aft cabins (one often a workshop). Low aluminium freeboard, beachable hull and a clear transom passage between the wheels make dog landings and boarding easy.', 'Best-in-class. Aluminium ice-breaking stem, watertight bulkheads, 1.08 m shoal draft to tuck into rock anchorages and dry out upright, hard doghouse for warmth. Born from the co-owner''s Patagonia and Antarctic voyages.', 'Strong — the larger 47.2 cockpit works as well in the tropics as up high, and shoal draft is welcome over reefs. Aluminium + doghouse can run warm; spec good awnings, ventilation or A/C.', '$590k–$930k', 'Base ~$590k–$650k; optioned new ~$760k–$930k', 'Thin supply; clean used/lightly-optioned new achievable under $1M', 'Fits — generally more headroom under $1M than the Kraken or Ovni 490.', 'Sir-Ernst (Boréal 47) — South Georgia, Antarctica, the Drake Passage, Lofoten and ocean crossings.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":4,"storage":5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['Hard doghouse', 'Aluminium centreboard', 'Patagonia-proven', 'Dries out']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2021 (Bluewater Cruiser).', 'The whole concept grew out of the founder''s six-year family circumnavigation.', 'Owners of the predecessor Boréal 47 ("Sir-Ernst") sailed it to South Georgia and Antarctica in Shackleton''s wake.']::text[], array['New base ~€541k ex-VAT; optioned new ~€700k–€850k', '2023 "Narval" 47.2 listed via Berthon International (since sold)', 'Sister Boréal 52 "Bravo" (2020) listed ~€885k / ~$1.02M']::text[], '[{"name":"Boréal Yachts","url":"https://www.boreal-yachts.com"},{"name":"Yachting World review","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/boreal-472-review"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sir-Ernst","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@sir-ernst1843","note":"Owners of a Boréal 47 to Antarctica & the Drake"},{"name":"Boat tour — Boréal 47.2","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GcWwXXkY3xE","note":"Owner walkthrough of an actual 47.2"},{"name":"27-min private tour (FR)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9BaBDRSBH04","note":"ActuNautique detailed 47.2 walkthrough"},{"name":"\"Is a pilot house worth it?\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uufUfXRH0cg","note":"Owner discussion of the doghouse"},{"name":"Voile Mag — EYOTY jury feature","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V61Vu471iLY","note":"European Yacht of the Year award (FR)"}]'::jsonb, array['Hard doghouse = unmatched all-weather shelter for cold Patagonia, yet works in the tropics too.', 'Aluminium + 1.08 m shoal centreboard + flat beachable base = the definitive rock-anchorage and reef platform; repairable anywhere.', 'Genuinely proven expedition record (Antarctic, Patagonia, circumnavigations) — a low-risk known quantity.', 'Enormous, well-distributed stowage and an optional dedicated workshop cabin; easy step-free deck movement for dogs.']::text[], array['You still step out of the doghouse into the working cockpit to reef (3rd reef not led aft as standard).', 'Lighter, lower-ballast shoal centreboarder — not a heavy full-keel feel (though proven stable).', 'Centreboard + twin daggerboards add maintenance points vs. a fixed keel.', 'Aluminium needs galvanic management and can be warm below in the tropics without good ventilation.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2021']::text[], '[{"who":"John Harries · Attainable Adventure Cruising","note":"Rates the Boréal 44/47 \"in a class of her own\" among aluminium expedition boats; nearly bought one, and for high latitudes would choose \"the Boréal every time.\"","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2019/11/16/the-garcia-exploration-45-compared-to-the-boreal-47-part-1-introduction-and-rig/"},{"who":"Jimmy Cornell · Yachting World","note":"Groups Boréal with Garcia and KM as the semi-custom step up in aluminium centreboarders.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"},{"who":"Yachting World (Rupert Holmes)","note":"\"A supremely capable yacht with long legs… the bigger cockpit will work just as well in the tropics as at high latitudes.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/boreal-47-2-review-a-proven-concept-refined"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2021', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (offshore-preferred)","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium centreboard, internal ballast (no bolt-on keel) · single protected NACA rudder","complexity":"Low–Moderate — deliberate simplicity: manual centreboard, conventional winches, cutter rig with a real staysail; few hydraulics/digital dependence. Aluminium needs galvanic discipline.","maintain":"Engineered to be owner-fixable far from yards (replaceable line channels, accessible systems, beachable for hull work). Aluminium welding & centreboard internals are specialist but rare.","partsText":"Independent boutique French yard, still active. Standard Volvo/Yanmar engine (global). Boat-specific aluminium/centreboard parts route through one small builder — moderate continuity risk.","problems":"No documented systemic defects; reputation for top build quality. Generic alloy items: galvanic corrosion if anodes/bonding neglected, centreboard pivot/lift-gear wear, condensation in the cold.","sentiment":"Owners and testers rate it a genuine go-anywhere expedition yacht with excellent build and a safe deck layout; few regrets. Main gripes: utilitarian looks, price, dependence on one small French yard.","communities":[{"name":"Boréal (official FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/voiliers.boreal/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/boreal-sailboats-165018.html"},{"name":"AAC owner write-up","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2015/07/02/boreal-47-an-owners-experience/"}],"risks":["Boutique single-builder: parts & refit concentrated in one small French yard","Aluminium galvanic/corrosion management is ongoing","Small owner community vs mass-market brands"],"scores":{"maintain":4.5,"simplicity":4.5,"parts":3,"community":2.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('garcia', 'Garcia Exploration 45', 'Garcia Yachts · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau w/ Jimmy Cornell', '#205e52', '2014–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + hardtop / deck saloon', '46''6" (14.21 m)', '41''2" (12.57 m)', '14''6" (4.44 m)', '3''9" (1.14 m) up', '9''6" (2.90 m) down', '14,612 kg / 32,214 lb', '4,540 kg', '~32%', '91 m² / 979 ft²', '~21 m / 69''', 'Volvo D2-75 (~55–80 hp)', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 1–2 heads', 'Integral aluminium centreboard retracting fully into the bilge; flat grounding-plate hull; twin rudders', 'Aft cockpit with a raised deck-saloon and rigid IMOCA-style hardtop "cap" over the twin helms', '700 L / 185 gal', '500 L / 132 gal', 14.21, 41.24, 14.57, 32214, 1.14, '~15.9', '~208', 700, 500, 75, 700000, 1200000, 'fit', 1, 'The high-latitude-first couple who want Jimmy Cornell''s expedition recipe — aluminium, beachable, with a real workshop — and can find a used one under $1M.', 'Very well protected — the hardtop cap shelters the seated helm, and the insulated, double-glazed raised saloon gives 270° visibility so you can stand watch from inside in the warmth. Excellent for cold water, though not as fully enclosing as the Amel''s center cockpit.', 'Sloop/cutter with furling genoa and a staysail; slab or in-mast main per owner spec; twin rudders for sure steering; push-button centreboard; all controls led to the protected cockpit.', 'All controls led to the protected cockpit; twin rudders give light, sure steering in big seas; push-button centreboard. Pete Goss and Jimmy Cornell both call it easily handled two-handed — spec electric winches/easy furling to make it effortless for a smaller crew.', 'A standout: a dedicated workshop / technical room with bench, tool and spares stowage, plus easy access to engine, generator, watermaker and pumps. Built for remote self-sufficiency.', 'Built for autonomy: watermaker, solar, wind and/or hydro generators, lithium, diesel heating, and an insulated double-glazed deck saloon — weeks of self-sufficiency.', 'Abundant — deep aluminium bilges (the board tucks away without stealing storage), large lockers, dedicated spares/tool stowage and watertight crash compartments.', '~900–1,200 nm motoring; routinely fitted with watermaker, solar, wind and/or hydro for weeks of autonomy.', '2–3 cabins, 1–2 heads, master en-suite, dedicated sea berth, insulated/heated interior. Shoal draft and the ability to beach make dog shore-access easy; lower freeboard aids boarding. Tighter volume than the Amel.', 'The purpose-built high-latitude boat. Aluminium shrugs off rock and ice, the lifting board + beachable hull let you anchor in shallow rocky coves and dry out for repairs, and the heated deck saloon is ideal for cold passages.', 'Equally capable — 1.14 m shoal draft opens up BVI/Polynesian thin water, and raw aluminium runs cool and benign in the heat.', '$700k–$1.2M', '~$1.1–1.2M new, typically equipped', 'Used ~$700k–$1.04M', 'Fits — a used Exploration 45 is comfortably attainable, fully outfitted, under $1M.', 'Jimmy Cornell''s Aventura IV (Northwest Passage attempt); reviewed and sailed by Pete Goss.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium centreboard', 'Real workshop', 'Jimmy Cornell design', 'Dries out']::text[], array['Co-designed by Jimmy Cornell — founder of the ARC rally — as his ideal go-anywhere yacht.', 'Cornell''s own Aventura IV was an Exploration 45 used to attempt the Northwest Passage.', 'You can deliberately beach it to scrub or inspect the hull between tides.']::text[], array['New ~€1,095,000 (2025) typically equipped', '2019 "Wings of Desire" — ~$875,000 (Swiftsure Yachts)', '2021–2025 boats roughly $725k–$1.04M']::text[], '[{"name":"Garcia Yachts","url":"https://www.garciayachts.com/en/sailsboats/exploration-45"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/exploration-45-garcia/"},{"name":"SAIL review","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/garcia-exploration-45-jimmy-cornells-ideal-boat/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Garcia Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/c/GarciaYachts_official/videos","note":"Tours and walkthroughs"},{"name":"A Ticket to Rove","url":"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLV1Qq_A0WXZTYWFsIYOfbAensBM6WxIMK","note":"Owner cruising series aboard an Exploration 45"},{"name":"Pete Goss — full boat tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5_hyr4CUSLs","note":"Complete tour with the round-the-world sailor"},{"name":"Swiftsure walkthrough (2026)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=68nv-7wnDws","note":"Detailed brokerage systems tour"},{"name":"SV Tonic review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GTG4oP5wNX0","note":"Owner-perspective review/tour"}]'::jsonb, array['Aluminium hull + lifting board + beachable plate — ideal for Patagonian rock anchorages, drying out and impact safety.', '1.14 m shoal draft unlocks shallow coves the Amel can''t reach and eases dog shore-access.', 'A real onboard workshop plus easy access to engine, watermaker and systems.', 'Insulated, heated, double-glazed deck saloon with 270° watchkeeping; well within budget used.']::text[], array['Hardtop "cap" protection is excellent but not as fully enclosing as the Amel''s center cockpit.', 'Less standard automation than the Amel — spec electric winches/easy furling for a smaller crew.', 'Smaller interior volume than the Amel 50 (46 ft vs 54 ft).', 'Aluminium requires electrical-isolation discipline (galvanic management, anodes).']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2015', 'Cruising World Boat of the Year 2015', 'SAIL Best Boats 2015']::text[], '[{"who":"Jimmy Cornell (owner, Aventura IV)","note":"\"For safety as well as convenience, a centreboard is a great advantage\"; the twin-ruddered Garcia \"was a joy to helm.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"},{"who":"John Harries · Attainable Adventure Cruising","note":"Wrote a five-part forensic Boréal-vs-Garcia comparison; rates both as genuinely great offshore boats.","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2019/11/16/the-garcia-exploration-45-compared-to-the-boreal-47-part-1-introduction-and-rig/"},{"who":"SAIL Magazine","note":"Named a Best Boats winner — \"Jimmy Cornell''s ideal boat,\" more closewinded than his old Ovni.","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/garcia-exploration-45-jimmy-cornells-ideal-boat/"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2015', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium centreboard, internal ballast (no bolt-on keel) · twin skeg-protected rudders","complexity":"Moderate — designed for self-sufficiency with easy systems access; scales with options (genset/watermaker/lithium). Aluminium galvanic management.","maintain":"Designed around owner access and at-sea intervention; bare-aluminium hull option = no topcoat upkeep. Alloy repair & centreboard internals are specialist.","partsText":"Active, well-backed (Grand Large Yachting group, dedicated refit division). Volvo D2-75 + Jefa steering (mainstream). Low–moderate parts risk.","problems":"Buyer-beware: Volvo D2-75 gearbox ''infant-mortality'' failures — verify fix history. Early hulls: restricted forward visibility (later improved) and occasional hatch/seal water ingress. One owner reported a poor handover.","sentiment":"Very positive — a comfortable, confidence-inspiring world cruiser that tracks well; the bare-alloy ''no-maintenance hull'' is a frequent plus. Negatives: the gearbox issue, price, a few finish/handover gripes.","communities":[{"name":"Garcia Exploration Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/1348196502191194/"},{"name":"Allures–Garcia Owners forum","url":"https://alluresgarciaowners.discussion.community/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/garcia-exploration-45-a-230710.html"}],"risks":["Volvo gearbox ''infant-mortality'' — confirm fix history before buying","Aluminium galvanic/corrosion management required","Keep options restrained (genset/watermaker/lithium) for DIY simplicity"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3.5,"parts":4,"community":3.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('ovni490', 'Ovni 490', 'Alubat · France', 'Mortain·Mavrikios with CBA', '#3a4a63', '2024–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Pilothouse + aft helm', '52''4" (15.95 m)', '45''10" (13.98 m)', '15''9" (4.80 m)', '3''3" (1.0 m) up', '10''2" (3.10 m) down', '21,000 kg / 46,300 lb (max loaded)', 'Lifting keel 480 kg + internal', 'form-stable hull', '129 m² / 1,389 ft²', '21.8 m / 71''6"', 'Twin 50 hp Volvo (or electric)', 'Twin shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'All-aluminium lifting keel / centreboard to 1.0 m; broad beam, take-the-ground hull; watertight bulkheads', 'Integrated aluminium pilothouse / deck saloon with watertight door + inside steering, plus an aft twin-helm cockpit', '1,000 L / 264 gal', '600 L / 158 gal', 15.95, 45.86, 15.75, 40000, 1, 'n/a', 'n/a', 1000, 600, 100, 1070000, 1250000, 'over', 3, 'The couple who want the most protected, biggest-tanked, get-home-redundant aluminium expedition boat — and have the budget to buy new.', 'The headline feature: a true sheltered inside steering/watch station with 360° view, sealable for foul weather, behind an open sailing cockpit. By far the most weather-protected boat here for cold, wet high-latitude watches.', 'Solent rig (large furling headsail + self-tacking-friendly inner stay) keeps sail changes simple; lines routed aft through two channels with winches at the companionway sides; routing configurable for small crews.', 'Explicitly built to "sail with two protected in the pilothouse." Solent rig keeps sail changes simple, lines routed aft. The weaker crew member can stand watch and trim from shelter — a big ergonomic win.', 'Dedicated technical space accessible from both cockpit and interior — excellent systems access and a built-in workshop/utility zone. Twin 50 hp diesel shafts add docking control and get-home redundancy.', 'First hull: twin 20 kW electric motors + 50 kWh lithium + generator, with 1,600 W solar; dedicated foul-weather-gear locker. Watermaker is the expedition norm.', 'Abundant — three-cabin layout still fits a washing machine and freezer, a dedicated foul-weather-gear locker, plus several large on-deck stowage spaces.', 'Biggest fuel here — long motoring range; first hull carried 1,600 W solar. Watermaker is the expedition norm.', '3 cabins + pilothouse living/watch space; the sealable pilothouse is somewhere dogs can shelter in cold/rough passages. Enormous protected indoor volume — arguably the most dog-and-cold-weather-friendly interior here.', 'Best-in-class. All-aluminium hull AND deck, lifting keel to 1.0 m, can take the ground, sealed pilothouse for warmth, twin-engine redundancy. Ovnis are a staple of Patagonia, Greenland, Svalbard and the Northwest Passage.', 'Shoal 1.0 m draft is great over reefs and lagoons, but the big watertight aluminium pilothouse soaks heat — good ventilation/A/C needed in the tropics.', '~$1.07M+ (new)', 'Base €995,000 ex-VAT; UK new-build ~€1,035,000', 'Brand-new model — essentially no used market yet', 'Over budget once outfitted. The cheaper path to the Ovni philosophy under $1M is a used Ovni 450 (below).', 'As a 2025 launch, no completed expeditions on the 490 yet — but the Ovni/Alubat line is among the most expedition-proven aluminium fleets in the world.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":5,"tropical":3.5,"budget":2}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium pilothouse', 'Inside steering', 'Biggest tankage', 'Twin engines']::text[], array['The hull, deck AND pilothouse are all welded aluminium — "full metal jacket."', 'The first hull launched with twin electric motors and a 50 kWh lithium bank.', 'Five were sold off the plans before the first one even launched.']::text[], array['New base €995,000 ex-VAT; UK new-build ~€1,035,000', 'Brand-new model — no used market yet', 'Cheaper path: a used Ovni 450/495']::text[], '[{"name":"Alubat","url":"https://www.alubat.com"},{"name":"Yachting World first look","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/ovni-490-first-look"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Alubat (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCqfN_fkd1cdjBwIWGVamcqQ","note":"Builder channel incl. Ovni 490 design videos"},{"name":"First Look at the Ovni 490","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oeTDqCqZlAA","note":"Walkthrough of the new design"},{"name":"Ovni 490 — Full Metal Jacket","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iThOuYiPaGE","note":"Intro to the all-aluminium build"},{"name":"Alubat CEO interview","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5XBYMVMayro","note":"Luc Jurien on the design philosophy"},{"name":"SV Tonic first look","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gy6JwukdUOw","note":"Review/tour of the Ovni 490"}]'::jsonb, array['Fully protected aluminium pilothouse with inside steering — the single best feature for cold, wet watches and for sheltering crew + dogs.', 'The definitive high-latitude rock-anchorage platform: all-aluminium, lifting keel to 1.0 m, can take the ground.', 'Biggest tankage here (1,000 L fuel / 600 L water) + dedicated foul-weather locker.', 'Twin engines give docking precision and get-home redundancy in remote waters.']::text[], array['Base €995k ex-VAT means a fully outfitted boat will almost certainly exceed $1M — the tightest fit (or a miss) against budget.', 'All-aluminium deck + big pilothouse can run hot in the tropics without good ventilation/A/C.', 'Heavier, higher-volume hull = less lively sailing than the lighter Allures.', 'Brand-new design with no long-term owner track record yet.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (first look)","note":"\"The pilothouse gives excellent shelter for two or three people when on watch,\" with high form stability and good upwind ability.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/ovni-490-first-look-all-aluminium-pilothouse-offers-great-protection-158498"},{"who":"Jimmy Cornell (brand)","note":"Credits the integral-ballast centreboard with virtually eliminating downwind broaching — the Ovni philosophy the 490 continues.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium lifting keel/centreboard, internal lead ballast (no bolt-on keel) · twin rudders","complexity":"Moderate–High — big deck-saloon flagship: twin engines, pilothouse systems, high genoa loads (electric winches recommended), optional electric drive/lithium. Aluminium galvanic management.","maintain":"Repair-friendly alloy build, beachable; but a large, complex flagship (twin engines, powered sail loads). Routine work OK; scale/complexity is beyond the smaller Ovnis.","partsText":"Alubat (est. 1973) — small INDEPENDENT yard with a turbulent financial history (post-2008 receivership, 2014 rescue, 2023 employee buyout); currently a full order book. Yanmar engines (global). Moderate continuity risk.","problems":"New (2024) — thin track record. Reviewer niggles: a tight helm and a recessed-winch sheet-override hazard. Brand-level: galvanic vigilance, centreboard lift-gear upkeep.","sentiment":"Ovnis have near-cult status for ruggedness and go-anywhere ability; testers rate the 490 coherent, complete and well-built, with adequate (not sparkling) performance and a steep price. Long-run 490 data is still thin.","communities":[{"name":"Ovni Owners (UK)","url":"https://ovni-owners.org.uk/"},{"name":"Ovni-Club (international)","url":"http://en.ovniclub.com/"},{"name":"Ovni/Alubat Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/1670746193160570/"}],"risks":["Small independent builder with a turbulent financial history — assess continuity","Larger/more complex flagship (twin engines, powered sails)","Aluminium galvanic management","Reported recessed-winch sheet-override hazard"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2.5,"parts":3,"community":4.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('outbound', 'Outbound 46', 'Outbound Yachts · USA/China', 'Carl Schumacher', '#475569', '2002–present (44 from 1999)', 'GRP (solid laminate)', 'Aft-cockpit bluewater', 'Aft (deep) + hard dodger', '46''4" (14.1 m)', '40''3" (12.27 m)', '13''6" (4.11 m)', '5''6" (shoal)', '6''6" (deep)', '28,000 lb / 12,700 kg', '10,000 lb lead (encapsulated, 3,500 lb in a bulb)', '~36%', '1,083 ft²', '~63''6"', 'Yanmar 4JH80 (80 hp)', 'Shaft', '2 cabins / 2 heads', 'Encapsulated long fin keel with bulb — no keel bolts; balanced spade rudder; collision bulkhead 7 ft aft of the bow', 'Deep, narrow, dry aft cockpit; many boats carry an extended hard dodger + bimini', '719 L / 190 gal', '757 L / 200 gal', 14.1, 40.25, 13.5, 28000, 1.68, '~18', '~192', 719, 757, 80, 339000, 895000, 'fit', 1, 'The two-handed couple who want a genuinely seaworthy, dry, easy-to-handle cruiser with a real workshop, huge tankage and dog-friendly access — Patagonia-to-Polynesia, under $1M.', 'A deliberately long, narrow, deep T-cockpit prized as "exceptionally dry and well protected" — owners "go out when others stay at the dock." A molded breakwater anchors a hard dodger (extended on boats like "Boojum") for near-pilothouse shelter over the companionway, with a 32-inch helm seat. No inside steering, so sustained cold relies on the dodger.', 'Keel-stepped Selden double-spreader rig; BOC-inspired double headstay with a solent jib ~3 ft behind the furling genoa (roll up the genoa, unroll a heavy-air jib without going forward); North full-batten slab main (Leisurefurl in-boom optional); code zero/asym off the stem; whisker pole common.', 'Built as a fast, easy couple''s boat: the solent setup lets you change down without leaving the cockpit; full-batten slab main (or optional in-boom) reefs from the cockpit. Well-found boats add electric primaries — "Ubiquitous" is wired so every line can reach a powered winch, effectively single-handable. Heavy-air storm sails reward an experienced hand.', 'Best-in-class. A stand-up workshop "garage" under a cockpit seat with a workbench, vise area, six drawers and cabinets — owners fit the genset, watermaker, freezer, even a washer-dryer and still stow spares. Companionway steps lift on gas struts and two side panels open both engine flanks.', 'Well-found boats: LiFePO₄ house bank + Victron 3 kW inverter/charger, twin alternators with a Balmar regulator, bimini solar + a stern wind generator, a Fischer Panda / Northern Lights / Kubota genset and a 40 gph watermaker in the workshop, Webasto diesel heat + saloon A/C, B&G electronics, gravity-feed heads.', 'Built for self-sufficiency — a stand-up foredeck sail locker (sized for the asym) behind a collision bulkhead, a giant cockpit lazarette, dedicated liferaft/propane/anchor lockers, and a no-liner interior. Tanks sit low over the keel.', '~1,000+ nm motoring on a frugal Yanmar (owner logs 6 kt at 3.5 L/hr). Watermaker and genset common.', 'Two cabins / two heads, 6''4"+ headroom, semi-raised salon; centerline queen forward, quarter double aft, the workshop + chart table opposite. The 7'' settee and dinette make lee-clothed sea berths; the head doubles as a wet locker. For dogs: a low 3-step companionway (no steep ladder), a deep secure cockpit, and a wide 32" walk-through transom step for easy boarding.', 'Very strong — solid hand-laid GRP, a molded keel with no keel bolts, a collision bulkhead 7 ft aft of the bow, CE Cat A and a factory Webasto diesel heat option. The deep keel claws to windward off a lee shore. "Bright Moments" cruised the Pacific NW and NZ for years.', 'Proven Pacific-crossing boat (French Polynesia and beyond), good ventilation, shoal-keel option for thin water. Its true sweet spot is the full Patagonia-to-Polynesia span.', '$339k–$895k', 'New semi-custom ~$700k–$900k+', 'Used ~$339k–$600k; near-new 2024 "Boojum" listed ~$875k', 'Comfortable fit — clean used hulls leave room for refit; a near-new 2024 example sits right under the cap.', '"Georgia" (Outbound 44, hull #10) circumnavigated in 8 years / ~37,000 nm; "Bright Moments" (hull #33) cruised Mexico, French Polynesia, Tonga and NZ; "Sequoia" (hull #5) hit 33 countries in 2 years.', '{"protection":3.5,"handling":4,"dogs":5,"workshop":5,"storage":5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":5,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['Stand-up workshop', 'Dog-friendly transom', 'No keel bolts', 'Best engine access']::text[], array['A genuine walk-in workshop "garage" — a workbench-and-vise tool room you can stand up in, rare on a 46-footer.', 'It only became the "46" at hull #9, when one owner asked to double the swim step — and everyone else wanted it too.', 'Reviewer John Harries said that among the marina''s "big-assed marina queens" the Outbound caught his eye and "after just one glance I was smitten."']::text[], array['2024 "Boojum" hull #86 — ~$875,000 (Collection Yachts / Denison)', '2012 — ~$525,000 (Forbes Horton, Annapolis)', '2011 "Gadabout" — $405,000 (Swiftsure, San Diego)', '2005 — ~$359,900 (Papeete, French Polynesia)']::text[], '[{"name":"Outbound Yachts","url":"https://www.outboundyachts.com"},{"name":"Practical Sailor reviews","url":"https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Have Wind Will Travel","url":"https://www.youtube.com/c/HaveWindWillTravelcom","note":"Owners of Outbound 46 \"Ubiquitous\""},{"name":"Nautilus tour — \"Bright Moments\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1913iFwSXj8","note":"Full video tour of hull #33"},{"name":"\"Gadabout\" walkthrough (Swiftsure)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NaJe2MQVnaE","note":"Brokerage listing tour"},{"name":"Hull 85 walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XjMZu_KpT9I","note":"Deck & interior tour of a current build"},{"name":"Sailing Fair Isle review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVB4wBXMzg4","note":"Owner-channel Outbound 46 review"},{"name":"Lady K Sailing review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-bQaZXyGCcs","note":"\"A Rival for Island Packet\""}]'::jsonb, array['Purpose-built two-handed couple''s boat — balanced helm, solent rig, lines aft, electric-winch/furling options for a smaller crew.', 'Best-in-class stand-up workshop "garage" plus the easiest engine/systems access in this comparison.', 'Big keel-centred tankage + a frugal Yanmar = ~1,000+ nm real ocean-crossing range.', 'Short 3-step companionway, walk-through transom and swim platform — the easiest boat here for two dogs.', 'Solid hand-laid GRP, no keel bolts, a forward collision bulkhead and factory Webasto heat — proven Patagonia-to-Polynesia.']::text[], array['Aft open cockpit with no inside steering — in sustained Patagonian cold the helmsman relies on a (good) hard dodger, not a heated doghouse.', 'Only a 2-cabin / 2-head layout — limited guest space.', 'China-built (excellent reputation, but survey the cored rudder for moisture and check mast-step drainage).', 'Truly turn-key cold + tropical kit on a cheaper used hull still needs real refit spend.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"John Harries · Attainable Adventure Cruising","note":"\"A great voyaging boat… ocean voyaging ready for short-handed crews\" — the boat at Annapolis that \"really called out to me.\"","url":"https://www.morganscloud.com/2020/04/21/outbound-46-review-introduction/"},{"who":"Practical Sailor / Lady K Sailing","note":"Reviewed as \"the gold standard of blue water cruising sailboats,\" with sea-kindly motion that \"builds confidence offshore.\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVB4wBXMzg4"},{"who":"John Kretschmer (brand)","note":"Lists the Outbound 44 (the 46''s predecessor) among his recommended seaworthy offshore designs.","url":"https://www.practical-sailor.com/blog/the-best-sailboats-for-the-high-seas/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"n/a (unverified; Sparcraft mast, simple slab/single-line reefing)","keelRudder":"Encapsulated/integral keel — lead bolted to the moulded keel then fully glassed in (no interior keel bolts to leak/corrode) · spade rudder on a 4-inch stainless stock","complexity":"Low–Moderate (deliberately simple) — built around a couple cruising offshore with robust, simple systems; slab reefing, a dedicated tool/spares ''garage,'' easy access. Bow thruster optional.","maintain":"Strong for a non-expert couple — US-spec mainstream components, generous spares/tool storage, a simple rig, no keel bolts to manage, good access. One of the most DIY-friendly here.","partsText":"Niche, founder-driven — designed by Carl Schumacher, built in China for US-based Outbound (founder Phil Lambert, hands-on near the yard). Most materials are US-sourced/mainstream (eases parts); only the keel lead is local. The main risk is key-person/succession, not parts.","problems":"No widespread fault pattern; the encapsulated keel removes keel-bolt failure modes. The general spade-rudder grounding caution applies. Low volume = fewer documented surveyor flags.","sentiment":"Consistently praised as a well-mannered, easily-driven, comfortable, easy-on-crew offshore boat and a pleasure to liveaboard; the spares ''garage'' and simple rig are repeatedly highlighted.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/outbound-46-a-208523.html"},{"name":"Sailing Anarchy thread","url":"https://forums.sailinganarchy.com/threads/outbound-46.128735/"},{"name":"Outbound Yachts (owner support)","url":"https://www.outboundyachts.com/"}],"risks":["Builder fragility / key-person risk — low-volume, founder-dependent; support could thin if the founder retires","Spade rudder is more grounding-vulnerable than a skeg rudder","No large public owner forum (a tight-knit private group + direct factory contact instead)"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":4,"parts":3,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('ovni450', 'Ovni 450', 'Alubat · France', 'Marc Lombard', '#43586f', '2018–present', 'Aluminium', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + optional hard dodger', '45''11" (13.98 m)', '41''5" (12.66 m)', '14''1" (4.29 m)', '3''4" (1.0 m) up', '9''6" (2.90 m) down', '11,550 kg light / ~14,550 kg max', '~3,725 kg cast iron', '~32%', '95.5 m² / 1,028 ft²', '~20.5 m / 67''', 'Volvo D2-50 (50 hp)', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Aluminium centreboard (lifting plate) with twin transom-hung rudders; flat double-chine hull that dries out upright', 'Aft cockpit (twin wheels) with an optional rigid aluminium hard dodger', '500 L / 132 gal', '540 L / 143 gal', 13.98, 41.54, 14.08, 28000, 1, '~19.0', '~159', 500, 540, 50, 400000, 850000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a proven shoal-draft aluminium boat that beaches itself in Patagonia and gunkholes the tropics — for well under budget, leaving cash to outfit.', 'Aft twin-wheel cockpit with deep braced benches and welded handrails; the common optional aluminium hard dodger partially encloses the cockpit for cold-water watches. Standard fit is a fabric sprayhood, so protection depends on speccing the hard top.', 'Fractional sloop; furling genoa with an optional removable Dyneema-stay or furling staysail (effectively a cutter); slab main on a low-friction ball-bearing mast track with lazy bag and a boom brake; granny bars at the mast.', 'Working winches under the dodger flank the companionway; genoa winches aft by the helm. Electric winches are a factory option (recommended here). The mast track makes hoisting/dropping the main notably lighter and the boom brake removes a dangerous job — manageable for a smaller crew if specced with electric winches.', 'Volvo D2-50 under gas-strut companionway steps for good frontal access, with side panels in the aft cabin and head. A dedicated aft technical room/workshop houses the watermaker, heater, freezer and steering gear with bench space.', 'Aluminium arch for solar + a wind generator; owners commonly add lithium, 300–600 W+ solar, a watermaker, a diesel cabin heater and a genset in the technical room. Hull and deck insulated as standard.', 'Abundant for the size — a watertight-bulkheaded forward sail/anchor locker, a huge cockpit "garage" under the starboard bench (gennaker, outboard, even a bicycle), gas and helm-seat lockers, and under-sole/settee stowage.', '~700–900 nm motoring on the 50 hp diesel — moderate; long crossings lean on sail. Many owners add jerry-can fuel/water.', 'Typically 3 cabins / 2 heads (six possible layouts thanks to the bulkhead-free alloy structure). Moderate freeboard, a wide flush bathing platform, swim ladder and big stern grab rails make dog boarding easy, and the dry-out ability lets dogs ashore in tidal anchorages. Aft cabin is a touch narrow for two.', 'Excellent — exactly what Ovnis are built for: welded insulated aluminium, a hard-dodger option, shoal draft to gunkhole the Chilean channels and take the ground in remote tidal coves. A fixture in Patagonia and Norway.', 'Very good — shoal draft for reefs and lagoons, insulation keeps it cool, big opening hatches; aluminium just needs disciplined anode/galvanic management in warm marinas.', '$400k–$650k (used)', 'New, well-equipped, ran ~$700k–$850k+', 'Used roughly $400k–$650k ready-to-cruise', 'Comfortable fit — the cheapest proven path to true aluminium expedition capability, leaving budget to outfit.', 'The Ovni line has an outsized high-latitude/circumnavigation following; "Sailing Astragale" outfitted their 450 for cold-water cruising toward Norway.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4,"dogs":4.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium centreboard', 'Dries out', 'Cheapest expedition path', 'Cockpit "garage"']::text[], array['"OVNI" literally means UFO in French — apt for a boat that sits flat on a tidal beach like no fin-keeler can.', 'The bulkhead-free alloy structure is so stiff Alubat offers six different interior layouts.', 'An optional welded aluminium toe-rail "bumper" rings the hull for Nordic-style pile moorings.']::text[], array['New well-equipped ~$700k–$850k+ (hard dodger, genset, watermaker, A/C)', '"Reverie" (2022) with hard dodger, electric winches, genset — via Alubat America', '2019 example listed in France ~€310k (looks low — verify)']::text[], '[{"name":"Alubat","url":"https://www.alubat.com"},{"name":"SailboatData (Ovni 450)","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/ovni-450/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing Astragale","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCut9OtfYSiiR2e6LxFT25aQ","note":"French couple cruising an Ovni 450, Med → Norway"},{"name":"Ovni 450 guided tour (English)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NWo5GLODnAU","note":"Builder walkthrough"},{"name":"Ovni 450 walkthrough 2020","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rv8Y7Nc36n8","note":"Volt-At-Sea detailed walkthrough"},{"name":"Ovni 445 owner tour (FR)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jBz22BLmO0I","note":"Liveaboard tour of the predecessor"}]'::jsonb, array['Centreboard + dry-out ability is uniquely valuable for Patagonia''s tidal/remote anchorages and for letting two dogs ashore on a beach.', 'Aluminium hull forgives ice, debris and the inevitable reef bump — the cheapest path to true expedition capability.', 'Hard-dodger option gives a genuinely protected, partially-enclosable cockpit for cold-water watches.', 'All sail handling leads to the cockpit; electric winches + mast track + boom brake make it workable for a smaller crew.', 'Dedicated aft workshop/technical room plus a huge cockpit "garage" for gear; low boarding height for dogs.']::text[], array['Tankage (500 L / 540 L) and ~700–900 nm range are only moderate for big crossings — budget for added fuel/water and a watermaker.', 'Engine access is "lift-the-stairs" rather than a walk-in room (adequate, but tighter than the Allures).', 'Flat-bottomed alloy hull slaps at anchor and upwind in chop, and it''s not a fast boat — slower passages.', 'Standard 50 hp engine is modest for windward/tidal motoring; many owners prefer more power.', 'Aluminium demands disciplined galvanic management, especially in warm tropical marinas.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Sailing Zingaro (James Evenson)","note":"Features the Alubat Ovni 435 (the 450''s predecessor) as a top affordable aluminium lifting-keel pick in his best-bluewater-under-$300K video.","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-9nFISFFhU"},{"who":"Jimmy Cornell (brand)","note":"Sailed ~100,000 miles in aluminium Ovni/Garcia centreboarders; rates the type \"the best choice for serious explorers.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral aluminium lifting keel/centreboard, internal lead ballast (no bolt-on keel) · twin (raisable) rudders","complexity":"Low–Moderate — single engine, manual cockpit-winch centreboard, conventional rig; scales with options. Aluminium galvanic management.","maintain":"Single engine + simpler systems than the 490 = more DIY-friendly; designed for remote self-sufficiency and beaching. Alloy repair & centreboard internals are specialist.","partsText":"Alubat (small INDEPENDENT yard, turbulent financial history — see Ovni 490). Volvo D2-50 (global). Moderate continuity risk.","problems":"No model-specific systemic defect. Brand-level: galvanic vigilance, centreboard pivot/lift-gear wear, condensation/insulation in cold, anode discipline.","sentiment":"Positive within the Ovni following — owners value safety, shoal-draft freedom and ruggedness over speed (performance is conservative). A practical family world-cruiser.","communities":[{"name":"Ovni Owners (UK)","url":"https://ovni-owners.org.uk/"},{"name":"Ovni-Club (international)","url":"http://en.ovniclub.com/"},{"name":"Ovni/Alubat Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/1670746193160570/"}],"risks":["Small independent builder, turbulent financial history","Aluminium galvanic management","Centreboard + twin-rudder mechanisms add maintenance items","Conservative sailing performance"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3.5,"parts":3,"community":4.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('allures519', 'Allures 51.9', 'Allures Yachting · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#26756e', '2021–present', 'Aluminium hull / composite deck', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft + windshield/arch', '54''8" (16.67 m)', 'LOD 51''1" (15.57 m)', '15''10" (4.82 m)', '4''5" (1.34 m) up', '9''7" (2.92 m) down', '18,400 kg / 40,565 lb', '~5,900 kg', '~32%', '118.6 m² / 1,277 ft²', '~22.2 m / 73''', 'Volvo D3-110 (150 hp opt)', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Aluminium centreboard in an alloy case with twin rudders; round-bilge hull (softer motion than a chined Ovni); dries out', 'Aft cockpit with a windshield + mainsheet arch; standard bimini/sprayhood, optional rigid bimini/doghouse', '700 L / 185 gal', '600 L / 158 gal', 16.67, 45.9, 15.81, 40565, 1.34, '~17.4', 'moderate', 700, 600, 110, 1050000, 1550000, 'over', 3, 'The couple who want the easiest-handling, most comfortable, walk-in-engine-room aluminium expedition cruiser in this size — if the budget can stretch to the top.', 'A prominent windshield and mainsheet arch shelter the cockpit and give clear helm sightlines; an optional rigid bimini/doghouse fully secures the watch-keeper. Comfortable, well-supported twin helm seats; an open transom with a drop-down platform.', 'Cutter/triple-headsail: genoa, removable staysail (with running backstays) and a Code 0 on the integral bowsprit, all on Furlex furlers; in-mast furling main typical (slab optional); Walder boom brake; all running rigging led aft.', 'Explicitly push-button from the helm — Lewmar winches and clutches right by the twin wheels, the in-mast main means no foredeck reefing, and electric winches/furling are common. Reviewers describe effortless single-couple handling — among the easiest here for a smaller crew.', 'A genuine walk-in engine room (a standout) housing the Volvo D3-110 (150 hp Volvo or Nanni options) with standing room to work, plus adjacent dedicated technical spaces. Bow and stern thrusters available.', 'BOTY test boat: 24 V / 800 Ah lithium, 500 W solar, Mastervolt charging, a Fischer Panda 8000i genset feeding the watermaker and reverse-cycle A/C + heating. The insulated alloy hull runs notably quiet.', 'Yacht-grade and generous — large under-berth stowage (the forward "princess" V-berth has excellent access beneath), deep cockpit lockers, a big forward sail/anchor locker and technical-room stowage.', '~900–1,100+ nm motoring on the 110 hp diesel — larger tankage and longer power range than the Ovni 450; watermaker standard on flagship boats.', 'Usually 3 cabins / 2 heads (full-beam aft owner''s suite + forward "princess" V-berth). U-shaped sea-going galley, light-filled salon, grippy MarineCork decks. Tall freeboard means a bigger step aboard for dogs, but the drop-down sugar-scoop platform and open transom make boarding workable; the centreboard dries out.', 'Outstanding and proven — the BOTY-winning sister sailed the "Viking route" (Scotland–Faroes–Iceland–Greenland–Canada). Insulated alloy hull, heating and the rigid-bimini option make it ideal for Patagonia/Chile.', 'Equally strong — shoal 1.34 m board-up draft for reefs and lagoons, A/C, a big bimini for shade, excellent ventilation, and the composite deck avoids a hot bare-alloy deck.', '$1.05M–$1.55M', 'New base ~€707k ex-VAT (2021) → ~€978k ex-VAT (2023); flagship outfitted ~€1.2–1.4M', 'Thin used market; verified used examples ~US$1.5M (southern Spain). The in-budget Allures path is a used 45.9 / 51 / 52.', 'Over budget — verified used 51.9s run ~$1.5M and a fully-outfitted boat clearly exceeds $1M; treat it as the aspirational benchmark and shop the in-budget Allures 45.9 (or a used 51/52).', 'Owners Markus Tanner & Marianne Daetwyler sailed "Castella" the Viking route (Scotland → Greenland → Annapolis), winning Cruising World''s 2025 BOTY.', '{"protection":4,"handling":5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":2}'::jsonb, array['Walk-in engine room', 'Push-button sailing', 'CW Boat of the Year 2025', 'Tight on budget']::text[], array['2025 Cruising World Boat of the Year (Best Full-Size Cruiser over 45 ft), judged after sailing to Annapolis from Greenland.', 'Decks are grippy low-maintenance MarineCork, not teak — and you can watch the sea rush by through the hull windows from inside.', 'Same Grand Large Yachting family as Garcia and Outremer — shared aluminium-expedition pedigree.']::text[], array['New base ~€707,000 ex-VAT (2021), rising to ~€978,000 ex-VAT (2023)', 'Well-specified late boats ~€1.0M–€1.38M', 'Some offered via I. Castañer Yachts (Cádiz) from ~€550k+']::text[], '[{"name":"Allures Yachting","url":"https://www.allures.com/en/models/allures-51-9/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/allures-51-9/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Yachting World — full test","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tRezvY2iGq8","note":"Toby Hodges sea-trial & tour"},{"name":"Allures 51.9 guided tour (English)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J-0sRtarLtg","note":"Builder/dealer walkthrough"},{"name":"The Boat Show — ENG walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aqBdiObsLYI","note":"Cannes professional walkthrough"},{"name":"Sailing Ruby Rose review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kZaPl9jQozQ","note":"\"Built to go anywhere\" review (2025)"},{"name":"Yachting World — full tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ObScSdrhoDw","note":"Second YW tour (different video)"},{"name":"Allures — sailing the 51.9 #2","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ssx17BchD4","note":"Builder sailing film"},{"name":"SeaExplorer — first sailing session","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kkjn8_59iN8","note":"Owner channel"},{"name":"Allures 51.9 — \"Built for Real Cruising\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96jOPM7Gs98","note":"Builder feature"},{"name":"BoatTube — 2024 Allures 51.9 review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5TWOAIkSFnw","note":"Walk-around review"},{"name":"Grand Large Rally — 51.9 crossing (FR)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=unf-YWNsP7I","note":"Owner ocean crossing, part 1"}]'::jsonb, array['Best-in-class shorthanded handling — push-button sailing from the helm, in-mast main, winches at the wheels — ideal for a smaller crew.', 'A walk-in engine room plus dedicated technical spaces directly answer the easy-engine-access + workshop requirement.', 'Larger fuel/water tankage (~700 L / ~600 L) and longer power range than the Ovni 450 for serious crossings.', 'Genuinely dual-climate: insulated alloy + heating + rigid bimini for Patagonia; shoal centreboard, A/C and shade for the tropics.', 'Quiet, sea-kindly round-bilge hull; centreboard dries out for shallow remote anchorages.']::text[], array['Price: a ready-to-sail used 51.9 likely sits at or above the $1M budget — the tightest fit of the new boats.', 'High freeboard makes climbing aboard a bigger step for two dogs (mitigated by the drop-down platform).', 'In-mast furling main (typical) trades some sail shape/performance and adds a jam-risk point offshore.', 'More boat and more complex systems for two people to maintain far from help.', 'Composite deck on an alloy hull means two maintenance regimes; centreboard case + twin rudders add inspection points.']::text[], array['Cruising World Boat of the Year 2025']::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World jury","note":"Best Full-Size Cruiser Over 45 ft — the aluminium cruiser \"excelled on a high-latitude voyage.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/boat-review-allures-51-9/"},{"who":"Yachting World (first look)","note":"Third-generation flagship retaining the rugged aluminium hull, composite deck, shoal draught and twin rudders.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/first-look-allures-51-9-133822"}]'::jsonb, 'CW BOTY 2025', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (with running backstays)","keelRudder":"Integral lifting centreboard, internal ballast (no bolt-on keel) · twin rudders","complexity":"High as specified — 24V/800Ah lithium, solar, Mastervolt, Fischer Panda genset, watermaker, A/C + heating, powered sails, running backstays. Capable but a lot of interdependent tech.","maintain":"Good designed-in access (tanks under sole; ''intelligent access to systems'') and a no-upkeep alloy hull — but the breadth of systems realistically needs professional support for the lithium/genset/watermaker stack.","partsText":"Active, well-backed (Grand Large Yachting group). Mainstream systems suppliers. Low–moderate parts risk; thinner model-specific service track record (new flagship).","problems":"New third-gen model — limited long-term data. Watch: centreboard upkeep, galvanic vigilance, and integration/commissioning of the 24V-lithium-genset-watermaker stack; deck-stepped base + running-backstay handling.","sentiment":"Positive — hugely practical for a shorthanded crew with strong self-sufficiency, shoal-draft freedom, dry-out and a well-thought-out liveaboard interior. Trade-offs: price, looks, the complexity of a fully-loaded systems package.","communities":[{"name":"Allures–Garcia Owners forum","url":"https://alluresgarciaowners.discussion.community/"}],"risks":["High systems complexity — needs professional support for the electrical/genset/watermaker stack","Running backstays add a manual sail-handling task to learn","Aluminium galvanic management","Newer large flagship = thinner model-specific community"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('hr44', 'Hallberg-Rassy 44', 'Hallberg-Rassy · Sweden', 'Germán Frers', '#1f5673', '2017–present', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + fixed windscreen', '47''5" (14.45 m)', '42''3" (12.88 m)', '13''9" (4.20 m)', '5''9" (1.75 m shoal)', '6''11" (2.10 m std)', '13,300 kg / 29,200 lb', '5,300 kg lead', '~40%', '106.5 m² / 1,152 ft²', '~21 m / 69''', 'Volvo D2-75 (75 hp)', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Lead fin keel on a deep bilge stub; twin rudders (a first for HR)', 'Center cockpit with the signature fixed glass windscreen + dodger', '420 L / 110 gal', '745 L / 196 gal', 14.45, 42.26, 13.78, 29200, 1.75, '~18.5', '~187', 420, 745, 75, 800000, 1100000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want the most protected GRP helm afloat (that fixed windscreen) with legendary build and resale, and will buy lightly used.', 'HR''s trademark fixed, framed glass windscreen wraps the cockpit front; with the dodger it fully encloses the helm. A test reviewer called the protection "mind-blowing" — stand watch dry and warm. About as protected as you get short of a pilothouse.', 'Masthead/genoa sloop with a slightly-overlapping headsail (self-tacking jib optional), electric in-mast FatFurl main with full vertical battens, a Furlex under-deck jib furler and an integral bowsprit for a code zero; all lines hidden-led aft.', 'Engineered for two: electric/reversible self-tailing winches (the reviewer "giggled" at how easy they were), self-tacking jib option, all lines hidden-led aft, and light twin-rudder steering even reefed in 24 kt. Optional bow/stern thrusters with docking function.', 'Classic center-cockpit advantage: a dedicated engine room aft with genuine standing/kneeling access all around the Volvo D2-75. No separate workshop cabin, but deep lockers/lazarette give tool and bench space.', 'Watermaker universal on bluewater boats; diesel heating the norm; optional retractable bow/stern thrusters with docking function; lithium and solar common owner upgrades.', 'Extensive — large forward anchor locker, deep aft-deck lockers, big lazarette, two hanging lockers forward, a hidden coaming line box, and the big aft cabin''s own stowage.', '~600–800 nm motoring; large water tankage. Watermaker universally fitted on bluewater boats.', '2–3 cabins, 2 heads, big forward owner''s cabin + generous aft cabin, separate showers. High coamings keep dogs secure on deck, but high freeboard means dog boarding is via the fold-out transom platform / bow ladder.', 'Outstanding cold-water watchkeeping thanks to the windscreen + dodger; heavy, stiff (40% ballast), CE Cat A, legendary build and diesel-heating norms. Caveat: GRP with a 2.10 m fixed keel limits rock-anchorage flexibility (consider the 1.75 m shoal keel).', 'Very good — large water tankage, big shaded protected cockpit and excellent ventilation.', '$800k–$960k (used)', 'New base ~€758k (well over $1.1M optioned)', 'Used 2018–2020 ~$800k–$960k', 'Fits — a clean, well-equipped used HR 44 sits at or just under $1M ready-to-cruise.', 'HR 43/44-class boats are common in ARC and circumnavigation fleets; the "Sailing Breezy" couple document long two-handed cruising aboard their HR 44.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Fixed glass windscreen', 'Center cockpit', 'Twin rudders', 'Legendary resale']::text[], array['The fixed windscreen is the HR signature — no other production builder does it quite the same way.', 'The 44 is the first Hallberg-Rassy ever fitted with twin rudders.', 'A reviewer literally giggled at how easy the reversible electric winches made sailing.']::text[], array['New base ~€758k (well over $1.1M optioned)', '2019 examples ~$803k (Transworld) and ~$910k (Marine Lions)', '2020 ~$956k (Jonacor); UK "Shearwater" (2019) ~£570k (Berthon)']::text[], '[{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy","url":"https://www.hallberg-rassy.com"},{"name":"Yachting World video feature","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/video/hallberg-rassy-44-video-how-traditional-cruising-values-fit-with-a-new-hull-shape-107362"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing Breezy","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@SailingBreezy","note":"Couple cruising their own HR 44"},{"name":"YW handover walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8sHBAXiFU3M","note":"Sailing Breezy factory-handover episode"},{"name":"Yachting World — On Test: HR 44","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2bnSeyQPBW0","note":"Pip Hare two-day sea trial"},{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@hallberg-rassy","note":"Yard channel with HR 44 content"},{"name":"BoatTube — 2020 HR 44 walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wsLLjoucI8I","note":"Boot Düsseldorf deck/interior walkaround"},{"name":"TrulyBoating — new HR 44 tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gCbhSfWVzrU","note":"Boat-show walkaround of a new 44"},{"name":"sailmoto — HR 44 (2025)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YXGWXiLa3SI","note":"Recent detail walkaround"},{"name":"Transworld — 2023 HR 44 (Springtide)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o-iSTAYiiWA","note":"Dealer walkthrough with HR-agent commentary"},{"name":"Berthon — HR 44 (Shearwater)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aBFaWJjWGV8","note":"Full brokerage tour of a high-spec 44"},{"name":"Berthon — HR 44 (Carioca II)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V9Rj_JmQyAo","note":"Brokerage walkthrough"},{"name":"Yachting World — HR 40C review (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GaZ4Dnb_9wY","note":"Newest Frers HR — same twin-rudder design language"},{"name":"Sailing Milagro — HR 46 (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGgH97MQvcw","note":"Owner tour of the close sister with offshore upgrades"},{"name":"Sailing Windfinder — HR 48 Mk II (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=acGIka0qV0o","note":"Owner voyage on the larger Frers sister"},{"name":"BoatTube — HR 48 walkaround (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8sQKAfiMuB0","note":"Larger-sister boat-show walkaround"},{"name":"HR drone boat-yard tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ktwJp2U2oMI","note":"Build-quality / factory proxy for the range"},{"name":"The Boat Show — HR factory tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0k0xZIl8ZA0","note":"Independent build-quality feature"}]'::jsonb, array['The fixed glass windscreen + dodger is purpose-built for cold, wet high-latitude watches.', 'Engineered for an easy two-handed life: electric/reversible winches, self-tacking jib option, light twin-rudder helm.', 'Center cockpit = excellent walk-in-style engine access and a large secure aft cabin.', 'Legendary build quality and resale; fits comfortably under $1M used.']::text[], array['No dedicated workshop cabin (uses lockers/lazarette) — less workshop space than the Outbound or Garcia.', '2.10 m fixed deep keel + twin rudders limit shoal flexibility and add rock-grounding risk (consider the 1.75 m shoal keel).', 'High freeboard + transom platform — dog (and human) boarding isn''t effortless.', 'Fuel range under power (~600–800 nm) is good but not huge for long windless legs.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"SAIL Magazine","note":"\"Excellent build quality, center cockpit, balanced hull form for good seakeeping,\" now with Frers'' twin-rudder hull.","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/new-boats-hallberg-rassy-44/"},{"who":"Yachting World","note":"A \"serious step-change\" for the builder; comes alive downwind above ~15 knots.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/hallberg-rassy-44-review-from-the-archive"},{"who":"Andy Schell · 59 North (philosophy)","note":"His offshore ideal — a seakindly Frers hull with an SA/D in the 15–18 \"sweet spot\" — is exactly this boat''s DNA.","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/cruising/the-perfect-offshore-boat-part-1/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (typical HR; unverified for the 44 specifically)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead-bulb keel (numerous stainless bolts) · twin spade rudders","complexity":"Moderate — conservative, robust factory systems (Volvo D2-75, bow thruster, in-mast furling main); less systems-dense than an Amel. A used boat''s complexity depends on owner add-ons.","maintain":"Good — conventional, accessible, well-documented systems and a globally serviceable Volvo. Quality joinery can hide issues; owner-installed electrics vary, so survey carefully.","partsText":"Excellent — HR (Ellös, Sweden) is family-run, stable and in continuous production, with a dedicated worldwide parts subsidiary. Volvo D2-75 (global). Low parts risk.","problems":"Excellent build (''no real shortcomings''). Survey hotspots on used boats: deck-core moisture around fittings as bedding ages, rudder-bearing play/weeping, chainplate corrosion, keel bolts/grounding signs, stainless tank welds, and amateur owner-installed electrics.","sentiment":"A benchmark mid-size bluewater cruiser — ''competence, not spectacle'': build quality, solid-wood joinery, protected center cockpit, balanced seakeeping, strong resale. Few complaints.","communities":[{"name":"HR Owners Association (HROA)","url":"https://www.hroa.co.uk/"},{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy Club (worldwide)","url":"https://hr-club.net/"},{"name":"HR Sailing (Groups.io)","url":"https://groups.io/g/Hallberg-Rassy-Sailing"}],"risks":["Used boats: owner-installed electrical quality varies — survey carefully","A 44-ft center-cockpit boat is sizeable for one near-beginner (mitigated by the sheltered cockpit)","High acquisition cost"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":4,"parts":5,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('allures', 'Allures 45.9', 'Allures Yachting · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#2a6f6b', '2018–present', 'Aluminium hull / GRP deck', 'Aluminium expedition', 'Aft (canvas / optional hardtop)', '48''4" (14.75 m)', '~45'' (13.70 m)', '14''6" (4.43 m)', '3''6" (1.06 m) up', '9''6" (2.90 m) down', '~12,600 kg / 27,800 lb', '~4,780 kg lead', '~38%', '~996 ft²', '~63'' (ICW)', 'Volvo D2-60 (75 opt)', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Lifting board over a weight-bearing stub keel (can take the ground); twin rudders; round-bilge alu hull', 'Aft cockpit with high coamings and inboard genoa winches; sprayhood/optional hardtop', '625 L / 165 gal', '420 L / 111 gal', 14.75, 44.95, 14.53, 27800, 1.06, '~18', '~136', 625, 420, 60, 590000, 1000000, 'fit', 1, 'The budget-savvy couple who want aluminium expedition capability and a real workshop layout for the lowest entry price of the group.', 'Higher coamings than a typical Med cruiser and inboard winches give a protected, secure aft helming zone — but weather protection is canvas (sprayhood/bimini) rather than a hard doghouse, so it''s less sheltered than the Ovni or Boréal for cold watches.', 'Double-headed sloop — furling genoa + inner staysail — with an anchor bowsprit for an asymmetric; the staysail behaves nearly self-tacking; electric winches/powered furling are common, recommended options.', 'Double-headed sloop; a reviewer found "a singlehander can tend all the controls and a crew of two will find it especially easy." Hydraulic push-button board. Electric winches/powered furling are common, recommended options for a smaller crew. Watch-out: few handholds forward.', 'The two-cabin "owner" layout turns the aft third cabin into a dedicated technical room / workshop with standing space and stowage — prized by long-term cruising couples.', 'Stern arch for solar/wind/radar; lithium, watermaker and diesel heating are typical bluewater fit; the composite deck stays cooler and drier than all-aluminium.', 'Cavernous in the owner''s layout — the unused third cabin becomes a huge hold for spare sails, food and parts, plus big cockpit line lockers and a stern arch for solar/wind.', '~700–900+ nm motoring; smaller tanks than the Ovni 490. Watermaker a near-universal bluewater fit.', 'Usually 2 cabins / 2 heads (workshop replaces cabin three); raised saloon with great light, a real nav station and a secure sea-going galley. Flat walkable deck suits dogs; the workshop/hold doubles as dog/gear space — but handholds forward are sparse.', 'Strong — aluminium hull shrugs off ice and rock, the lifting board lets you tuck into shallow rocky Patagonian coves, and the standard centreboard version can dry out. (The lighter "45.9 S" swing-keel variant can''t dry out — choose the standard boat for high latitudes.)', 'Equally strong — 1.06 m board-up draft for reef anchorages, 63 ft air draft clears ICW bridges, and the GRP deck stays cooler and drier than an all-aluminium one.', '$590k–$1.0M', '45.9 S fully outfitted ~€1,000,000', 'Used 2018–2019 ~€550k–€590k (~$590k–$640k)', 'Comfortable fit — a clean used standard 45.9, refit for cruising, sits well under $1M.', '"A Capella of Belfast" (Atlantic→Pacific two-handed); "Loly" on the Grand Large World Odyssey circumnavigation.', '{"protection":3,"handling":4,"dogs":4,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Aluminium + GRP deck', 'Lifting board', 'Workshop layout', 'Best budget fit']::text[], array['Unusual hybrid build: a welded aluminium hull but a composite deck — quieter and less condensation-prone than all-metal.', '"A Capella of Belfast" sailed one across the Pacific via the Galápagos, French Polynesia and Tonga — this couple''s exact dream route.', 'Allures runs its own owner circumnavigation rally, the World Odyssey.']::text[], array['New base ~$462k (2018); 45.9 S fully outfitted ~€1,000,000', '2019 two-cabin, Martinique — €550,000', '2019 three-cabin, Bretagne Sud — €590,000; 2018, Bremerhaven — €575,000 ex-VAT']::text[], '[{"name":"Allures Yachting","url":"https://www.allures.com/en/models/allures-45-9/"},{"name":"SAIL review","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/boat-review-allures-45-9/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"SV Tonic","url":"https://www.youtube.com/c/svtonicboatwives/videos","note":"Review channel with Allures 45.9 content"},{"name":"Allures Yachting (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@AlluresYachting","note":"Model walkthroughs incl. 45.9"},{"name":"Guided tour (English)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S0zEFWVJ53E","note":"Choose Your Boat narrated tour"},{"name":"360° tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CSdP9Qr2AtE","note":"Seakeeping/safety/shorthanded focus"}]'::jsonb, array['Aluminium hull + lifting board = ideal for rock-strewn Patagonia and reef-strewn tropics alike; the standard boat can dry out.', 'Easy short-handed handling praised by reviewers; electric options suit a smaller crew.', 'Two-cabin owner layout delivers a real workshop + cavernous stowage.', 'GRP deck = cooler, drier, quieter living; best budget fit of the whole group.']::text[], array['No hard pilothouse/doghouse — protection is canvas, materially less sheltered than the Ovni for cold watches.', 'Smaller fuel (625 L) and water (420 L) than the Ovni/Oyster — shorter range/autonomy.', 'Sparse handholds forward of the mast — a real consideration for a smaller crew and for dogs.', 'The lighter/faster "S" variant loses dry-out ability — insist on the standard centreboard boat.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Sailing Zingaro (James Evenson)","note":"Puts the Allures 44 (sister/predecessor) at the top of his best-bluewater-sailboats-under-$300K list.","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-9nFISFFhU"},{"who":"Jimmy Cornell (brand)","note":"Recommends Allures as an entry point into aluminium centreboarders before stepping up to Garcia/Boréal.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/features/jimmy-cornell-aluminium-centreboarders-explorer-yachts-128465"},{"who":"SAIL Magazine","note":"Praises the near-unique recipe — aluminium round-bilge hull, composite deck, centreboard and twin rudders on one boat.","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/boat-review-allures-45-9/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped","keelRudder":"Integral centreboard OR ballasted lifting keel, encapsulated ballast (no bolt-on external keel) · twin rudders","complexity":"Moderate — pragmatic Solent rig (easy sail changes), winches by the helm, raw-aluminium hull (no topcoat upkeep); scales with options. Galvanic management + the alloy/GRP join to watch.","maintain":"Shorthanded-friendly, accessible systems, no-upkeep raw-alloy hull; tanks under the sole accessible. Alloy repair, keel/board internals & the hull-to-deck interface are specialist.","partsText":"Active, well-backed (Grand Large Yachting group + refit division). Mainstream engine/steering. Low–moderate parts risk.","problems":"No systemic defect; minor finish lapses noted. Type watch items: lifting keel/board mechanism inspection (some yard-only), galvanic vigilance, the alloy-hull/GRP-deck join and rig base.","sentiment":"Positive — a hugely practical, dry-out-capable, shoal-draft cruiser whose raw-alloy hull needs no cosmetic upkeep; comfortable and easy shorthanded. Trade-offs: looks, price, alloy care.","communities":[{"name":"Allures–Garcia Owners forum","url":"https://alluresgarciaowners.discussion.community/"},{"name":"Sailing Anarchy thread","url":"https://forums.sailinganarchy.com/threads/allures-45-9s.246970/"}],"risks":["Aluminium galvanic/corrosion management required","Lifting keel/board mechanism needs regular inspection (some yard-only)","Dissimilar materials (alloy hull + GRP deck) — watch the join","Choose the standard centreboard, not the ''S'' swing-keel, to keep dry-out ability"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3.5,"parts":4,"community":3.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('amel', 'Amel 50', 'Chantiers Amel · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#1b4f72', '2017–~2021', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + enclosed hardtop', '54''1" (16.50 m)', '47''6" (14.50 m)', '15''7" (4.79 m)', '7''1" (2.15 m fixed)', '7''1" (2.15 m fixed)', '18,750 kg light / 22,200 kg loaded', '5,360 kg', '~29%', '126 m² / 1,356 ft²', '~22.5 m / 74''', 'Volvo 110 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Fixed fin keel with bulb; twin rudders; watertight bulkheads', 'Center cockpit with a rigid hardtop shelter, opening sunroof and wraparound glazing', '~660 L / 175 gal', '600 L / 159 gal', 16.5, 47.57, 15.71, 45000, 2.15, '~18–20', '~171', 660, 600, 110, 900000, 1750000, 'tight', 2, 'The couple who prioritise effortless push-button sailing and an enclosed center cockpit above shoal-draft/aluminium expedition ability.', 'Among the best-protected production cockpits afloat — the helm and crew sit deep inside an integrated hard shelter, sealed from wind, spray, sun and cold; the boat can be managed almost entirely from the deckhouse. Superb for both Patagonian cold and tropical sun.', 'Masthead sloop (optional cutter/staysail); electric in-mast main furling, electric genoa (and optional staysail) furling, and powerful electric winches — set/reef/trim by button; bow thruster standard.', 'The Amel hallmark: electric in-mast main furling, electric genoa furling, and powerful electric winches — set, reef and trim everything at the push of a button from the protected cockpit. Bow thruster standard. The easiest boat here for a smaller/less-strong crew.', 'Class-leading: the cockpit sole lifts to a dedicated, watertight, insulated walk-in engine room with full standing access all around the engine, genset and systems — plus room for tools and spares.', 'Watermaker effectively standard; generator, A/C, heating and a big house bank — a fully integrated turnkey systems boat designed to run itself for a couple.', 'Very generous — deep cockpit lockers, large lazarette, cavernous bilge stowage and abundant interior lockers; designed for long-term liveaboard provisioning.', '~800–1,000+ nm motoring (owners report ~1,000 nm in calm); watermaker effectively standard for this role.', '3 cabins / 2 heads, aft owner''s suite with island berth, handrails everywhere. Big, climate-controllable interior — comfortable hot or cold. But high freeboard makes dog boarding harder; getting dogs down into the center cockpit needs a ramp/sling routine.', 'Strongly all-climate for comfort — enclosed hard cockpit, watertight bulkheads and heating make it genuinely livable in the cold. But GRP and a fixed 2.15 m keel limit gunkholing and make a rock grounding more consequential than on an aluminium centreboarder.', 'Excellent — full glazing with shade, sunroof, good ventilation and easy push-button sailing in the trades.', '$900k–$1.75M (used)', 'New was ~€0.9–1.2M fully outfitted', 'Used ~$900k–$1.0M for early 2017–2019 boats, up to ~$1.3–1.75M for newer/loaded', 'Tight — a well-found 2017–2019 example can be found at or just under $1M, but many are above. Careful shopping required.', 'Hugely popular with two-handed circumnavigators; "Sailing Amazing Grace" cruise hull #100 worldwide.', '{"protection":5,"handling":5,"dogs":2.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4,"highlat":3,"tropical":5,"budget":2.5}'::jsonb, array['Enclosed center cockpit', 'Push-button sailing', 'Walk-in engine room', 'Couple''s classic']::text[], array['Famous for letting a couple sail a 54-footer almost entirely by button.', 'The cockpit sole lifts up to reveal a stand-up watertight engine room.', 'Heir to the legendary Amel Super Maramu, an icon among circumnavigating couples.']::text[], array['New was ~€0.9M–€1.2M fully outfitted', '2019 examples advertised ~$950k … up to ~$1.75M for loaded boats', 'Brokerage spread roughly £718k–£1.3M']::text[], '[{"name":"Amel","url":"https://amel.fr/en/our-yachts/amel-50/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/amel-50/"},{"name":"Yachting World review","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/boat-test/amel-50-review-120818"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing Amazing Grace","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@SailingAmazingGrace","note":"Owners of Amel 50 hull #100"},{"name":"Sailing Talia","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TrBuYCZdSQ0","note":"Owners sailing a new Amel 50"},{"name":"Amel (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCYAbSsQcVxNKUHZyBOtCx2Q","note":"Builder walkthroughs"},{"name":"20-min private tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wMjCs4pDtyI","note":"Boatscopy detailed walkthrough"},{"name":"\"Only true single-handed bluewater boat?\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lvb-9gvgiQM","note":"Review of the couple-friendly systems"}]'::jsonb, array['Best-in-class enclosed center cockpit — a fully sheltered helm for cold Patagonia and hot tropics alike.', 'All-electric furling and winches mean a smaller/less-strong crew can sail it almost button-only.', 'Walk-in watertight engine room with superb access and space for tools/spares.', 'Huge stowage and a comfortable, secure liveaboard interior; proven couple''s ocean boat.']::text[], array['GRP hull + fixed 2.15 m keel: less suited to rock/ice contact and shallow gunkholing than the aluminium boats.', 'Fixed deep draft limits access to thin-water anchorages.', 'Mostly at/above budget — getting one fully outfitted under $1M is tight.', 'High freeboard makes dog boarding harder (needs a ramp/sling), and it leans heavily on electric systems.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2018']::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (Toby Hodges)","note":"\"These French bluewater cruisers are like no others on the market\" — sails well and handled comfortably shorthanded.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/boat-test/amel-50-review-120818"},{"who":"Sailing SV Delos","note":"Circumnavigated ~13 years on an Amel Super Maramu, crediting it as a secure shorthanded ocean boat.","url":"https://svdelos.com/sailing-travel-blog/amel-super-maramu-2000-sailing-sv-delos/"},{"who":"Sailing Zingaro (James Evenson)","note":"Features the Amel Super Maramu as a benchmark sub-$300K bluewater boat.","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-9nFISFFhU"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2018', '{"mastStep":"n/a (unverified) — robust offshore alloy rig with electric in-mast furling","keelRudder":"Bolted-on cast-iron ballast keel · twin balanced spade rudders (with an inspection port)","complexity":"High — electric in-mast main + twin electric headsail furlers, powered winches, retractable bow thruster, genset, watermaker, A/C, washer/dryer, dishwasher, 24V system, single-through-hull ''sea chest.''","maintain":"Mixed — an outstanding stand-up engine room (lift the cockpit-table floor) and the sea-chest make leak isolation simple; but the many integrated, proprietary systems are the burden — deep work wants Amel-trained techs/factory parts. Day-to-day operation is genuinely easy.","partsText":"Active — Amel (La Rochelle), owned by Groupe Beneteau since 2017 (strong backing). Mainstream Volvo engine + conventional shaft. Amel-specific furling/sea-chest/joinery are proprietary via the yard. Moderate parts risk.","problems":"Limited long-term data (since 2017). Watch: in-mast furling drum-bearing flushing and foil drive-bolt wear with frequent furling; furling-motor issues in owner threads; the iron keel is a deliberate righting-moment/corrosion trade-off; motorsailer-like, so engine hours accrue.","sentiment":"Rated a superbly built, genuinely ocean-ready ''complete package'' run from a sheltered enclosed helm. Downsides: expensive, heavy in light air, and the enclosed helm isolates the helmsman from conditions (some dislike this).","communities":[{"name":"Amel Owners Group (Groups.io)","url":"https://amelyachtowners.groups.io/g/main"},{"name":"Amel Owners Yacht School","url":"https://www.amelschool.com/"},{"name":"Amel Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/amelyachtowners/"}],"risks":["High systems complexity — many proprietary, integrated systems to learn and repair","Some maintenance needs Amel-trained service / factory spares (costly/slow when remote)","High purchase & running costs (offset by a strong owners'' community + the Amel owners'' school)"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('wauquiez', 'Wauquiez Pilot Saloon 48', 'Wauquiez · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#345a78', '2016–present', 'GRP (balsa-cored)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Pilothouse / deck saloon', '48''6" (14.77 m)', '41''10" (12.75 m)', '15''1" (4.61 m)', '5''11" (1.80 m shoal)', '7''9" (2.35 m deep)', '14,000 kg / 30,865 lb (light)', '3,900 kg cast iron', '~27%', '102 m² / 1,098 ft²', '~23.5 m / 77''', 'Yanmar 110 hp', 'Saildrive', '2–4 cabins / 2 heads', 'L-shaped keel with bulb (3 depth options); single spade rudder; twin wheels', 'True raised deck-saloon / pilothouse with inside steering capability + a sheltered twin-wheel cockpit', '650 L / 172 gal', '615 L / 162 gal', 14.77, 41.83, 15.12, 30865, 1.8, '~17.4', '~190', 650, 615, 110, 760000, 950000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a true heated pilothouse with inside steering and luxury joinery, and will accept thinner workshop/engine access.', 'A genuine heated pilothouse with big wraparound windows, near-360° views and an inside watch/steering station — keep watch warm and dry inside on cold passages. The compact outside cockpit sits behind deep coamings and the Wauquiez windshield, ideal for a full hard dodger.', 'Cutter-capable: genoa + optional self-tacking jib or staysail; in-mast (often electric) main furling; all lines led aft to oversized primaries at the twin wheels; bow thruster common.', 'Built around couple sailing: oversized primaries reachable from the wheels, all lines led aft, electric winches, optional self-tacking jib, in-mast (often electric) furling and a bow thruster. Arguably the easiest routine solo handling here — at the cost of in-mast furling trade-offs offshore.', 'A real gap for this mission: no dedicated workshop, and engine access (Yanmar 110 hp under the saloon sole) is only adequate, not class-leading. Aft space goes to cabins and a tender garage instead of a workbench.', 'Watermaker normal on cruising boats; A/C, diesel heating and lithium common; aft tender garage; Oyster-grade systems integration.', 'Stows "like a 50–55-footer" — long galley-corridor worktops and lockers, deep under-sole and settee stowage, and an aft tender garage that swallows the dinghy to keep decks clear.', '~700–900 nm motoring; less reserve than the Outbound/Oyster. Watermaker normal on cruising boats.', '2–4 cabins, 2 heads; Oyster-level joinery and a 5-star owner''s suite, lee-cloths fitted standard. The single-level raised saloon is comfortable, but high freeboard + a tall deckhouse make boarding two dogs more of a climb — plan a ramp/passerelle.', 'Excellent protection/comfort — a heated fully-glazed saloon with inside watch is purpose-made for cold, windy high latitudes. Watch-outs: a balsa-cored hull demands diligent impact/moisture care in ice-and-rock waters, and the iron keel needs corrosion management.', 'Those big windows + shoal-keel option suit the Caribbean/BVI/Polynesia, with A/C commonly fitted — but the tall deckhouse runs warm in the tropics without good shade.', '$140k–$950k', 'New PS48e is price-on-application — effectively over $1M outfitted', 'Modern used 2021–2022 ~€700k–€725k (~$760k–$790k); older Ed-Dubois-gen 48s ~$139k–$300k', 'Fits via the modern used market (~$760k–$790k). Beware: cheap listings are often the older, different Dubois-design 48.', 'Reputation as a quiet circumnavigator "seldom seen because they''re off cruising"; framed by reviewers alongside Oyster and Amel.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":3,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":4,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Heated pilothouse', 'Inside steering', 'Tender garage', 'Two generations exist']::text[], array['One of the few production boats this size with a true heated pilothouse and inside steering.', 'An aft "garage" swallows the dinghy so it''s not on davits or the foredeck.', 'Two completely different boats share the name: the modern Berret-Racoupeau (2016+) and the older Ed Dubois (1998–2008) — don''t confuse them.']::text[], array['New PS48e is price-on-application — effectively >$1M outfitted', '2021 modern PS48 — €723,000 (Denmark, Grabau International)', '2022 — ~€700,000 (France); older Ed-Dubois-gen 48s ~$139k–$300k']::text[], '[{"name":"Wauquiez","url":"https://www.wauquiez.com"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/pilot-saloon-48-wauquiez/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Malta Yachting — interior walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=amxeQdRccHY","note":"Full PS48 interior tour"},{"name":"PS48 2023 walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JBK8-NAAL5I","note":"Recent walk-through/promo tour"},{"name":"BoatTube — 2017 PS48 walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6IZbf7WFvKU","note":"Boat-show walk-around"},{"name":"Wauquiez 47 interior tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9U8230CttBQ","note":"Close sister model"}]'::jsonb, array['A heated, fully-glazed pilothouse with inside steering — the best cold-weather crew protection of any GRP boat here.', 'Easiest routine short-handing: self-tacking jib + in-mast furling + electric winches + bow thruster.', 'Superb storage volume (stows like a 50–55-footer) with Oyster-grade liveaboard comfort.', 'Modern used examples (~$760k–$790k) fit under budget with room to outfit; three keel depths to optimise.']::text[], array['No workshop and only adequate engine access — a real shortfall vs. this mission''s priorities.', 'Balsa-cored hull is a maintenance/impact concern for ice-and-rock high latitudes; iron keel needs corrosion care.', 'Tankage (650 L / 615 L) is smaller than the Outbound''s for very long ocean legs.', 'High freeboard + tall deckhouse make boarding two dogs a climb; rare boat with thinner support outside Europe.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World","note":"\"A genuine deck-saloon design… combining excellent sea-keeping with live-aboard comfort,\" small enough for a couple.","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/wauquiez-pilot-saloon-48/"},{"who":"No-Frills-Sailing","note":"\"Serious long-haul\" walkthrough praising it as \"the essence of Wauquiez yacht building.\"","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/wauquiez-48-pilot-saloon-walkthrough/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead fin keel (deep/standard/shoal options) · spade rudder · balsa-cored infused hull","complexity":"Moderate–High — a high-end performance cruiser with a single-handed-assist helm, raised-saloon glazing and a well-equipped, feature-rich modern fit-out.","maintain":"Moderate — mainstream European systems are serviceable, but the upmarket finish, deck-saloon glazing and proprietary joinery favour a yard for some work; older Dubois boats need more refit attention.","partsText":"Operating, part of a larger group. Two/three generations share the name (Dubois ~late-90s/early-2000s; Berret-Racoupeau ''48-2'' since 2016; 48e since 2023) — CONFIRM which you''re buying. Older Dubois boats are more likely to face discontinued parts.","problems":"Owner criticism (mostly on the smaller 40/41, applied cautiously): systems/rig teething on some boats, an ''Ikea-y'' finish, concern about thin deck laminate. Big saloon windows are an inherent heavy-weather liability. Generation confusion is itself a buyer risk.","sentiment":"Generally positive on performance, helm ergonomics, the light-filled saloon and bluewater capability; mixed on build/finish detail and some systems teething.","communities":[{"name":"YBW Wauquiez thread","url":"https://forums.ybw.com/threads/wauquiez.236292/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum (PS owner feedback)","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/wauquiez-40-and-41-pilot-saloon-owners-feedback-270999.html"}],"risks":["Confirm the generation (Dubois vs Berret-Racoupeau vs 48e) — they differ in hull, layout & parts","Large deck-saloon windows are a real heavy-weather exposure offshore","Higher complexity than a simplicity goal; a more scattered (not centralized) community"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":3,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('hr43', 'Hallberg-Rassy 43 Mk III', 'Hallberg-Rassy · Sweden', 'Germán Frers', '#2a6285', '2013–2016', 'GRP (cored)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + fixed windscreen', '44''6" (13.57 m)', '38''7" (11.75 m)', '13''5" (4.08 m)', '5''7" (1.70 m shoal)', '6''7" (2.00 m std)', '12,700 kg / 28,000 lb', '4,500 kg lead', '~35%', '110.2 m² / 1,186 ft²', '20.2 m / 66''4"', 'Volvo D2-75 (75 hp)', 'Shaft', '2 cabins / 2 heads', 'Long fin lead keel on a deep bilge stub with a skeg-hung rudder — protects the rudder for high-latitude grounding/ice-edge risk', 'Center cockpit with HR''s trademark fixed windscreen + hard dodger option', '395 L / 104 gal', '650 L / 172 gal', 13.57, 38.55, 13.39, 28000, 1.7, '~17.4', '~218', 395, 650, 75, 450000, 650000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want HR''s protected center-cockpit, fixed-windscreen formula at a used price well under a new 44.', 'HR''s signature: a fixed structural windscreen (the Mk III''s was restyled with rounded tops) plus a hard dodger option — a reviewer noted standing watch behind it would be "pleasant on a damp, breezy night." The wide wheel lets you sit either side for sightlines. One of the best-protected helms in its size.', 'Masthead sloop (cutter/staysail a common factory option); roller-furling genoa; full-batten slab main OR in-mast furling (the Mk III offered FatFurl roached furling main); overlapping genoa on tracks — not self-tacking.', 'Built for couples — "no one needs leave the cockpit to sail the boat properly." Double-ended mainsheet winches aft of the helm, genoa winches forward; electric primaries and optional REVO reversible winches; in-mast furling main; optional bow/stern thrusters with a docking function. Very manageable for a smaller crew.', 'Volvo D2-75 on a shaft drive (more reliable/serviceable offshore than a saildrive); the center-cockpit layout gives excellent standing access to the engine front from the companionway and the sides/back via the aft cabin. No dedicated workshop cabin at this size.', 'Factory Webasto diesel heating (HR is bred for cold northern waters) + an insulating cored hull. Solar/lithium/watermaker are common owner retrofits rather than 2013-era factory kit — favour a boat already so equipped.', 'Very good — deep cockpit lockers, a larger forward anchor locker and more watertight aft-deck lockers (Mk III improvements), plus HR''s abundant high-quality interior joinery and alcoves. Low tankage frees interior volume.', '~430–550 nm motoring (estimate) — modest; long ocean gaps want deck jerry cans and a watermaker (rarely factory-fitted on these years).', 'Two cabins / two heads — forward V-berth with en-suite + a large aft owner''s cabin with en-suite stall shower; full sit-down nav station. A couple''s boat. High freeboard, solid bulwarks and the aft cabin make dog boarding from a dinghy/low dock awkward (plan a ramp), but bulwarks give dogs secure footing underway.', 'Excellent — center cockpit + fixed windscreen + hard dodger + standard Webasto heat + insulated cored hull + skeg-protected rudder + CE Cat A. Squarely the kind of boat that does well in the Chilean channels.', 'Strong — low-maintenance GRP with an anti-osmosis layer and a fixed lead keel; the insulation that keeps cold out tempers heat. Watch-outs: the deep 2.0 m standard keel limits thin-water gunkholing (favour the 1.70 m shoal version) and lots of teak means more UV upkeep.', '$450k–$650k (used)', 'New base was just under ~$600k; well-optioned ~$800k delivered', 'Mk III scarce, holds value: ~$450k–$650k+', 'Fits with margin — a used Mk III leaves budget for solar/lithium/watermaker upgrades. Hunt for a shoal-keel, well-equipped boat.', 'HR 43 center-cockpit boats have circumnavigated (incl. a Swedish family with two kids aboard); Leon Schulz/Reginasailing built his ocean sail-training around the HR 43/46.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4,"dogs":3,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['Fixed glass windscreen', 'Center cockpit', 'Predecessor to the 44', 'Strong resale']::text[], array['The aft pulpit has built-in stainless "rail seats" — a reviewer''s favourite downwind perch.', 'Mk III brought 27 documented improvements over the Mk II, including four hull windows and a retractable companionway washboard.', 'HR''s low-profile mushroom vents have built-in ping-pong balls to stop downflooding — charming and very seaworthy.']::text[], array['New base just under ~$600k; well-optioned ~$800k delivered', '2016 Mk III, Lagos, Portugal — ~$510k (Båtagent)', 'Most cheap 43s listed are the earlier Mk I/II (~$340k–$450k) — the Mk III commands a premium']::text[], '[{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy 43 Mk III","url":"https://www.hallberg-rassy.com/yachts/previous-models/hallberg-rassy-43-mk-iii"},{"name":"Cruising World review","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/hallberg-rassy-43/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Leon Schulz / Reginasailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@reginasailing","note":"HR specialist; two years sailing an HR 43"},{"name":"HR 43 and 46 side by side","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IAZkL434gPw","note":"On-water comparison"},{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@hallberg-rassy","note":"Mk III walkthroughs & feature demos"},{"name":"HR 57 full tour (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PaN63NYAos","note":"Build quality / layout philosophy proxy"},{"name":"HR 43 Mk III — GoPro walkthrough (No.193)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12g1LDkOKrY","note":"Full deck-and-interior GoPro tour of a specific Mk III"},{"name":"HR 43 Mk III — interior walk-through","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jg36C64Qz8w","note":"Hardtop version, twin aft berths + two settees"},{"name":"HR 43 Mk III — interior GoPro","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RC0scaE9gYE","note":"Interior GoPro tour of the Mk III"},{"name":"Sailing MAJA — classic HR ocean voyage (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MlFQ9fA9CVM","note":"Singlehanded Atlantic-bound owner voyage on a classic HR"},{"name":"Sailing Milagro — HR 46 (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGgH97MQvcw","note":"Contemporary sister, close in size/era, offshore-prepped"},{"name":"Sailing Windfinder — HR 48, North Sea (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=acGIka0qV0o","note":"Owner voyage on the next-size-up Frers sister"},{"name":"Sailing Windfinder — HR 48 to Allinge (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H52LGc1sYiM","note":"More owner-voyage footage on the 48 Mk II"},{"name":"Sail Cloudy Bay — HR 54 interior (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hT21wBoEmfk","note":"Owner interior tour of the larger sister"},{"name":"HR 50 galley/interior (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-9oGMbR6Hc","note":"Same build-era joinery detail"},{"name":"Clarke & Carter — HR 39 tour (HR family)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s968JMdGLzY","note":"Same-era HR brokerage walkthrough"},{"name":"HR drone boat-yard tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ktwJp2U2oMI","note":"Build-quality / factory proxy for the range"},{"name":"The Boat Show — HR factory tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0k0xZIl8ZA0","note":"Independent build-quality feature"}]'::jsonb, array['Center cockpit + HR''s fixed windscreen + hard dodger keeps the smaller crew member dry and warm on cold Patagonian watches.', 'Built for short-handed couples: all lines at the cockpit, electric/optional reversible winches and a furling main; optional thrusters with docking function.', 'Standard Webasto diesel heat + insulated cored hull = genuine cold-water capability while tempering tropical heat.', 'Generous water tankage and quality stowage, with offshore-friendly shaft-drive and excellent center-cockpit engine access.', 'True bluewater pedigree at a used price well under $1M — leaving margin for solar/lithium/watermaker upgrades.']::text[], array['Standard 2.0 m draft is deep for tropical thin water — prioritise a 1.70 m shoal-keel example.', 'High freeboard, bulwarks and a center-cockpit aft cabin make dog boarding from a dinghy/low dock awkward (plan a ramp).', 'No factory self-tacking jib (overlapping genoa) and the cockpit feels tight with more than two aboard.', 'Modest fuel/range (~430–550 nm) needs deck jerry cans and almost certainly a watermaker for big gaps.', 'Heavy teak inventory is high-maintenance under tropical UV; Mk III units are rare and command a premium.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World (\"Make Way for the Swedes\")","note":"Praised for its comfortable, singlehander-friendly cockpit and the yard''s renowned build quality.","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/hallberg-rassy-43-malo-41-najad-460-make-way-swedes/"},{"who":"YACHT (yacht.de)","note":"Exclusive test: \"surprisingly fast\" despite the long keel/half-skeg — a sturdy improvement on an already impressive design.","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/hallberg-rassy-43-mk-iii/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped (supported by a saloon compression post)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on external lead keel (stainless bolts) · balanced spade rudder","complexity":"Moderate (rises with options) — base boat conventional (mechanical steering, Volvo diesel); Mk III options add in-mast/in-boom furling, retractable bow+stern thrusters with auto-docking, reversible powered winches.","maintain":"Generally good — thoughtful, accessible HR installations; a big center-cockpit engine space; globally serviceable Volvo. Heavily-optioned boats (furling, thrusters, powered winches) raise specialist needs.","partsText":"Excellent — HR fully operational with a dedicated parts subsidiary (worldwide shipping + physical shop). Volvo D2-75 (global). Low parts risk.","problems":"No widespread structural defects. BOTY niggles: primary winches too close to the dodger, a low stern battery vent, throttle/shift can foul the wheel in reverse; pin the mast step. Type concerns: teak-over-cored deck ingress, in-mast furling jam risk, spade-rudder bearing wear.","sentiment":"Consistently high regard (the HR43 Mk II was CW''s 2003 Overall Boat of the Year): ''no flex, no groan,'' seakeeping/comfort over speed, a user-friendly deck, quality systems, great resale and factory support.","communities":[{"name":"HR Owners Association (HROA)","url":"https://www.hroa.co.uk/"},{"name":"Hallberg-Rassy Club (worldwide)","url":"https://hr-club.net/"},{"name":"HR Sailing (Groups.io)","url":"https://groups.io/g/Hallberg-Rassy-Sailing"}],"risks":["Deep 2.0 m standard draft limits thin-water gunkholing (a 0.30 m shoal option exists)","A fully-optioned example raises complexity/specialist needs — favour a simpler boat","Teak-over-cored deck is a known long-term liability on Orust boats"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":2.5,"parts":5,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('oyster', 'Oyster 495', 'Oyster Yachts · UK', 'Humphreys Yacht Design', '#2d5066', '2021–present', 'GRP (infused)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + sprayhood', '52''10" (16.10 m)', '46''10" (14.27 m)', '15''8" (4.77 m)', '6''0" (1.83 m shoal)', '7''6" (2.28 m std)', '21,000 kg / 46,297 lb', '6,645 kg', '~32%', '127.4 m² / 1,371 ft²', '~23.5 m / 77''', 'Yanmar 4JH110 (110 hp)', 'Saildrive', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Fin keel with lead bulb; twin rudders; fixed bowsprit', 'Center cockpit (semi-raised saloon), twin helms, sturdy sprayhood', '800 L / 211 gal', '600 L / 159 gal', 16.1, 46.82, 15.65, 46297, 1.83, '~17', '~201', 800, 600, 110, 1500000, 2000000, 'over', 3, 'The couple who want the most refined push-button bluewater boat with the biggest fuel tank — if budget were no object (it''s over $1M).', 'Protection is "perhaps Oyster''s best yet relative to size" — a big sprayhood with clear panels shelters the forward cockpit and the footwells suit standing at heel. But there''s no fixed glass windscreen/doghouse; the higher helms are more exposed, so most owners autopilot and retreat under the hood on cold watches.', 'Fractional sloop; electric (alloy rig) or hydraulic (carbon rig) in-mast furling, electric self-tailing winches by the helm, push-button furling and windlass; fixed bowsprit for downwind sails.', 'Marketed as one-person sailing: electric (or hydraulic) in-mast furling, electric self-tailing winches by the helm, push-button furling and windlass — a reviewer furled both sails and anchored single-handed. Helm feel is a touch heavy via the geared twin-rudder linkage.', 'Superb engine access — twin doors open to the centreline Yanmar 110 hp with all-round reach, genset behind its own door. But the 495 is too small for a dedicated workshop cabin; the passageway and lazarette substitute.', 'Optional ~100 L/h Dessalator watermaker, 8 kW genset, a big house bank and A/C; superb acoustic insulation. No standard wet/foul-weather locker.', 'Very generous — a cavernous full-beam lazarette, a forward sail locker, passageway stowage for freezer + washer, and cedar-lined wardrobes. Watch-out: no dedicated wet/foul-weather locker.', '~1,000+ nm motoring (≈6 L/h at 8.5 kt) — among the best here; optional 100 L/h watermaker.', '3 cabins / 2 heads, a standout full-beam aft owner''s stateroom (best-in-class at 50 ft). Integral fold-down boarding ladders and an electric cassette platform ease boarding, but high freeboard means dogs mostly live in the cockpit/saloon.', 'Capable (CE Cat A, robust infused build, forgiving hull) and Oysters do high latitudes — but cold-weather helm protection is canvas, not a windscreen, and there''s no standard wet locker, so you''d add a full enclosure and heating. Deepest fixed keel here.', 'Excellent — powerful trade-wind shape, big shaded cockpit, large tankage and strong systems integration.', '$1.5M–$2M', 'New base ~£1.25M ex-VAT (~$1.55–1.6M as-tested)', 'Used ~$2M (2022 example, Palma)', 'Over budget — new ~$1.5M+, used ~$2M. Included as a benchmark; it doesn''t fit the brief financially.', 'Hull #1 "Carpe Diem" did a Baltic/Med debut tour; 495s enter the Oyster World Rally circumnavigation program.', '{"protection":4,"handling":5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":5,"budget":1}'::jsonb, array['European YoY 2023', 'Push-button sailing', 'Biggest fuel', 'Over budget']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2023, with an aft owner''s suite reviewers call best-in-class at this length.', 'Olympic double-gold sailor Shirley Robertson has sailed and presented it.', '15 were sold before the boat even launched — but it sails well past this budget.']::text[], array['New base ~£1.25M ex-VAT (~$1.55–1.6M as-tested)', 'Carbon rig alone ~£140k; thrusters ~£40k', 'Used ~$2.0M (2022, Palma); UK ~£1,495,000 VAT-paid']::text[], '[{"name":"Oyster Yachts","url":"https://www.oysteryachts.com"},{"name":"Yachting World review","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/oyster-495-review-an-impressive-smaller-oyster"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Oyster Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@OysterYachts","note":"Builder channel"},{"name":"Oyster 495 — Extended Boat Tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qr2GB17ASQ","note":"Full official tour"},{"name":"Yachting World — On Test (200 miles)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3e-bld34ly4","note":"Toby Hodges 3-day sea trial"},{"name":"Sailing with Shirley Robertson","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lPXBEK4XA5o","note":"Olympic-sailor sea trial"},{"name":"£1.25M Yacht Tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Duki-zQ9ed0","note":"Detailed third-party full tour"}]'::jsonb, array['Best push-button short-handed handling here — furl both sails, anchor and dock single-handed.', 'Outstanding engine access and a cavernous full-beam lazarette for world-cruising stowage.', 'Largest fuel tankage (800 L) → ~1,000+ nm motoring range; superb full-beam owner''s stateroom.', 'Prestigious bluewater pedigree, Oyster World Rally network, European Yacht of the Year 2023.']::text[], array['Price is the dealbreaker: new ~$1.5M+, used ~$2M — well above the $1M budget.', 'No fixed windscreen/doghouse and no standard wet locker — gaps for cold, wet high-latitude cruising.', 'Deepest draft here (2.28 m std) — shoal keel needed for rock/shallow anchorages.', 'Heavier and less sail-powered — wants breeze, more motoring in light air; helm feel is geared and heavy.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2023']::text[], '[{"who":"European Yacht of the Year jury","note":"\"So reassuringly strong, so surprisingly quick in straight-line speed… so easy to handle and so, so comfortable.\"","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/news/news-stories/oyster-495-wins-european-yacht-of-the-year-2023/"},{"who":"Yachting World (Toby Hodges)","note":"\"A wonderfully designed and engineered luxury bluewater cruiser… consistent passage-making speeds in real voluminous comfort.\"","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/oyster-495-review-an-impressive-smaller-oyster"},{"who":"Sailing Zingaro (James Evenson)","note":"Features the Oyster 485 (his own former boat) as a top sub-$300K pick — \"comfortable on any point of sail.\"","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-9nFISFFhU"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2023', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Bolted-on fin/bulb keel · twin spade rudders","complexity":"High — bow thruster, electric winches, integrated Yanmar vessel-control, optional dishwasher/microwave/freezer, twin-rudder steering, full bluewater systems.","maintain":"Lower for a non-expert couple — good engine access (hatches all four sides) but designed around professional/yard support and Oyster''s owner-care model. Major work realistically needs a competent yard.","partsText":"Operating but with a turbulent history — Oyster Marine liquidated Feb 2018, bought by Richard Hadida and relaunched. Yanmar 4JH110 on a saildrive (good engine commonality). Oyster-proprietary fittings depend on continuing factory support; the brand has shown financial fragility before.","problems":"Brand context: the 2015 keel-loss of the Oyster 885 ''Polina Star III'' (capsized after a lamination/build error); Oyster overhauled its build process. That was the larger 885, NOT the 495 — but it''s central QA context. The 495 itself is well-reviewed with no fault pattern documented yet.","sentiment":"Owners/reviewers call the 495 solid, beautifully finished, easy to handle and capable — an EYOTY 2023 nominee and Oyster''s fastest seller. Brand sentiment carries lingering caution from 2018 and the keel incident.","communities":[{"name":"Oyster Owners Group","url":"https://www.oyster-owners.com/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/website-for-owners-of-an-oyster-197356.html"}],"risks":["High systems complexity & cost of ownership; reliance on specialist/yard support","Proprietary parts depend on a builder with a fragile financial track record","The brand''s historical keel-failure event (on a larger model) is worth understanding","Well over the $1M budget"],"scores":{"maintain":2,"simplicity":2,"parts":3,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('kraken', 'Kraken 44', 'Kraken Yachts', 'Kevin Dibley', '#3b4b5a', '2025–present (new)', 'GRP (Kevlar-reinforced)', 'Aft-cockpit bluewater', 'Aft (enclosable bimini)', '44''3" (13.52 m)', '40''9" (12.40 m)', '13''8" (4.20 m)', '5''10" (1.8 m fixed)', '5''10" (1.8 m fixed)', '15,400 kg / 34,000 lb (full)', '4,700 kg', '~40%', '114 m² / 1,227 ft²', '~20 m / 66''', 'Nanni 4.65 (59 hp) / Yanmar 4JH57', 'Shaft (or hybrid)', '2 cabins (+saloon) / 2 heads', 'Encapsulated "Zero Keel" (no keel bolts) + full-length skeg-hung "Alpha" rudder', 'Aft cockpit with a solid windscreen + fully enclosable bimini/screens', '600 L / 159 gal', '500 L / 132 gal', 13.52, 40.68, 13.78, 34000, 1.8, '~19', '~224', 600, 500, 59, 920000, 1000000, 'tight', 2, 'The couple who want a brand-new, collision-engineered boat with a walk-in engine room and turnkey spec — and can sit right at the budget ceiling.', 'Good for an aft-cockpit boat: a solid plexiglass/stainless windscreen plus a tubular bimini with removable panels and screens that fully enclose the cockpit. But it relies on a canvas enclosure rather than a hard doghouse — less inherently weatherproof than the Boréal or a pilothouse in sustained Patagonian cold.', 'Solent double-headsail rig (furling jib + reaching genoa), in-mast electric Seldén furling standard (slab main offered); all halyards/furling lines led aft; electric primary winches are an upgrade.', 'Designed so one person can set, furl, reef and trim from the cockpit: Solent twin-headsail rig, all lines led aft, in-mast electric furling standard. Note electric primary winches appear to be an upgrade on the 44 — budget for them to make it easy for a smaller crew.', 'A standout: a dedicated walk-in engine/machinery room with full standing access, a second access panel under the companionway, plus a dedicated tool cupboard and wet locker.', 'Full world-cruising spec standard: triple fuel-polishing, a 120 L/h watermaker, lithium/solar, tropical A/C and Webasto heating throughout.', 'Extensive — a watertight-bulkheaded fore-deck sail locker, double stern lazarettes, gas-strut drawers under the master berth, a wet locker and a tool cupboard.', '~700–1,000+ nm motoring (estimate); triple fuel-polishing standard, 120 L/h watermaker in full spec.', 'Sleeps 4 + 2, two heads in full spec. Side-deck boarding gates with ladders, a fold-out swim platform and high bulwarks with triple lifelines help dog boarding and on-deck safety. A/C and Webasto heating both standard in full spec.', 'Strong on safety — a Kevlar-reinforced stem, two sealed forward bulkheads, a grounding-protected encapsulated keel + skeg rudder, Cat A, heating and a full enclosure. But the fixed 1.8 m GRP keel can''t dry out, and GRP is more vulnerable to ice/rock abrasion than aluminium.', 'Excellent — standard tropical A/C, watermaker, full bimini/enclosure and good ventilation.', '~$920k–$950k (new)', '€850,000 incl. full world-cruising spec (~$920k–$950k)', 'None yet — first hulls launching late 2025/2026', 'Tight — base spec lands right at the ceiling; once delivered, commissioned and fully kitted it can edge over $1M.', 'Too new for owner expeditions on the 44; Kraken''s larger 50/58 are in active world cruising and the brand is endorsed by offshore authors.', '{"protection":3.5,"handling":4,"dogs":4,"workshop":5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":5,"budget":2.5}'::jsonb, array['Walk-in engine room', 'Zero Keel (no bolts)', 'Brand-new model', 'Full spec standard']::text[], array['The "Zero Keel" is moulded into the hull with no keel bolts — it can''t be lost in a grounding.', 'The "Alpha Rudder" runs on a stainless armature from hull to a grounding shoe and can be serviced afloat.', 'A brand-new 2025/26 design — you''d be an early adopter with little used-market or refit history yet.']::text[], array['New €850,000 including full world-cruising spec (~$920k–$950k)', 'No used market yet — first hulls launching late 2025/2026', 'Budget to land at or modestly above $1M once delivered & commissioned']::text[], '[{"name":"Kraken Yachts","url":"https://krakenyachts.com"},{"name":"Yachting World — Kraken 50 test","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/kraken-50-yacht-bluewater-cruiser"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Kraken Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@KrakenYachts","note":"Yard/build content across the range"},{"name":"What''s Kraken Sailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@whatskrakensailing","note":"Owner/cruising channel on a Kraken yacht"}]'::jsonb, array['Designed for safe short-handed ocean sailing; Solent rig + in-mast electric furling, handled from a protected cockpit.', 'Genuine walk-in engine room plus a dedicated tool cupboard — nails the workshop/engine-access wish.', 'Encapsulated keel + skeg rudder + Kevlar collision protection = exceptional grounding/impact safety.', 'Full world-cruising spec (heating, A/C, watermaker, lithium/solar) comes standard — close to ready-to-sail.']::text[], array['Brand-new, unproven model with essentially no owner track record or used market yet.', 'Price leaves little headroom under $1M once delivered and commissioned; electric primary winches look like an upgrade.', 'Fixed 1.8 m GRP keel can''t take the ground upright — less suited to drying rock anchorages.', 'Cockpit protection relies on canvas, not a hard doghouse — less shelter in sustained Patagonian cold.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (sister, Kraken 50)","note":"Calls the line \"a bluewater beast built to cruise,\" noting the integral Zero keel and full-length skeg-hung rudder.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/kraken-50-yacht-bluewater-cruiser"},{"who":"Dick Beaumont (Kraken founder)","note":"Frames the whole boat around systematically reducing risk — the bolt-free \"Zero keel\" that can''t part from the hull.","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/dick-beaumont-zero-keel-kraken/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"n/a (unverified; heavy, conservative offshore construction)","keelRudder":"''Zero Keel'' — ballast encapsulated/integral in the hull (no keel bolts) · long keel with a keel-hung rudder","complexity":"Moderate — the philosophy favours rugged simplicity over complexity (which suits the couple); but the 44''s specific systems are thin given how new it is.","maintain":"Good in principle (no keel bolts; conservative, robust systems; built to sail shorthanded long-distance) but UNPROVEN in the field and constrained by a very thin parts/support network.","partsText":"RED FLAG — a new, small, unproven builder; production in Turkey/Poland, sales in Gibraltar. The UK entity shows Companies House status ''Active proposal to strike off'' with an overdue filing (as researched) — diligence warranted. Very few 44s afloat = barely any parts/support track record.","problems":"Essentially no track record — too few boats and too little owner history to identify failure points. The encapsulated keel/keel-hung rudder are intended to eliminate common failure modes, but that''s a design claim, not proven service history.","sentiment":"Press reviews of larger Krakens (50/58/66) praise ruggedness and offshore intent; genuine independent owner sentiment for the 44 specifically is scarce.","communities":[{"name":"Kraken Yachts (official)","url":"https://krakenyachts.com/"},{"name":"Ocean Sailor (Kraken content)","url":"https://krakenyachts.com/oceansailor/news/"}],"risks":["New/unproven model & small builder","Current UK-entity strike-off proposal/overdue filing — financial/governance uncertainty","Weak/essentially no independent owner community","Parts & warranty continuity are genuine concerns if the company falters"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":2,"community":1}}'::jsonb),
  ('discovery55', 'Discovery 55', 'Discovery Yachts · UK', 'Ron Holland', '#244b74', '2000–2021', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + watch station', '54''8" (16.70 m)', '49''2" (15.00 m)', '15''8" (4.78 m)', '5''11" (1.80 m shoal)', '7''4" (2.23 m std)', '22,500 kg / 49,600 lb', '9,500 kg lead (~42%)', '~42%', '115 m² / 1,238 ft²', '~23.5 m / 77''', 'Yanmar 160 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2–3 heads', 'Moderate fin keel with lead bulb (low CG) + skeg-hung rudder; shoal option', 'Center cockpit with a deck-saloon coachroof + internal 270° watch station; sprayhood/bimini', '1,334 L / 352 gal', '1,008 L / 266 gal', 16.7, 49.21, 15.68, 49600, 1.8, '~15–17', '~186', 1334, 1008, 160, 475000, 870000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple wanting a turn-key, heavily-equipped British bluewater yacht with a true engine room and enclosed watch station for high-latitude-to-tropics voyaging.', 'Deep, well-protected center cockpit behind a substantial deck-saloon coachroof; standard sprayhood and big bimini. The internal watch-keeper''s station just inside the companionway gives a 270° view and lets crew stand watch under cover — a major cold/wet-weather advantage.', 'The "Discovery rig" — a masthead twin-headsail setup: a self-tacking blade jib inboard plus a large overlapping furling genoa, mainsail slab/stack-pack or optional in-mast. Twin headsails pole out for trade-wind running; also offered as a true cutter; all headsails furl.', 'Designed from the outset for a couple: electric primary winches standard, optional electric furling on main and headsails — "push-button sailing." The self-tacking jib makes upwind work effortless. Caveat: loads are high on a 22.5-tonne boat, so good winch discipline matters.', 'A real strength — the center-cockpit layout creates a large dedicated engine room beneath the cockpit sole with standing all-around access to the engine, generator and systems. A generous lazarette and technical spaces double as workshop/stowage.', 'Exceptionally high standard spec — diesel generator, heating, air-conditioning, electric winches and a washer/drier are fitted as standard; 300 L fridge/freezer. Watermakers, solar and lithium are common owner additions. Diesel hydronic heat suits high latitudes.', 'Abundant — deep bilges, a large lazarette, the dedicated engine room, a deep-fiddled galley and big hanging/locker volume throughout. Heavy displacement carries stores without overloading.', 'Among the largest tankage here — roughly 1,000+ nm under power; most boats add a watermaker on top.', '3 cabins / 2–3 heads, large aft owner''s suite, sleeps 6–7. High topsides (dry at sea but a longer climb aboard — plan a passerelle/steps and a dog ramp). Wide flat side decks, a secure cockpit, and a ship-like deck-saloon level give plenty of floor space for two dogs.', 'Excellent — heavy GRP hull, ~42% ballast, low-CG bulb keel, skeg-protected rudder, standard heating and the enclosed watch station suit Patagonia. Not metal, so extra care with ice/grounding; consider hull/cutwater protection.', 'Excellent — standard A/C, big tankage/watermaker, a trade-wind twin-headsail rig and a large fridge/freezer; many have done the ARC and World ARC.', '$475k–$870k', 'Out of production (2000–2021)', '~$475k–$640k for 2002–2010 boats; ~$700k–$870k for later/MkII examples', 'Comfortably under $1M fully outfitted — a lot of equipped, proven bluewater boat for the money.', 'The Discovery 55 fleet has collectively logged hundreds of thousands of bluewater miles; many have completed the ARC and World ARC circumnavigation rallies.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":4.5,"storage":5,"tankage":5,"highlat":4,"tropical":5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Twin-headsail rig', 'Watch station', 'Walk-in engine room', 'Huge tankage']::text[], array['The bespoke GN Espace galley cooker was designed specifically for Discovery as "the ultimate marine cooker."', 'Discovery kept 24-hour technical support and full build records for every hull, even decades on.', 'The watch station lets you stand watch in foul weather and still see the horizon on the lee side when heeled.']::text[], array['2004 Discovery 55 — £399,259, Montenegro (boats.com)', '2008 "Sylvia" — £430,000 + VAT (Berthon)', '2008 "Eupraxia" — £495,000 VAT paid (Berthon)', '2012 "Cool Cat" — €675,000 ex-VAT (Berthon)']::text[], '[{"name":"Discovery Yachts","url":"https://discoveryyachts.com/yachts/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/discovery-55/"},{"name":"boats.com review","url":"https://uk.boats.com/reviews/discovery-55-mkii-review-evolutionary-update/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Berthon — \"Merlyn III\" walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KqW5zy6y2bg","note":"Full Discovery 55 brokerage tour"},{"name":"Berthon — \"Saxon Blue\" walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7PphfAkseqg","note":"Updated-deck Discovery 55 tour"},{"name":"Berthon — \"Blue Harmony\" walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2yBijWaBEo","note":"Detailed walkthrough"},{"name":"Berthon — \"Kiloran\" (first MkII)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zLpoDXtqV88","note":"MkII-deck Discovery 55 tour"}]'::jsonb, array['Purpose-built for two-handed bluewater sailing: electric winches + self-tacking jib + optional electric furling for a smaller crew.', 'Enclosed internal watch-keeper''s station with a 270° view — invaluable in cold, wet Patagonian conditions.', 'A walk-in engine room with all-around access plus a large lazarette — ideal workshop/maintenance space.', 'The largest tankage here (1,334 L fuel / 1,008 L water) for long ocean legs.', 'Standard generator, heating, A/C and big freezer cover both cold and tropical extremes out of the box.']::text[], array['Complex, systems-heavy boat — more maintenance and cost than a simpler yacht.', 'GRP (not metal) hull means extra caution with ice and rock in Patagonia.', 'High freeboard makes dog and crew boarding harder; plan a passerelle/steps and a dog ramp.', 'High rig/winch loads on a 22.5-tonne boat — disciplined technique essential for the lighter crew member.', 'Out of production; parts/support depend on the (still-active) owner network and brokers.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"boats.com","note":"Designed \"to be easily handled by a bluewater cruising couple\" — a \"superlative blue water cruising yacht.\"","url":"https://uk.boats.com/reviews/discovery-55-mkii-review-evolutionary-update/"},{"who":"Distant Shores (Paul Shard)","note":"Benchmarked Discovery-tier offshore monohulls (Hallberg-Rassy, Oyster, Hylas) when choosing their ideal passagemaker.","url":"https://distantshores.ca/boatblog_files/distant-shores-3-criteria-for-the-around-the-world-sailboat.php"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (offshore-preferred)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead fin keel · skeg-hung rudder (one source says spade — verify per hull)","complexity":"High — a luxury liveaboard: deck saloon, twin-headsail rig, often in-mast/in-boom furling, genset, A/C, watermaker, washer/dishwasher, bow thruster, big electrical systems.","maintain":"Low–Moderate for a non-expert couple — a mainstream Yanmar + reasonable engine access, but dense optional systems and boat-specific spares now depend on a reconstituted builder. Realistically needs systems support.","partsText":"HIGH RISK / discontinuous — original Discovery Yachts into administration 2019, liquidation 2022; the legal entity was dissolved (struck off Dec 2024). Brand/IP/tooling acquired Sept 2024 by a new company. Generic engine/systems parts fine; boat-specific OEM spares/warranty disrupted across three corporate failures.","problems":"No single dominant structural defect; generally well built (balsa-cored topsides — survey moisture at fittings). Build quality improved over the run (later hulls preferred). The biggest risk is corporate, not structural.","sentiment":"Positive among a small owner base — ''a boat built for a job, blue-water cruising, and does it very well''; praised build quality and a large dry cockpit for liveaboard comfort. Favourable but thinly distributed (~52–55 hulls).","communities":[{"name":"SailNet owner thread","url":"https://sailnet.com/forums/boat-reviews/307778-discovery-55-a.html"},{"name":"Builder ''reDISCOVERY'' page","url":"https://discoveryyachts.com/rediscovered/"}],"risks":["Builder discontinuity — three corporate failures; original entity dissolved Dec 2024; OEM spares/warranty not guaranteed","Weak owner community — no dedicated active forum/association","High systems complexity beyond casual DIY","Cored hull/deck needs diligent moisture surveys","A heavy 55-footer is a lot of boat for a near-beginner"],"scores":{"maintain":2,"simplicity":2,"parts":2,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('contest50cs', 'Contest 50CS', 'Contest Yachts (Conyplex) · NL', 'Georg Nissen', '#2f5a72', '2006–2021 (classic)', 'GRP (infused)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + deck saloon', '49''2" (14.99 m)', '43''1" (13.13 m)', '15''0" (4.58 m)', '7''1" (2.15 m)', '7''1" (2.15 m)', '17,500 kg / 38,581 lb (light)', '6,100 kg (iron fin + lead bulb)', '~35%', '125 m² / 1,345 ft²', '23.55 m / 77''', '~110 hp diesel', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Fin keel with iron fin + lead bulb; single spade rudder; moderate-displacement performance-cruiser hull', 'Center cockpit with a raised deck-saloon coachroof; sprayhood/bimini', '564 L / 149 gal', '718 L / 190 gal', 14.99, 43.08, 15.03, 38581, 2.15, '~18.5', '~219', 564, 718, 110, 380000, 650000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple wanting a Lloyd''s-built, easy-handling Dutch deck-saloon center-cockpit cruiser with lively performance and top build quality, at a sub-$1M used price.', 'Center cockpit with the raised deck-saloon coachroof providing real shelter to the helm and crew; a deep, secure cockpit with high coamings. Sprayhood/dodger and bimini standard; well-protected, though less fully enclosed than a true pilothouse.', 'Sloop on a keel-stepped aluminium mast (carbon optional), 3 swept spreaders; furling genoa (106%), optional self-tacking jib; in-mast furling main commonly specified for short-handed ease (slab/stack-pack also offered).', 'A core Contest design goal — "an extremely easy yacht for a couple to handle." In-mast furling main + furling genoa (or self-tacking jib) and electric winches make it very manageable for a smaller/weaker crew, with high average passage speeds.', 'Center-cockpit layout yields a dedicated engine compartment under the cockpit with good all-round access to the engine and systems; aft lazarette and technical lockers provide stowage/workshop room — smaller than the Discovery''s walk-in room.', 'High-quality systems throughout; generator, hydronic diesel heating, watermaker and A/C are common (heating typical on Northern-European boats). Lithium upgrades common on refits.', 'Generous and well-engineered — deep bilges, a large aft lazarette, abundant lockers and galley stowage; the raised deck-saloon sole creates volume below.', '~600–900 nm motoring depending on revs — smaller fuel tankage than the Discovery, a key trade-off for big ocean legs.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads; light-filled deck saloon with panoramic windows; secure center cockpit; quality joinery. Lower freeboard than the Discovery eases boarding for dogs and a less-strong crew (a passerelle and dog ramp still recommended).', 'Good — Lloyd''s-certified, CE Cat A GRP build, heating commonly fitted, deck saloon for warm watch-keeping. But the fin/spade configuration (unprotected rudder) and GRP hull mean the same ice/grounding caution as the other GRP boats.', 'Excellent — deck-saloon ventilation, A/C, watermaker and an easy-handling rig suit the Caribbean/Polynesia; lighter displacement gives livelier light-air performance than the Discovery.', '$380k–$650k (used)', 'Classic out of production; all-new 2023 judel/vrolijk 50CS is ~€1.3M+ (over budget)', 'Classic used ~€350k–€600k (~$380k–$650k)', 'Comfortably under $1M for the classic (2006–2021). The desirable new-generation 50CS is well over budget.', 'Contest''s 50-foot center-cockpit boats are long-standing favourites among experienced Northern-European bluewater couples, sitting alongside the Contest 55CS/57CS that rival Oyster and Discovery.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4,"storage":4,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['Deck-saloon center cockpit', 'Lloyd''s-built', 'Easy for a couple', 'Great value used']::text[], array['The new-generation Contest 50CS won European Yacht of the Year 2022 (Luxury Cruiser).', 'Every Contest is built to Lloyd''s certification and vacuum-infused in Medemblik.', 'The new model offers integrated photovoltaic solar decking and an electric-propulsion option.']::text[], array['2006 Contest 50CS — ~€450,000 (YachtFocus, NL)', '2009 Contest 50CS — via De Valk Yacht Brokers (NL)', 'US-market listing ~$379,793 (YachtWorld)']::text[], '[{"name":"Contest Yachts","url":"https://www.contestyachts.co.uk/range/sailing-yachts/50cs/"},{"name":"Boat-Specs (classic)","url":"https://www.boat-specs.com/sailing/sailboats/conyplex/contest-50cs-standard"},{"name":"Yachting World first look","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/yachts-and-gear/first-look-contest-49cs-and-50cs-134892"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Contest 50CS — light-wind sailing","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ox3XEkM3IE","note":"Builder sailing film"},{"name":"Contest 50CS 2024 sea-trial","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oFxRMHdsGYw","note":"Walkthrough & sailing"},{"name":"De Valk Yacht Brokers","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@DeValkYachtBrokers","note":"Brokerage walkthroughs incl. Contest"},{"name":"Contest Yachts (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@ContestYachts","note":"Model films / factory"}]'::jsonb, array['Engineered specifically for easy two-handed sailing — in-mast furling + furling headsail + electric winches.', 'Center cockpit with a protective deck-saloon coachroof; a light, airy panoramic saloon for sheltered watch-keeping.', 'Outstanding Lloyd''s-certified Dutch build quality and CE Cat A ocean rating.', 'Lower freeboard / easier boarding (and a new-model bathing platform) — friendlier for dogs and a less-strong crew.', 'Center-cockpit engine compartment with good systems access; well-finished workshop/lazarette stowage.']::text[], array['Notably smaller fuel (564 L) and water (718 L) than the Discovery 55 — shorter motoring range.', 'Lower ballast ratio (~35%) and a fin/spade configuration — capable but less "tank-like"; the spade rudder is unprotected.', 'GRP hull — same ice/rock caution in high latitudes; not a metal hull.', 'The desirable new-generation 50CS is out of budget; you''re buying a 10–20-year-old boat — survey systems carefully.', 'Smaller dedicated engine space than the Discovery''s walk-in engine room.']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2022']::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World","note":"A \"luxurious bluewater cruiser\" and \"surprisingly good performer\" with modern underwater sections and a fully balanced rudder.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/contest-49cs-review-luxurious-bluewater-cruiser"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2022', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead-bulb fin keel · balanced spade rudder(s) (single vs twin varies — verify per hull)","complexity":"Moderate–High — a semi-custom luxury 50: electric/hydraulic furling & powered winches, thruster(s), genset, watermaker, modern digital switching (CZone/EmpirBus); the newest offers all-electric propulsion.","maintain":"Mixed — good service access (walk-in engine/genset space) and a DIY-friendly Volvo, but digital switching + powered/hydraulic handling aren''t casual DIY (need software/schematics/technician); major proprietary work points back to the Dutch yard.","partsText":"Active & healthy — Contest (Conyplex, est. 1959), a 3rd-gen family yard (EYOTY 2025 for the 63CS). Mainstream Volvo/Seldén/standard brands. Low for engine/mechanical; low–moderate for boat-specific proprietary items (single Dutch source).","problems":"Limited public failure history (current 50CS new, ~2022). High build quality (Lloyd''s-approved infusion). Survey focus for the class: spade-rudder bearing wear, the keel-stepped mast collar/keel bolts, and digital-switching/hydraulic-circuit condition/firmware.","sentiment":"Press rate Contest a trusted Dutch builder of quality semi-custom bluewater yachts; earlier-Contest owners report long successful passages. Little long-term liveaboard data on the new 50CS specifically.","communities":[{"name":"Contest Yacht Owners Club (CYOC)","url":"https://www.cyoc.nl/"},{"name":"CYOC (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/100696539981522"},{"name":"Contest community & events","url":"https://www.contestyachts.com/community"}],"risks":["Single-source proprietary support — one Dutch family yard (consider when cruising far from Europe)","Feature-rich/semi-custom (digital switching, powered handling) runs against a simplicity goal","Thin model-specific online community","Unprotected spade rudder(s) — more grounding-vulnerable","A large, pricey 50-footer to maintain short-handed"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":2.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('hylas48', 'Hylas 48 (H48)', 'Hylas Yachts · Taiwan', 'Bill Dixon', '#2c5e6e', '2018–present', 'GRP (solid hull)', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + raised coachroof', '48''0" (14.63 m)', '42''0" (12.80 m)', '14''6" (4.42 m)', '6''6" (1.98 m)', '6''6" (1.98 m)', '~16,040 kg / 35,360 lb (light)', '~5,950 kg lead', '~37%', '~1,091 ft² (100% FT)', '67''6" (63'' ICW)', 'Yanmar 75 hp turbo', 'Saildrive', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Moderate fin keel (lead) with a partial-skeg-hung rudder; watertight bulkheads fore and aft', 'Center cockpit with a pilothouse-style coachroof and high coamings', '1,100 L / 290 gal', '450 L / 119 gal', 14.63, 42, 14.5, 37000, 1.98, '~16–23', '~213', 1100, 450, 75, 350000, 700000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple wanting a current-production, systems-rich, factory-fresh center-cockpit ocean cruiser — if they can find a used one under budget.', 'Center cockpit (inherently drier/more protected than aft), with high coamings; engine controls, running-light and bilge-pump switches are at the helm/coaming so the crew need not go below underway. A dodger/bimini is standard fare; no fixed windscreen.', 'Selden aluminium masthead sloop/cutter (3 spreaders); carbon spar optional; electric Furlex genoa furler + a manual staysail off a reinforced foredeck plate; self-tacking jib option; in-mast furling, hydraulic backstay/vang optional.', 'Explicitly engineered for two: an easily-managed sail plan, electric headsail furling, optional self-tacking jib, end-boom sheeting and Jefa rod steering that keeps a big boat agile. SAIL noted "the sailplan, although generous, is easily managed by two."', 'Award-winning systems install (2019 SAIL "Best Systems"). The engine room is meticulously organised and accessible from multiple points, with color-coded labelled wiring/plumbing. The optional 3rd cabin can become a dedicated workshop/utility room. Saildrive is a maintenance item.', '24 V AGM bank; dual Racor fuel filtration with a 4-tank manifold allowing onboard fuel polishing; Raymarine Axiom MFD; optional Northern Lights genset. Strong factory systems reputation.', 'Generous for a 48; semi-custom so lockers can be specified; the optional utility cabin adds a gear room. Twin bow rollers, anchor-chain deck plate, saltwater washdown.', '~900–1,200+ nm motoring on a huge 290-gal tank — superb for Patagonian calms; but only 119 gal water, so a watermaker is effectively mandatory for crossings.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads; 6''4" saloon headroom; big pilothouse-style windows for light and warmth. Center cockpit + side decks workable for dogs and the deep cockpit well is secure, but the slightly steep companionway is a watch-out for an older dog (a ramp/gate helps). Aft master is private.', 'Strong — solid hull, watertight bulkheads fore and aft, partial-skeg rudder, heavy displacement, a protected center cockpit and big fuel for motoring through Patagonian calms. Caveats: modest water and a saildrive (cold-water/ice fouling risk).', 'Strong — large opening hatches/hull ports, good ventilation, a light interior; add awnings and lean on the watermaker.', '$350k–$700k (used)', 'New now well above $1M (test boat $846k in 2019)', 'Used ~$350k–$700k', 'Used H48s fit under $1M (new ones do not); the used pool is thin, and clean examples command top dollar.', 'Hylas has a long pedigree of circumnavigators and ARC participants; the H48 is positioned squarely as a couples'' world cruiser (David Walters Yachts is a leading dealer).', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4,"tankage":4,"highlat":4,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Center cockpit', 'Huge 290-gal fuel', 'Award-winning systems', 'Watertight bulkheads']::text[], array['Won 2019 Cruising World Boat of the Year (Full-Size Cruiser Under 48 ft) and SAIL "Best Systems."', 'A 4-tank fuel manifold lets you polish your own fuel at sea — a serious-cruiser touch.', 'His-and-hers overhead hatches over the master berth solve the too-cold/too-hot argument at night.']::text[], array['~$350,000 early H48 (Collection Yachts, Fort Lauderdale)', '~$525,000 (North Point Yacht Sales, Annapolis)', '~$699,900 low-hours late model (At Ease Yacht Sales, FL)']::text[], '[{"name":"Hylas Yachts","url":"https://www.hylasyachts.com"},{"name":"Boat-Specs","url":"https://www.boat-specs.com/sailing/sailboats/hylas-yachts/hylas-48"},{"name":"SAIL review","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/boat-review-hylas-48/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Hylas H48 walkthrough & review","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=56lHJZItigU","note":"2019 Boat of the Year tour"},{"name":"Chesapeake sailing on a 2019 H48","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3e_NRUXRU-8","note":"On-the-water footage"},{"name":"Hylas 49 walkthrough (sister)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nNqFhFSS8c0","note":"Closely related S&S model (Annapolis)"},{"name":"David Walters Yachts","url":"https://www.youtube.com/user/DavidWaltersYachts","note":"Hylas dealer channel"}]'::jsonb, array['Protected center cockpit with helm-mounted engine/light/pump controls — minimal going-below underway.', 'Built explicitly for two-handed sailing: electric furling, optional self-tacking jib, light Jefa rod steering.', 'Huge 290-gal fuel tankage = long motoring range for Patagonian calms and high-latitude legs.', 'Best-in-class, award-winning, accessible engine room and color-coded systems — a boon for a self-sufficient couple.', 'Watertight bulkheads fore and aft add real offshore peace of mind; optional 3rd cabin can be a workshop.']::text[], array['Saildrive (not shaft) — extra maintenance and a debris/cold-water consideration in ice-strewn high latitudes.', 'Only modest 119-gal water — a watermaker is effectively mandatory for crossings.', 'Few on the used market; clean examples command top dollar near/over budget.', 'Steep companionway and isolated aft master can be awkward for an older/less-mobile dog or smaller crew.', 'New boats are far above $1M; the used pool is thin.']::text[], array['Cruising World Boat of the Year 2019']::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World jury (Alvah Simon)","note":"Best Full-Size Cruiser Under 48 ft — the stainless work is \"incredible… so many things that reflect quality and attention to detail.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/2019-full-size-cruiser-under-48-feet-hylas-48/"},{"who":"SAIL Magazine","note":"Hand-laid glass, partial-skeg rudder and watertight bulkheads fore and aft \"to bring peace of mind to offshore cruisers.\"","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/boat-review-hylas-48/"},{"who":"John Kretschmer (brand)","note":"Hylas''s former head delivery captain lists earlier Hylas models among his recommended bluewater boats.","url":"https://www.practical-sailor.com/blog/the-best-sailboats-for-the-high-seas/"}]'::jsonb, 'CW BOTY 2019', '{"mastStep":"n/a (unverified; Seldén masthead rig, carbon optional)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead fin keel · rudder on a partial skeg · watertight collision bulkheads fore & aft","complexity":"Moderate–High — a cutter with self-tacking jib, electric headsail + in-mast main furling from the helm, electric winches, bow thruster, genset, 24V, saildrive. Powered handling is easy for two but adds dependency.","maintain":"Moderate — a mainstream Yanmar, off-the-shelf branded gear, famously tidy/accessible wiring (SAIL ''Best Systems''). The saildrive (specialist seal/diaphragm service, galvanic vigilance) and in-mast furling are the main specialist items.","partsText":"Good — a living brand (Queen Long Marine, Taiwan; Hylas International, FL); off-the-shelf branded hardware; Yanmar engine. Low parts risk (saildrive adds proprietary seals/anodes).","problems":"No systemic defect; reputation for heavy, solid, well-finished boats. Watch: saildrive (diaphragm interval, anodes/galvanic, seals), in-mast furling jamming if neglected, balsa-cored deck moisture at fittings.","sentiment":"Strongly positive — CW Boat of the Year 2019 + SAIL Best Boats; praised for build, stainless work, ventilation, stiff sea-kindly motion and quality wiring. An engaged, helpful owner forum.","communities":[{"name":"Hylas Owners Association","url":"https://www.hylasyachts.org/"},{"name":"Hylas Yacht Club","url":"https://www.hylasyachts.club/"},{"name":"Hylas Owners (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/71332985122/"}],"risks":["Saildrive — the main specialist item (haul-out diaphragm service, galvanic vigilance)","In-mast furling can jam if neglected","Moderate systems complexity (electric furling, genset, thruster, 24V)","A heavy 48-footer is still a lot of boat for a near-beginner"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2.5,"parts":4,"community":4.5}}'::jsonb),
  ('tayana48', 'Tayana 48 Deck Salon', 'Ta Yang · Taiwan', 'Robert Perry (deck: Rob Ladd)', '#3a5e72', '~2002–present', 'GRP (PVC-foam-cored)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Center + deck saloon', '48''0" (14.63 m)', '40''0" (12.19 m)', '14''6" (4.42 m)', '5''3" (1.60 m shoal)', '6''0" (1.83 m std)', '~15,650 kg / 34,500 lb', '~11,800 lb (lead/iron)', '~34%', '~1,048 ft² (cutter)', '~70'' (64'' ICW)', 'Yanmar ~62 hp', 'Shaft', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Moderate-displacement Perry hull, longer fin keel, skeg-hung rudder; raised deck-saloon coachroof; center cockpit', 'Center cockpit (drier, protected) with long comfortable seats; raised saloon coachroof', '454 L / 120 gal', '833 L / 220 gal', 14.63, 40, 14.5, 34500, 1.6, '~19.8', '~240', 454, 833, 62, 250000, 675000, 'fit', 1, 'The budget-conscious two-handed couple wanting a proven, shaft-driven, true-cutter bluewater cruiser with a warm panoramic saloon and big water tankage.', 'Center cockpit (drier, more protected), with long comfortable seats good for lying down and level helm seating. Watch-out: relatively low bow freeboard means a wet bow in steep seas (the cockpit itself stays well protected).', 'True cutter rig (inner forestay/staysail — excellent for short-handed heavy-weather sail reduction) with furling headsails; performance ~70 ft rig or ICW ~64 ft rig; optional running backstays on some.', 'The cutter rig is inherently short-hander-friendly — drop to the staysail in a blow without going far forward; furling headsails standard on most. Watch-out: the original cable-in-sleeve steering is "spongy" under load — many owners upgrade it; budget for steering improvements.', 'The engine sits under the galley/walk-through with access from a single side under the sinks, genset front-access through the companionway ladder — adequate but not the multi-point access of the H48. Semi-custom build means stowage/workshop nooks vary by hull.', 'Semi-custom and varies by hull/refit; many on the market carry modern refits (lithium, Victron, watermaker, solar, updated electronics). Original stainless water tanks are a known weak point — inspect/budget replacement.', 'Excellent — deep bilges; the DS version adds extra tankage and stowage below the raised sole; renowned Ta Yang teak joinery with abundant lockers and a large nav station. Limited clear deck for a hard dinghy (use davits/cradle).', '~600–800 nm motoring on 120 gal; the big ~220-gal water tankage is a real advantage for crossings with two people and two dogs.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads; bright airy raised saloon with wrap-around windows and a pilothouse feel — great for watch-keeping, warmth and keeping an eye on dogs. A separate master stall shower; secure center cockpit; swim platform/teak steps aft for boarding.', 'Strong on hull and rig — a heavy, foam-cored (insulating) hull, a true cutter for storm-sail reduction, skeg-hung rudder, shaft drive (no vulnerable saildrive), and a warm enclosed raised saloon. Watch-outs: a wet bow, modest fuel, and the spongy steering to address.', 'Excellent — a panoramic-but-shaded saloon, good ventilation, teak decks, and a shoal-draft option for Caribbean/Bahamas gunkholing; add awnings.', '$250k–$675k (used)', 'Still built semi-custom to order (new ~$1M+ fully outfitted)', 'Used ~$250k–$675k depending on year/refit', 'The value play — fully outfitted DS examples sit comfortably under $1M, often with modern lithium/solar refits already done.', 'Many Tayana 48s have circumnavigated; the related Bob Perry Tayana 47 is sailed worldwide by the YouTube family Sailing Nandji (with a dog aboard).', '{"protection":4,"handling":4,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":3.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4,"highlat":4,"tropical":4.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['True cutter rig', 'Big water tankage', 'Panoramic saloon', 'Great value']::text[], array['A PVC foam-cored hull (insulating and stiff) — unusual among heavy Taiwanese bluewater cruisers.', 'An exceptionally active owners'' group (TOG) is a genuine support network for parts and advice.', 'Designer Bob Perry can be (and has been) hired as a consultant — he knows the 47/48''s quirks intimately.']::text[], array['2007 Tayana 48 DS "Windward" — San Francisco/Grenada (Denison)', '2005 Tayana 48 DS "Temerity" — Fort Lauderdale (Collection Yachts)', '"Tutkum" — Preveza, Greece (1000 Ah lithium, watermaker, recent circumnavigation)']::text[], '[{"name":"Ta Yang / Tayana","url":"https://www.ta-yang.com"},{"name":"Sailboat-Cruising specs","url":"https://www.sailboat-cruising.com/Tayana-48-DS-Specs.html"},{"name":"Jordan Yachts review","url":"https://www.jordanyachts.com/2230"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"2005 Tayana 48 DS walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E8U6ksoQ4d0","note":"Ian Van Tuyl broker review/tour"},{"name":"Sailing Nandji (Tayana 47, family + dog)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKzcVZX2xM_kiOFWuGg-Phw","note":"Closest documented sister-design cruising example"},{"name":"Sailing Nandji — full boat tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mwGfWh3SIC8","note":"Tayana new-boat full tour"},{"name":"David Walters Yachts","url":"https://www.youtube.com/user/DavidWaltersYachts","note":"Tayana brokerage walkthroughs"}]'::jsonb, array['True cutter rig + furling = easy short-handed sail reduction without going forward in a blow.', 'Generous ~220-gal water tankage (rare at this size) — a major plus for crossings with two people and two dogs.', 'Warm, light, panoramic raised saloon — excellent for cold high latitudes and watch-keeping on the dogs.', 'Shaft drive (no saildrive) — simpler, more robust for ice-strewn high latitudes.', 'Strong value: fully outfitted DS examples sit comfortably under $1M, often with modern lithium/solar refits done.']::text[], array['Original cable-in-sleeve steering is "spongy" under load — inspect/upgrade for confident short-handed offshore.', 'Low bow freeboard = a wet bow in steep seas (the cockpit stays protected).', 'Original stainless water tanks prone to leaking welds — verify or budget replacement.', 'Only ~120 gal fuel — shorter motoring range than the Hylas; plan fuel stops for Patagonian calms.', 'Engine access is single-sided under the galley; limited clear deck for a hard dinghy.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Robert (Bob) Perry (designer)","note":"Calls the 47/48 a successful design \"still going strong with… serious offshore cruising.\"","url":"https://www.jordanyachts.com/2230"},{"who":"Jordan Yachts","note":"\"One of Bob Perry''s most successful production designs\" — a serious offshore sailor with quality teak joinery.","url":"https://www.jordanyachts.com/2230"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"n/a (likely keel-stepped — owners note mast leaks in driving rain; unverified)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on fin keel (standard/shoal) · skeg-hung rudder (robust, grounding-tolerant)","complexity":"Low–Moderate — a traditional, heavily-built cruiser; conventional systems, typically owner-specified to favour robust over high-tech.","maintain":"Good — traditional construction, a skeg rudder, conventional systems and a famously deep owner knowledge base make it DIY-friendly (though the age-related jobs below are labour-intensive).","partsText":"Ta Yang (Taiwan) — a long-established, well-regarded yard; semi-custom so parts vary boat-to-boat, but most systems are mainstream/serviceable. These are older used boats: availability depends on what each owner fitted.","problems":"Age-related, well-documented: (1) chainplates glassed into the hull suffer crevice corrosion/leaks — labour-intensive replacement; (2) teak-over-balsa decks can hide core rot at fastenings; (3) the early Tayana 47 had under-braced rudder posts (later retrofitted) — check early boats. Survey chainplates, deck core, rudder/skeg.","sentiment":"Owners call the hull/deck ''bombproof'' and praise construction quality, while candidly acknowledging the chainplate, teak-deck-core and mast-leak realities of an older Taiwanese cruiser.","communities":[{"name":"Tayana Owners Group (TOG)","url":"https://www.tognews.com/"},{"name":"TOG list archive","url":"https://www.ftp.tognews.com/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f137/tayana-48-1996-a-174243.html"}],"risks":["Older boats — condition is everything; budget for chainplate replacement and possible teak-deck/core repair","Check early-hull rudder-post bracing","Parts vary boat-to-boat (semi-custom, owner-specified)"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":4,"parts":3,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('moodyds54', 'Moody Decksaloon 54', 'Moody (HanseYachts) · Germany', 'Bill Dixon / Judel·Vrolijk', '#3b5a76', '2012–present', 'GRP (balsa-cored)', 'Deck-saloon & pilothouse', 'Single-level deck saloon', '56''3" (17.17 m)', '51''0" (15.55 m)', '17''0" (5.19 m)', '7''3" (2.22 m shoal)', '8''8" (2.69 m deep)', '~24,500 kg / 54,000 lb', '~6,700 kg', '~27%', '142 m² / 1,528 ft²', '~25 m / 82''', 'Volvo D3 ~150 hp', 'Shaft', '3–4 cabins / 3 heads', 'Fin keel with bulb + spade rudder; deep or shoal cast-iron keel; bow & stern thrusters standard', 'Single-level deck saloon: cockpit and main saloon on ONE level via sliding glass doors; inside steering/nav; retractable bimini', '522 L / 138 gal', '790 L / 209 gal', 17.17, 51, 17.03, 54000, 2.22, '~15–17', '~180', 522, 790, 150, 650000, 950000, 'fit', 1, 'The cruising couple who want a catamaran-style, single-level, glass-walled bluewater monohull where dogs and a less-mobile crew never face a companionway ladder.', 'Exceptional. A large single-level cockpit shares one level with the saloon via sliding glass doors, closed off in bad weather by a retractable bimini; substantial bulwarks and inboard/outboard handrails make the side decks "the most secure we''ve seen" (BOTY judges). Inside steering/nav keeps the watch warm and dry.', 'Fractional sloop on a double-spreader Seldén spar; standard solent/twin-furler setup plus a self-tending staysail; in-mast furling main (with vertical battens) common; reaching Yankee and gennaker options.', 'Strong — a self-tacking staysail/jib, in-mast furling main and furling headsails mean almost no foredeck work; all lines led aft to Lewmar winches at the helms; electric winches and electric/hydraulic furling available; bow + stern thrusters for two-handed docking.', 'Engine under the saloon/cockpit sole; large under-sole and lazarette spaces give good machinery access, but the integrated "apartment afloat" fit-out means it''s an engine-behind-panels yacht more than a workshop boat. The big lazarette/garage is the most workshop-capable space.', 'CZone digital switching is the electrical hub; typically a genset, A/C/heating, watermaker, lithium/large house bank and full electronics; electric galley appliances throughout (a large power budget).', 'Abundant for a couple — high topsides create voluminous lower-deck stowage, deep lockers, and a big lazarette/garage aft (dinghy/toys/spares). The single-level layout frees floor area for living.', '~700–1,000+ nm motoring (fuel-dependent); moderate fuel for the longest legs, so plan fuel/jerry cans plus a watermaker.', 'The headline advantage: cockpit and main saloon are on ONE level via sliding glass doors — like a catamaran — so dogs and a less-mobile crew move between the sheltered saloon and the cockpit with NO companionway ladder, and reach the fold-down transom platform with minimal vertical movement. Only the sleeping cabins (and optionally the galley) need stairs.', 'Very good — an enclosed, heated deck saloon with all-around visibility is a major asset for cold Patagonia (keep watch and steer without exposure); Cat A hull, secure side decks. Watch-outs: extensive glass means more heat loss/condensation (good heating/insulation essential) and a big systems load.', 'Excellent — the retractable bimini and shaded saloon give superb sun protection; sliding doors + hatches give cross-ventilation; A/C typical; the swim platform and one-level living are perfect for anchorages.', '$650k–$950k (used)', 'New base well over $1M (~$1.1M+)', 'Used ~$650k–$950k (2013–2016 up to late, well-equipped)', 'A clean used DS54 fits under $1M; new is above budget. The single-level layout is its killer feature for this crew.', 'No single famous campaign, but the DS54 is widely chosen as a two-person liveaboard world-cruiser and is Moody''s flagship long-range deck-saloon model; owners cruise them transatlantic and in the Med/Caribbean.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":5,"workshop":3,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4}'::jsonb, array['Single-level living', 'No companionway ladder', 'Inside steering', 'Best for dogs']::text[], array['The deck-saloon concept revived a near-200-year-old British marque under German (Hanse) ownership — a Judel/Vrolijk hull wearing a Bill Dixon "lifestyle" deck.', 'A hydraulically folding transom becomes a beach-club swim platform.', 'BOTY judges singled out "the most secure side decks we''ve seen" and the genuinely livable one-level layout.']::text[], array['2016 Moody DS54 — US$949,000 (IVT Yacht Sales, San Diego)', '2013 DS54 "Genova" — Italy (YachtWorld)', '2022 DS54 "Dost" — Didim, Turkey (Next Generation Yachting)']::text[], '[{"name":"Moody (HanseYachts)","url":"https://www.hanseyachtsag.com/moody/us/yachts/moody-ds54/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/moody-54-ds/"},{"name":"Cruising World review","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/moody-ds-54-boat-review/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Moody yard — official guided tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FjPT70UhfVk","note":"Builder walkthrough"},{"name":"Boot Düsseldorf walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YJ1WvAzZ6RY","note":"BoatTube show walkaround"},{"name":"IVT 2016 DS54 walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bHMoTyA1jHY","note":"Detailed brokerage tour"},{"name":"2021 DS54 \"Easy\" owner walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fjtgjp9Zbvs","note":"Owner''s-eye tour"}]'::jsonb, array['Single-level saloon-to-cockpit living with sliding doors — outstanding for two dogs and a smaller/less-strong crew (no ladder, eye-level views, easy boarding).', 'Protected, heated inside steering/nav station with panoramic visibility — ideal for cold high-latitude watchkeeping.', 'Genuinely short-handed: self-tacking staysail, furling everything, all lines to the helm, bow+stern thrusters.', 'Huge, secure side decks and bulwarks; a very protected cockpit with retractable bimini for chill and sun alike.', 'Big lower-deck volume and a lazarette garage for storage, spares, dinghy and toys.']::text[], array['Moderate fuel tankage (~138 gal) limits motoring range for the longest crossings — plan fuel/jerry cans carefully.', 'Massive glazing means heat loss, condensation and big A/C/heating loads; insulation and a strong heater are mandatory for Chile.', 'Systems-heavy "apartment afloat" with electric galley and digital switching — more to maintain and a large power budget far from support.', '8''+ deep keel (shoal still 7''+) limits gunkholing; high windage from topsides affects close-quarters handling.', 'Engine/systems access is good but behind joinery — not a true walk-in workshop boat.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World","note":"Single-level living \"unmatched by any monohull of this size\" (though testers noted some slamming/tracking in a Force 7).","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/moody-54ds-boat-test"},{"who":"Yachting Monthly (Theo Stocker)","note":"One-level deck-saloon living tested on a real passage — a \"bluewater beast\" concept.","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/moody-ds-54-boat-review/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (tapered Seldén alloy)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on lead keel (shoal/deep) · single deep spade rudder · balsa-cored infused hull + carbon-reinforced grid","complexity":"High — electric Lewmar winches (trim from the helm), drop-down bow & stern thrusters with joystick, twin-helm steering, big deck-saloon glazing, a feature-rich production fit-out.","maintain":"Lower–Moderate — hardware is mainstream and dealer-supported (a plus), but the density of electric/hydraulic systems and the complex deck-saloon structure favour dealer/yard servicing for many tasks.","partsText":"Good — built by HanseYachts AG (Germany), a large operating production builder; shares hardware with the Hanse range (good commonality + a wide European dealer network). Volvo engine. (HanseYachts'' corporate finances have been volatile — note, but parts risk is far lower than the niche builders.)","problems":"No widespread documented DS54 fault pattern; reviews largely positive (the spade rudder was ''well up to the job''). Considerations: a single spade rudder is less grounding-tolerant; large saloon windows are an inherent heavy-weather exposure; many electrically-actuated systems are potential maintenance points.","sentiment":"Praised for close-winded performance for a big cruiser, helm-controlled electric trimming, safe single-level living and the deck-saloon ''superyacht'' feel and visibility.","communities":[{"name":"Moody (HanseYachts) official","url":"https://www.hanseyachtsag.com/moody/us/yachts/moody-ds54/"}],"risks":["High systems complexity — reliance on electric winches/thrusters and their upkeep","Large saloon windows are an offshore heavy-weather exposure","Single spade rudder is less forgiving in groundings","Weaker independent community than Oyster/Tayana (mostly builder/dealer-centred)"],"scores":{"maintain":2,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('najad460', 'Najad 460', 'Najad · Sweden', 'Judel/Vrolijk & Co.', '#1f5e7a', '~2000–2014', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center cockpit', '45''8" (13.95 m)', '39''0" (11.88 m)', '14''0" (4.28 m)', '6''2" (1.90 m shoal)', '7''1" (2.15 m std)', '15,500 kg / 34,171 lb', '~5,400 kg', '~35%', '99 m² / 1,066 ft²', '~19.8 m / 65''', 'Yanmar 96 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Center-cockpit fin keel with ballast bulb + spade rudder (standard and shoal keels)', 'Deep, secure center cockpit with high coamings; sprayhood/bimini; running rigging led to the cockpit', '460 L / 122 gal', '565 L / 149 gal', 13.95, 38.98, 14.04, 34171, 1.9, '~16.3', '~258', 460, 565, 96, 115000, 410000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple wanting a proven, heavily-built Swedish center-cockpit bluewater cruiser with superb engine access and high-latitude pedigree, at a fraction of the Moody''s price.', 'Very good and traditional — a deep, secure center cockpit with high coamings, a large folding table, sprayhood and bimini, excellent visibility, and rigging led to the cockpit so sheets are reachable from the helm. The center-cockpit position keeps crew well inboard and protected in a seaway.', 'Cutter rig on a Seldén-type spar; in-mast furling main plus Furlex furling for both the high-clewed jib and a fixed inner staysail; supports the "Simbo rig" (twin headsails poled out) for trade-wind downwind sailing.', 'Very good for a traditional cruiser — the cutter rig gives easily managed, balanced sail combinations for heavy weather; furling main + twin furling headsails mean little foredeck work; sheets accessible from the helm; powered windlass standard. A touch more crew effort than a fully self-tacking boat.', 'A Najad/center-cockpit strength — the engine lives under the cockpit sole with genuinely good walk-around/standing access from the aft cabin passage, much better than most aft-cockpit boats. Quarter/aft lockers give real workshop and spares stowage. A true fix-it-yourself bluewater boat.', 'Built for self-sufficient ocean cruising — typically a diesel cabin heater, watermaker, generator, large house bank, refrigeration and full electronics on cruising-spec boats. Robust, conventional DC-centric systems are easier to service in remote ports.', 'Excellent — deep bilges and a heavy-displacement hull carry a full cruising payload; large lockers, under-berth and aft-cabin stowage; the center-cockpit layout creates a big, dry aft cabin plus generous lazarette space.', '~700–900 nm motoring at cruise; moderate tankage, so a watermaker and fuel planning are expected for long Pacific legs.', '3 cabins / 2 heads; a warm, ship-like satin-mahogany interior with a snug, secure feel for high latitudes. There IS a companionway ladder (cockpit-to-saloon) and a step down to the aft cabin — less convenient than the Moody for two dogs and a less-mobile crew — but the deep protected cockpit and solid handholds keep dogs secure underway.', 'Excellent — arguably the Najad''s home turf: a heavy, stiff, Cat A Swedish bluewater hull, a deep protected center cockpit, a warm insulated interior with diesel heating, and superb build quality. Main limitation vs. the Moody: watch is stood outside (no inside helm) in the cold.', 'Very good — the cutter rig and Simbo downwind setup suit trade-wind passages; sprayhood/bimini give shade. Heavier displacement means slightly slower light-air sailing, and the mahogany interior + teak deck need tropical care.', '$115k–$410k (used)', 'Out of production (Najad went bankrupt in 2011; brand survives)', 'Used ~$115k–$410k depending on year/condition/refit', 'Huge value — a fully-cruise-equipped example sits far under budget, freeing money for tankage, watermaker, heating and refit.', 'No single celebrity campaign, but Najads (incl. the 460) have a strong record of private circumnavigations and high-latitude voyaging; a staple of the Swedish/Northern-European bluewater fleet.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4,"dogs":3,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":4.5,"tropical":4,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Swedish bluewater build', 'Center cockpit', 'Great engine access', 'Best value']::text[], array['Built on Orust, Sweden — the same boatbuilding island as Hallberg-Rassy and Malö; Cruising World rated the Najad the best performer of the three in a head-to-head test.', 'Rebranded "Aphrodite 460" in 2008 — so identical boats appear under two names in brokerage listings.', 'Satin African-mahogany joinery, leather and Corian give a quietly luxurious cabin owners keep for decades.']::text[], array['Najad 460, Lisbon — ~$114,453 (Siroco Nautica)', 'Najad 460, Valencia — ~$161,274 (Marine Team)', 'Najad 460 (top of market), Abruzzo — ~$410,411 (Admiral Yachting)']::text[], '[{"name":"Najad","url":"https://najad.se/"},{"name":"SailboatData","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/najad-460/"},{"name":"Cruising World — Swedish test","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/hallberg-rassy-43-malo-41-najad-460-make-way-swedes/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Najad 490 owner tour (sister)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vvUlyprpDH0","note":"Closely related center-cockpit Najad"},{"name":"Sailing Naves — Najad 360 tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=puRbhvec7gM","note":"Najad bluewater boat tour"},{"name":"Najad 36 \"Aphrodite\" walkthrough","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6CA8lRPZK_Y","note":"Najad build-quality proxy"},{"name":"Cruising World","url":"https://www.youtube.com/cruisingworldmag","note":"Swedish-yard reviews"}]'::jsonb, array['World-class Swedish bluewater build (Cat A) with a stiff, bulb-keeled hull — proven in cold high-latitude waters.', 'Center-cockpit gives outstanding, near-walk-in engine access and a big, dry aft cabin — excellent for a maintenance-minded couple.', 'Cutter rig with furling main and twin furling headsails handles heavy weather and trade-wind downwind (Simbo) easily short-handed.', 'Deep, very protected cockpit kept well inboard; a warm, snug insulated interior with diesel heating.', 'Huge value: a fully-cruise-equipped example sits far under budget, freeing money for tankage, watermaker, heating and refit.']::text[], array['No single-level layout and no inside helm — there IS a companionway ladder, less ideal for two dogs and a less-strong crew than the Moody.', 'Moderate fuel (~122 gal) and water (~149 gal) for the longest ocean legs — budget for added tanks/bladders and a watermaker.', 'Out of production with a bankrupt original yard — proprietary parts can need sourcing (support continues under new ownership).', 'Galley is slightly small for the length, and reviewers flagged a lack of handholds in the heads.', 'Older boats may need teak-deck, rigging and systems refit; surveys essential.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Cruising World (\"Make Way for the Swedes\")","note":"A fast, seaworthy Judel/Vrolijk centre-cockpit cutter with a rigging layout that makes it \"a dream to sail singlehanded.\"","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/hallberg-rassy-43-malo-41-najad-460-make-way-swedes/"}]'::jsonb, '', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (offshore-preferred)","keelRudder":"Bolted-on external lead fin keel (stainless bolts) · semi-balanced rudder on a partial skeg","complexity":"Moderate–High as equipped — a cutter with in-mast + headsail/staysail furling, electric windlass, often genset/watermaker/A/C/heating/bow thruster. Core drivetrain (mechanical steering, Aqua Drive) is conventional.","maintain":"Good underlying serviceability — a ''nearly walk-in engine room'' and a DIY-friendly Yanmar. Offset by likely systems load and ownership discontinuity (proprietary/joinery spares take more effort than HR).","partsText":"DISCONTINUITY FLAG: original yard bankrupt 2011; the brand survives under Orust Quality Yachts (Hexiron), which bought back the Henån service yard and offers a support channel. Mainstream Yanmar engine. Moderate parts risk — better than a defunct brand, not as seamless as HR.","problems":"Well-built cored hull; no systemic structural failures. BOTY flags: AC breakers in a damp-prone locker, awkward DC fuses, gas-locker drainage (later enlarged), a small-ish galley, no handholds in the heads. Type: teak-over-cored deck ingress, in-mast furling jam risk, partial-skeg rudder-bearing wear.","sentiment":"Positive — CW judged the 460 the best performer of three Swedes (finer bow, Judel/Vrolijk lines), with impeccable handling under power, a standout engine room and an African-mahogany interior. Najads stay sought-after used for Orust quality.","communities":[{"name":"Najad Owners Association","url":"https://najad.co.uk/"},{"name":"Najad Owners Forum (FB)","url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/716904748491726"}],"risks":["Brand discontinuity — original builder bankrupt 2011 (brand survives; some proprietary spares take effort)","Likely systems-rich as equipped — favour a simpler, documented example","Deep ~2.15 m draft limits thin-water cruising","Smaller owner community than HR"],"scores":{"maintain":3.5,"simplicity":2.5,"parts":3,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('deerfoot50', 'Deerfoot 50', 'Lange and Sons (Port Townsend, WA, USA)', 'Steve & Linda Dashew', '#4A6B7C', '~1989–1991', 'Fibreglass (GRP over balsa core)', 'Aft-cockpit bluewater', 'Aft + hard dodger', '49''11" (15.21 m)', '~47''0" (14.33 m, est.)', '13''6" (4.11 m)', '7''10" (2.40 m)', '7''10" (2.40 m)', '~32,000 lb (~14,500 kg)', 'Lead keel (weight not published)', '~33%', '~1,150 sq ft (≈107 m², est.)', 'not published', '~72 hp diesel (Nanni/Mercedes OM606 on known hull — may be repower)', 'Inboard shaft, 3-blade fixed prop', '2', 'Fin keel, lead, bolted', 'Aft cockpit, wheel steering, hard dodger and targa bar', '~480 L (2 × 240 L stainless tanks, ~127 US gal)', '~600 L (~158 US gal)', 15.21, 47, 13.5, 32000, 2.4, '~18', '~140', 480, 600, 72, 150000, 280000, 'fit', 1, 'Experienced bluewater couples who want Dashew-doctrine speed-as-safety offshore passage-making — fast, couple-optimized, with a real walk-in engine room and serious blue-water credentials at a price well under $1M.', 'The aft cockpit is open rather than enclosed — a hard dodger and targa bar provide useful spray and sun protection, and the cockpit sits fairly deep with a high coaming, but there is no full shelter. In Patagonia or the North Atlantic, you will be at the helm in the elements. Good foul-weather gear is non-negotiable. For a couple choosing between cockpit protection and passage speed, the Deerfoot makes its tradeoff explicit: you give up the Amel''s cocoon in exchange for a boat that gets through bad weather faster.', 'Masthead sloop, keel-stepped alloy spar, fully battened main with 3 reefs, genoa track, furling headsails, staysail option', 'The entire Deerfoot design brief — articulated by Dashew from day one — was a couple sailing long offshore passages without paid crew. Moderate sail plan, all lines led aft, fully battened main that reefs from the cockpit, and a modest headsail inventory that can be managed without brute strength. Twin autopilots with Iridium integration on the known hull. The narrow, easily-driven hull keeps sailing loads light even in breeze. Genuinely two-person capable, and arguably more so than wider, beamier contemporaries that need more power to move.', 'A standout feature: confirmed walk-in engine room with full workbench — genuinely rare on a 50-ft hull. Dashew treated the engine space as a real workshop with standing headroom, and all accounts of the known hull confirm this. If you intend to do your own diesel work, this is the fleet''s best engine access.', 'Watermaker (Sea Recovery), dual chartplotters, full electronics suite, Iridium sat-comm, dual autopilot, watertight bulkheads throughout. Pre-CE era: no mandatory category certification, but designed for Category 0 offshore conditions. Systems are owner-maintained in keeping with the Dashew philosophy of capability without complexity.', 'Long, narrow hull with deep bilges fore and aft provides significant stowage volume — a Dashew design priority for extended passages. The high freeboard translates to tall interior volume and locker depth. No published cubic-foot figure, but the boat is designed for extended ocean voyaging without shoreside resupply and owner reports describe generous provisioning capacity.', '480 L fuel at ~6 L/hr gives roughly 640 engine-hours at moderate throttle. At 6–7 knots motoring, that is approximately 3,800–4,500 nm under power alone — exceptional range. Add the fast sailing hull (cruising 8–10 knots in breeze) and the Deerfoot 50 genuinely earns the ''world-ranging passagemaker'' descriptor. The narrow hull''s low resistance means less motoring required to maintain passage times.', 'Owner''s forward cabin with island double berth (semi walk-around), dedicated head/shower cabin, full saloon with U-settee and L-galley, navigation station with dual displays. Optimised for a couple with occasional guests on settee berths. Two sleeping cabins plus saloon. The interior volume punches above its beam measurement because of the high freeboard giving vertical space.', 'No formal high-latitude or ice-class certification, and no documented Deerfoot 50 high-latitude passages in accessible sources. The watertight bulkheads, robust GRP/balsa construction, and Dashew emphasis on heavy-weather seaworthiness provide a solid foundation. However, unlike modern expedition-aluminium designs (Garcia, Boréal, Ovni), the GRP hull has no rub-ice resilience, and the boat has no published insulation or heating system for sustained cold-climate cruising. Patagonia is achievable with proper preparation; the Southern Ocean is not the boat''s home territory.', 'The aft cockpit is well-ventilated — an advantage in the tropics over centre-cockpit designs with enclosed helms. Natural airflow through the open cockpit and down the companionway is good. The narrow beam limits side deck width but allows fore-and-aft airflow along the hull. Dorades and opening hatches are standard for below-decks ventilation. No hull-mounted fans or solar arch noted on the known hull, but these are straightforward retrofits. Overall: reasonable tropical comfort, not the best shade shelter for a sun-drenched day at anchor.', 'Extraordinary value relative to capability: the one known Deerfoot 50 on the global market in early 2026 was listed in Australia at approximately USD $155,000–$170,000. Budget $50,000–$100,000 for a full systems refresh and you are well under $300,000 for a serious offshore passagemaker with documented world-cruising credentials. The catch is availability — perhaps one or two hulls trade hands per decade.', 'Not available new — production ended ~1991. No builder offers this model.', '~USD $150,000–$280,000 depending on condition and upgrades. Extremely limited supply.', 'Comfortably within the $1M budget — likely acquirable for under $300,000 fully outfitted, leaving substantial margin for upgrades. The constraint is not budget but availability: this is one of the rarest hulls in the offshore fleet.', 'A genuine rarity: the Deerfoot 50 is a fibreglass (GRP-over-balsa) hull, not aluminium — a smaller, fast passagemaker in Steve & Linda Dashew''s Deerfoot line, which otherwise ran 58–74 ft. The known 1991 hull was professionally built by Lange & Sons of Port Townsend, Washington; the number of 50-footers built is believed to be very small (possibly under five). The series preceded Dashew''s later Sundeer fibreglass cruisers and the FPB power passagemakers.', '{"protection":2.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":5,"storage":4,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":2.5,"tropical":3.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['Dashew passagemaker', 'Walk-in engine room', 'Fast narrow hull', 'Shorthanded couple']::text[], array['Steve and Linda Dashew accumulated over 200,000 bluewater miles on their own designs — the Deerfoot 50 embodies that empirical, obsessively owner-tested approach.', 'The walk-in engine room on a 50-foot boat was considered eccentric when the Deerfoot was designed; Dashew argued it was the only honest way to maintain a diesel offshore. He was right.', 'The core Dashew doctrine — speed is safety, a fast boat sails out of bad weather rather than riding it out — was radical in 1980 and is still debated; the Deerfoot 50 is a physical argument for one side of that debate.']::text[], array['1991 hull, Queensland Australia, listed ~AUD $240,000 (~USD $155,000), ''huge price reduction'', upgraded engine and electronics (2025–2026 listing)', 'Estimated fully outfitted cost (purchase + $75k refit): USD $225,000–$350,000 — well within the $1M mission budget', 'Comparable Dashew Sundeer 60 (larger, later model): USD $350,000–$600,000 — the Deerfoot 50 is the accessible entry into the Dashew offshore ecosystem']::text[], '[{"name":"SysYacht — 1991 Deerfoot 50 listing (boats.com)","url":"https://sysyachtsales.com/yacht-search/1991/deerfoot-50/9676435/"},{"name":"BoatsOnline AU — Deerfoot 50 specifications","url":"https://www.boatsonline.com.au/boats-for-sale/used/sailing-boats/deerfoot-50/323168"},{"name":"Practical Sailor — Deerfoot 61 (Deerfoot series design review)","url":"https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/deerfoot-61/"},{"name":"Soundings Online — Steve & Linda Dashew profile","url":"https://soundingsonline.com/news/a-journey-ends/"},{"name":"WaveTrain — Sundeer 60 / Deerfoot design philosophy","url":"https://wavetrain.net/2011/12/26/sundeer-60-an-ideal-bluewater-cruising-boat/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Deerfoot 50 Video Tour Part 1 — Blue Rodeo","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4KcgGy3qOLc","note":"Interior and deck walkthrough of a Deerfoot 50 named Blue Rodeo"},{"name":"Deerfoot 50 Walkthrough — Hemisphere Explorer","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x4yp6N3wRw8","note":"Detailed walkthrough of an upgraded 1991 Deerfoot 50 marketed for world touring"}]'::jsonb, array['Walk-in engine room with workbench — the best engine access of any 50-ft cruising boat, period', 'Genuinely two-person offshore capable by design, not by retrofit — every system sized and positioned for a couple', 'Exceptional motoring range (~3,800+ nm) from 480 L fuel at the hull''s low resistance', 'Dashew''s fast narrow hull exits bad weather rather than wallowing in it — real-world safety through speed', 'Extremely affordable relative to capability — well under $300,000 fully outfitted, leaving the $1M budget nearly intact']::text[], array['Open aft cockpit offers limited shelter in cold or wet conditions — Patagonia passages will be uncomfortable at the helm without full oilskins', 'Extreme rarity: perhaps one hull available globally at any time — if you don''t buy the one that''s listed, you may wait years', 'GRP/balsa construction, not aluminium — no rub-ice resilience for true high-latitude or ice work, unlike alloy expedition boats.', 'Narrow beam limits cockpit width and deck space — two large dogs in an aft cockpit will feel cramped; boarding from the water is awkward with high freeboard']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Steve & Linda Dashew (designers)","note":"Accumulated 200,000+ bluewater miles on their own Deerfoot and Sundeer designs, validating the core design philosophy from first-hand ocean experience","url":"https://soundingsonline.com/news/a-journey-ends/"},{"who":"Practical Sailor","note":"Reviewed the Deerfoot 61 positively, characterizing the Deerfoot design line as having a devoted following among serious offshore bluewater cruisers","url":"https://www.practical-sailor.com/sailboat-reviews/deerfoot-61/"}]'::jsonb, 'Dashew doctrine', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped alloy mast — one-piece tapered Sparcraft Wicard Pacific spar. Keel-stepped gives better support offshore; stepping requires crane or skilled yard work.","keelRudder":"Fin keel, lead, stainless bolts. Spade or skeg-hung rudder (exact type not confirmed from sources). Keel bolt inspection every haulout is prudent on a GRP/balsa hull of this age.","complexity":"Moderate-high for a 1990s bluewater cruiser — dual autopilot, watermaker, full electronics, watertight bulkheads with through-hull fittings at each compartment. Dashew designed for owner maintainability, but the systems count is substantial.","maintain":"The walk-in engine room genuinely changes the maintenance calculus — you can work on the diesel properly rather than upside-down through a cabin sole hatch. Dashew''s design philosophy explicitly prioritises owner-serviceable systems. GRP/balsa hull requires attention to osmotic blistering; 30+ year hulls may need epoxy barrier coat work.","partsText":"Nanni/Mercedes OM606 diesel parts are widely available in Europe and Australia. Sparcraft mast spares require specialist alloy spar suppliers. The boat''s age and small fleet size means no dedicated parts network — owners source from generic marine chandleries and diesel specialists. ZF gearbox parts are widely available worldwide.","problems":"Balsa core delamination in deck areas is a known issue on GRP/balsa boats of this era — thorough survey with moisture meter essential. Keel bolt corrosion (stainless in lead) requires inspection. Age of electrical and plumbing systems on any 30+ year hull typically requires full replacement. The very small fleet size means finding another owner who has solved your specific problem is difficult.","sentiment":"Owners who have one tend to keep them for decades — the known hull was described as having the same captain for 25+ years. The Dashew brand carries genuine respect among offshore bluewater circles, and Deerfoot owners identify strongly with the design philosophy. The small fleet creates a tight, knowledgeable owner community.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Deerfoot experiences thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/anyone-sail-on-a-deerfoot-sailboat-20584.html"},{"name":"Dashew SetSail archives","url":"https://www.setsail.com"}],"risks":["Extreme rarity means a long wait for a hull to come to market — this is not a boat you can decide to buy next month","Age (30+ years) means any purchase requires a thorough professional survey with moisture testing of the balsa core","No builder support, no active production, no OEM spares — all maintenance falls to owner and generic marine trades","Small global fleet limits peer support when troubleshooting specific systems problems","GRP/balsa is not the material for grounding on rocks or brush ice — high-latitude passages require extraordinary care"],"scores":{"maintain":4,"simplicity":3,"parts":3,"community":2}}'::jsonb),
  ('amel55', 'Amel 55', 'Chantiers Amel · France', 'Berret-Racoupeau / Amel', '#244e6b', '2011–2018', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + enclosed', '56''9" (17.30 m)', '48''9" (14.85 m)', '16''4" (4.99 m)', '7''3" (2.20 m fixed)', '7''3" (2.20 m fixed)', '24,000 kg / 52,911 lb (full load; ~21,500 kg light)', '5,900 kg', '~27%', '151 m² / 1,625 ft² (upwind)', '~21.3 m (~70 ft) — single-source', 'Volvo Penta D3, 110 hp', 'Shaft · prop set in keel trailing edge (no propwalk)', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads', 'Encapsulated fixed fin keel · skeg-protected single rudder · multiple watertight bulkheads', 'Fully enclosed, protected center cockpit (GRP hardtop or canvas Cabriolet top)', '900 L / 238 gal', '800 L / 211 gal', 17.3, 48.75, 16.4, 52911, 2.2, '~19', '~189', 900, 800, 110, 567000, 1035000, 'tight', 2, 'A couple wanting Amel''s last great push-button ketch — the fully-sheltered, sail-anywhere safety boat — and willing to spend most of $1M on a clean, sorted example rather than refit a neglected one.', 'Amel''s signature fully-enclosed center cockpit — GRP hardtop or canvas Cabriolet, high bulwarks, sail it through a gale without leaving the sheltered helm. Among the best-protected production cockpits afloat; ideal for a nervous or inexperienced second crew.', 'Cutter-headed ketch (NOT a sloop — that''s the successor Amel 50). Electric in-mast furling main + mizzen, electric furling genoa + optional staysail (Bamar). Reviewers note the rig is a touch mizzen-heavy and lacks upwind balance.', 'Built around a two-person crew: every sail furls electrically, electric winches, retractable bow thruster, all controlled from the protected cockpit. Genuinely short-handable. The trade-off: the helm is heavy/dull and astern handling is weak (prop buried in the keel).', 'A standout — a fully isolated, acoustically-treated engine room under a gas-strut cockpit sole, with standing/crouching headroom and best-in-class access doubling as a real workshop. Note: full-access engine room, not a literal walk-through.', 'Factory-integrated 24V system, Onan 7.5 kVA genset, watermaker, reversible A/C, heating — coherent but deeply proprietary (Amel furlers, keel-prop, hydraulic passerelle). The sheer count of systems IS the maintenance burden.', 'Voluminous liveaboard stowage — lifting berths over deep lockers, big insulated freezers, a large mixed-use bow locker that also houses systems. Pack thoughtfully to keep gear accessible.', '900 L fuel ≈ 1,000–1,400 nm motoring at economical rpm; 800 L water + watermaker = genuine long-range self-sufficiency for two plus dogs.', '2–3 cabins / 2 heads, large aft owner''s suite, stall showers, real galley + nav station. High freeboard and the enclosed cockpit shelter dogs well, but boarding is a long step up — the hydraulic passerelle is finicky, so plan a dedicated dog ramp.', 'Decent for cold work — enclosed heatable cockpit, robust GRP build, watertight bulkheads, skeg-protected rudder. But it''s a tropical-bias, ~27%-ballast fixed-keel cruiser pressed into high latitudes, not a dedicated expedition boat; AVS is only ~110–115° (estimated).', 'Its native habitat — shaded enclosed cockpit, A/C, easily-reefed conservative ketch rig, watermaker, big freezers. Made for trade-wind passages and Caribbean/Polynesia heat.', '$567k–$1.04M (used)', 'Out of production (new ~€980k in 2013)', 'Used ~$567k (older Euro hull) to ~$1.04M (clean late hull); most US listings $600k–$1.0M', 'Tight — a clean, sorted late hull eats most of the $1M before high-latitude prep, and a cheap Amel is almost invariably a costly refit. Two same-year 55s have differed by ~$450k on condition alone.', 'Amel''s last classic ketch before the company switched to the sloop-rigged Amel 50 — the refined end of a circumnavigation-icon lineage, built for short-handed couples.', '{"protection":5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":2.5,"workshop":4.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4,"highlat":3,"tropical":5,"budget":2.5}'::jsonb, array['Enclosed center cockpit', 'Push-button ketch', 'Walk-in engine room', 'Last classic Amel']::text[], array['The propeller is set in the keel''s trailing edge — no propwalk, but weak astern steering as the trade.', 'Amel''s last ketch before the Amel 50 went sloop; the end of a 30-year two-masted lineage.']::text[], array['2018 Amel 55, Anacortes WA — $979,000 (YachtWorld / Swiftsure)', '2016 Amel 55, Mamaroneck NY — $899,000 (boats.com)', '2012 Amel 55 — €649,000 / $599,000 (Ancasta / boats.com)']::text[], '[{"name":"SailboatData — Amel 55","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/amel-55/"},{"name":"boat-specs.com — Amel 55","url":"https://boat-specs.com/en/sailboat/amel-55"},{"name":"Yachting Monthly — Amel 55 review","url":"https://www.yachtingmonthly.com/reviews/amel-55-review"},{"name":"SailWiki — Amel 55","url":"https://www.sailwiki.com/en/amel-55"},{"name":"YachtWorld — Amel 55 listings","url":"https://www.yachtworld.com/boats-for-sale/make-amel/model-55/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Yachting Monthly — Amel 55 boat test","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dqonNcACzDQ","note":"Magazine sail test"},{"name":"Sailing Today — Amel 55 Cabriolet tested","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HvgP4QwNgNY","note":"La Rochelle sail review"},{"name":"BoatTube — 2016 Amel 55 walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y6RQqmKwv50","note":"Annapolis dock walkthrough"},{"name":"Amel (official)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCYAbSsQcVxNKUHZyBOtCx2Q","note":"Builder channel"}]'::jsonb, array['Best-in-class enclosed, weatherproof center cockpit — sail it short-handed through foul weather without leaving shelter.', 'All-electric furling on every sail plus a retractable bow thruster — genuinely two-person-friendly.', 'Fully isolated engine room with standing access that doubles as a real workshop — exceptional for a 56-footer.', 'CE Category A ocean construction, watertight bulkheads, keel-buried prop and skeg-protected rudder.', '900 L fuel + 800 L water + watermaker give real ocean-crossing autonomy for two plus dogs.']::text[], array['The electric in-mast furlers (both masts) are the #1 documented failure point — a safety and big-dollar repair item.', 'High freeboard and a finicky hydraulic passerelle make dog boarding awkward; plan a dedicated ramp.', 'Heavy/dull helm and weak astern handling; the ~27% ballast gives only ~110–115° estimated AVS — not a heavy-weather screamer.', 'Unforgiving of neglect — coachroof core moisture, hidden steering U-joints and the Volvo D3 all reward — and punish — diligent owners; budget 10–15% of value/year.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[]'::jsonb, 'Last classic Amel ketch', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped masts (ketch); proprietary Amel electric in-mast furling on main and mizzen.","keelRudder":"Encapsulated fixed fin keel with prop in the trailing edge; single skeg-protected rudder. Inspect for rudder play and skeg cracking at survey.","complexity":"High — an integrated, all-electric, heavily systemed boat. The number of subsystems is the single biggest maintenance challenge; watertight bulkheads make rewiring laborious.","maintain":"Demanding and unforgiving. Superb when maintained, costly when deferred. Furler motors and the Volvo D3-110 (overheating, diesel-bug) are the recurring spend; budget 10–15% of value per year.","partsText":"Many components are proprietary to Amel (furlers, hydraulics, keel-prop arrangement); the factory supports owners but parts are specialist and not generic-chandlery.","problems":"Documented: electric furler hesitation/failure (both masts), D3 overheating and fuel contamination, heavy/worn hidden steering U-joints, cored-coachroof moisture, hydraulic passerelle corrosion.","sentiment":"Owners revere the build quality, shelter and engine room but are candid that it is a complex, expensive boat that does not tolerate a cheap, neglected example.","communities":[{"name":"Amel Yacht Owners (groups.io)","url":"https://amelyachtowners.groups.io/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Amel threads","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/"}],"risks":["Aging electric furler motors that look fine but are near end of service","Cored-coachroof moisture ignored into a six-figure repair","Hidden steering U-joint wear requiring cockpit disassembly","A bargain-priced hull masking a deferred-maintenance refit"],"scores":{"maintain":2,"simplicity":2,"parts":3,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('amel60', 'Amel 60', 'Chantiers Amel (France)', 'Berret-Racoupeau', '#1B3A5C', '2019–present', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + enclosed glass', '62''4" (19.00 m)', '55''3" (16.85 m)', '17''7" (5.35 m)', '7''9" (2.35 m)', '7''9" (2.35 m)', '63,824 lb (28,950 kg) light ship', '15,873 lb (7,200 kg)', '~25%', '1,776 ft² (165 m²) upwind (main 77 m² + genoa 88 m²); staysail 39 m² optional', '85''4" (26.0 m)', 'Volvo Penta 175 hp diesel', 'Saildrive, folding propeller', '3 cabins, 3 heads, 6 berths', 'Fin keel with T-bulb', 'Enclosed centre cockpit; port-side helm with swivel chair and push-button sail control panel; electric sunroof; twin rudders; bow thruster standard', '238 US gal (900 L)', '185 US gal (700 L)', 19, 55.3, 17.6, 63824, 2.35, '~18', '~169', 900, 700, 175, 1491000, 2720000, 'over', 3, 'Couples wanting maximum short-handed automation, a pilothouse-style enclosed cockpit, and a walk-in engine room in a large bluewater sloop — comfort and systems over budget', 'The Amel 60 sets a high bar for cockpit protection: a glassed-in centre cockpit with five panels of tempered glass, an electric sliding sunroof with opening sections, and solid surfaces on three sides. Crew work the boat entirely from this sheltered station. In rain, spray, or cold, occupants are dry; this is closer to a pilothouse than an open cockpit. Downside: in tropical anchorages the enclosure traps heat unless hatches are open.', 'Masthead cutter sloop; carbon Lorima furling mast; electric in-mast mainsail furling; self-tacking staysail option; all sail controls electric from helm dashboard', 'Purpose-built for two. Every sail and anchor operation runs electrically from the helm: electric in-mast main furling, electric genoa furler, push-button windlass, bow thruster standard. Tacking and gybing require minimal deck time. The offset helm swivel chair and glass panels mean watch-standing in conditions is protected. Twin autopilots standard. Reserve: marina maneuvering is tricky without the optional stern thruster (saildrive gives no propwalk).', 'Exceptional: the cockpit sole lifts on gas struts to reveal a stand-up engine room housing the Volvo Penta 175 hp, 17.5 kW generator, battery banks, watermaker, and all major systems. Amel and Yachting World reviewers both call it one of the best engine access arrangements afloat. A true workshop space — not just an access hatch.', '24 V DC system; 920 Ah lithium battery bank (4× Mastervolt Li-Ion Ultra); 530 W solar; 24 V / 150 A dedicated alternator; 17.5 kW diesel generator; 240 L/hr reverse-osmosis watermaker; electric-only galley (induction, dishwasher, washing machine/dryer, electric oven); twin hydraulic Furuno autopilots; electric furling on all sails; retractable bow thruster; Starlink and Iridium nav suites (on fitted-out examples)', 'A 19 m LOA hull delivers serious volume. Three cabins, a large owner''s suite forward, two guest cabins aft, plus dedicated chart/nav station, wet-gear locker, large cockpit lockers, and storage throughout the deep bilge areas. Six watertight hull compartments. Not the most cleverly subdivided storage by count, but sheer size means comfortable provisioning for months.', '900 L fuel at ~130 hours motoring range (per no-frills-sailing.com estimates) gives roughly 1,200–1,400 nm under power depending on conditions. Supplemented by 240 L/hr watermaker and 530 W solar, the boat is genuinely ocean-passage-capable without port calls. Modest watermaker/solar by today''s expedition standard — supplemental generator fills the gap.', '3 cabins: large centre-line owner stateroom forward with island berth, two aft guest double cabins to port and starboard, 3 heads. Galley to starboard amidships. Nav station integrated into saloon. Interior by Isabelle Racoupeau — warm teak and modern finishes. 6 defined berths total.', 'The glassed-in cockpit makes cold-weather watch-keeping genuinely comfortable — Patagonia sailing would benefit enormously from staying out of spray and wind. GRP hull offers no inherent insulation; a diesel heating system (optional from Amel or fitted by owners) is essential for Chilean channels or high latitudes. Stand-up engine room also makes servicing in cold anchorages less miserable. Not purpose-built for ice, but much better protected than open-cockpit competitors.', 'Wide beam and three cabins provide liveable space in the tropics. The enclosed cockpit can be a heat trap at anchor: opening the roof sections and forward panel provides airflow, but it will be warmer than an open cockpit in 35°C air. Air conditioning is not standard but the 17.5 kW generator supports it. Electric galley (no propane) is a real advantage in the heat. The sunroof overhead shades the helm from direct sun underway.', 'New factory price in 2020 was approximately €1.65M ex-VAT (~$1.78M USD); by 2024 new pricing has risen to approximately €2.5M incl. VAT (~$2.72M USD). Used 2020–2024 hulls trade on brokerage in the $1.49M–$2.2M range. All configurations are well above the $1M mission budget.', '~€2.0–2.5M (≈$2.1–2.7M USD) depending on options and year', '~$1.5–2.2M USD for 2020–2024 hulls on brokerage', 'Substantially over the $1M ceiling. Even the cheapest 2020 used example on the open market starts near $1.5M. Fully outfitted to bluewater standard (watermaker, lithium banks, Starlink, generator, stern thruster, heating) adds further. This boat costs 50–150% more than the mission budget — no realistic path under $1M.', 'Amel''s first sloop flagship since the iconic Super Maramu ketch era; winner of European Yacht of the Year 2020 Luxury Cruiser; carbon Lorima in-mast furling rig as standard; walk-in stand-up engine room; fully electric sail handling; no gas aboard (all-electric galley); 6 watertight compartments', '{"protection":5,"handling":5,"dogs":2.5,"workshop":5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":4,"budget":1}'::jsonb, array['enclosed-cockpit', 'push-button-sailing', 'walk-in-engine-room', 'electric-everything']::text[], array['The cockpit glass surround means you can sail across the Southern Ocean in a t-shirt while spray hammers the windows — genuine pilothouse comfort in a sloop.', 'The engine room is large enough to stand in and work comfortably; an Amel 60 owner reportedly keeps a proper toolbox and spare parts cache down there, treating it like a garage.']::text[], array['2024 Amel 60, Imperia, Italy — €2,200,000 ex-tax (~$2.39M USD) via Sizun & Charpentier brokerage', '2020 Amel 60 used examples on Boatshop24: from ~$1,491,000 USD', 'New factory price at launch (2020): ~€1,650,000 ex-VAT (~$1.78M USD at the time)']::text[], '[{"name":"Amel official specifications — amel.fr","url":"https://amel.fr/en/our-yachts/amel-60/"},{"name":"Yachting World sea trial review","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/amel-60-modern-cruiser"},{"name":"Yacht.de test review (English)","url":"https://www.yacht.de/en/yachts/cruising-yachts/test-amel-60-comfortable-luxury-yacht-with-a-wow-effect/"},{"name":"No Frills Sailing — Amel 60 review and yard visit","url":"https://no-frills-sailing.com/amel-60-sailing-yacht-review/"},{"name":"Amel award press release — European Yacht of the Year 2020","url":"https://amel.fr/en/2020/02/19/amel-60-awarded-european-yacht-of-the-year-2020/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Amel 60 Review 2025: Ultimate Bluewater Cruiser Sailboat Tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbkN5hZXUAw","note":"Exploring Eden channel — full walkaround tour of a fitted-out Amel 60"}]'::jsonb, array['Best-in-class enclosed cockpit protection: glassed-in pilothouse-style centre cockpit keeps crew dry and sheltered in all weather', 'Fully push-button short-handed sailing: electric in-mast furling main, electric genoa, push-button windlass, bow thruster — all from the helm swivel chair', 'Unmatched walk-in stand-up engine room: gas-strut cockpit sole lifts to reveal every major system in one accessible space', 'Electric-only galley (no propane) and heavy lithium/solar/generator package deliver genuine offshore electrical autonomy', 'European Yacht of the Year 2020 (Luxury Cruiser) — real design and engineering recognition, not marketing']::text[], array['Substantially over budget: used examples from ~$1.5M, new ~$2.1–2.7M — 50–150% above the $1M mission ceiling', 'Low ballast ratio (~25%) criticised by reviewers as below the 30–35% range of competitors; hull speed limited by generous displacement', 'Heavy electrical dependency: lithium bank, generator, and electric furling must all be in top condition — a single failure has cascading effects offshore', 'High freeboard and enclosed cockpit limit easy dog access on/off the boat at anchor; no dedicated dog area on deck']::text[], array['European Yacht of the Year 2020 — Luxury Cruiser category (BOOT Düsseldorf, January 2020)']::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (sea trial, March 2020)","note":"Called the engine room ''the best engine access you can imagine'' and praised the enclosed cockpit concept for long-passage crews.","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/amel-60-modern-cruiser"},{"who":"European Yacht of the Year 2020 jury","note":"Awarded top prize in the Luxury Cruiser category at the world''s largest boat show, citing build quality and innovation in short-handed systems.","url":"https://amel.fr/en/2020/02/19/amel-60-awarded-european-yacht-of-the-year-2020/"}]'::jsonb, 'EYOTY 2020 Luxury Cruiser', '{"mastStep":"Deck-stepped carbon Lorima in-mast furling rig; stepping requires crane and is not DIY; electric furling system has hydraulic/electric components needing specialist knowledge","keelRudder":"Fin keel with T-bulb; twin spade rudders on semi-custom appendages — replaceable at a boatyard but not a simple repair; keel bolts accessible via engine room bilge","complexity":"High. The Amel 60 is arguably the most system-dense production bluewater cruiser available: lithium banks, in-mast furling, saildrive, 17.5 kW generator, electric galley appliances, watermaker, electric furling on all sails, bow thruster. Every system is well-integrated by Amel but complexity multiplies failure modes offshore.","maintain":"Amel builds for long-distance autonomy and factory support is strong in Europe (La Rochelle shipyard). Parts are proprietary in some areas (Lorima mast, Amel-specific deck hardware). Amel Yacht Owners Group (amelyachtowners.groups.io) is active and knowledgeable. In remote Pacific or South America, sourcing specialist Lorima or Amel-specific components will be a challenge — budget for Iridium/Starlink support calls and carry deep spares.","partsText":"Volvo Penta diesel parts are globally available. Mastervolt lithium batteries and Furuno autopilots likewise. Proprietary Amel hardware (mast, furling drum, deck fittings) and the Lorima carbon spar are French-sourced and may require factory or specialist dealer involvement. Parts availability in Patagonia or French Polynesia for specialty items: limited.","problems":"No known structural defects or safety recalls as of research date. Documented criticisms: steering feel described as ''decoupled'' due to long cable runs to twin rudders; maneuvering difficulties in marinas without optional stern thruster; heavy electrical system demands on the battery bank; modest light-air performance for the displacement. No owner reports of major hull or keel failures found.","sentiment":"Owners who buy Amels tend to be deeply loyal — the Amel Yacht Owners Group has been active for over 25 years. The Amel 60 generates strong enthusiasm from those who prioritise comfort, safety, and autonomy over performance. Critical commentary focuses on price, ballast ratio, and the reality that push-button convenience requires that every electric system work perfectly.","communities":[{"name":"Amel Yacht Owners Group (groups.io)","url":"https://amelyachtowners.groups.io/g/main"},{"name":"Sailing Anarchy — Amel discussions","url":"https://forums.sailinganarchy.com/threads/amel-questions.77666/"}],"risks":["Electrical system failure cascades: lithium bank or generator fault disables furling, galley, autopilot, and bow thruster simultaneously in remote waters","Lorima carbon mast and Amel-proprietary furling hardware are not sourced from local chandleries — a furling drum failure in Patagonia or the Tuamotus is a serious logistical problem","High freeboard and weight mean difficult re-boarding for dogs or crew in rough conditions; no sugar-scoop stern standard on early hulls","Saildrive seal requires periodic inspection and replacement; neglect leads to flooding risk; must be hauled at a yard with saildrive lift capability","Twin rudder and cabling arrangement makes it difficult to carry full spare steering gear; autopilot pump failure in a two-autopilot system needs specialist parts"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":2,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('oyster485', 'Oyster 485', 'Oyster Marine', 'Holman & Pye', '#2E5D7E', '1992–2002', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + deck saloon', '48''6" (14.78 m)', '39''1" (11.91 m)', '14''10" (4.52 m)', '5''6" (1.68 m shoal — wing keel option)', '7''2" (2.18 m standard fin/bulb keel)', '~37,550 lb (17,030 kg)', '~13,000 lb (5,900 kg) lead', '~35%', '~960 sq ft (89 m²) cutter', '~65 ft (19.8 m) to masthead', 'Perkins M90 (or 4236) 4-cyl diesel', 'Shaft drive, 3-blade MaxProp feathering', '3', 'Standard: fin with lead bulb, 7''2" (2.18 m) draft. Optional: wing/shoal keel, 5''6" (1.68 m). Skeg-hung rudder on both. Check keel bolts and bonding on any 1990s example — mild steel fasteners were used in this era.', 'Deep, well-protected centre cockpit with high coamings and wide seats. Single helm station set behind a substantial deck saloon coachroof that blocks most wind and spray forward. Most boats fitted with dodger and bimini. Secure passage-making environment but open to the sky aft — sustained rain calls for full enclosure.', '~530–750 L (140–198 US gal, varies by year)', '~680–750 L (180–198 US gal, two tanks)', 14.78, 39.1, 14.83, 37550, 1.68, '~16', '~318', 545, 720, 82, 250000, 430000, 'fit', 1, 'A cruising couple wanting a proven, spacious Oyster at a fraction of the cost of newer models — with the build quality and sea-kindly motion to go anywhere, at the cost of some modernity in systems and layout.', 'The deck saloon sits between the crew and the weather forward: seas breaking over the bow rarely reach the cockpit in the conventional sense. The centre cockpit places the helm well inboard of the stern, and high coamings wrap the seats. A well-fitted dodger and bimini (standard on most boats by now) close the remaining gap. The helm is exposed to rain from astern in a blow, and the open aft deck gives little windbreak without a full enclosure. For Patagonia, a full cockpit tent is advisable.', 'Fractional cutter — two headsails on twin forestays (staysail and roller-furling genoa), slab-reefed or in-mast furling mainsail depending on fit. Two-spreader anodized aluminium mast by Kemp. Inner staysail stay gives a manageable heavy-weather headsail.', 'A couple can sail this boat comfortably offshore. Self-tacking staysail covers the working slot; genoa furls from the cockpit. Slab reefing is standard on earlier boats; some have in-mast furling (convenient but sail shape compromise). Lewmar winches throughout, typically self-tailing. Electric windlass. Bow thruster standard or common retrofit. The cutter rig means no single sail is unmanageable.', 'Dedicated engine compartment under the cockpit sole with large lift-out panels — one of the 485''s genuine strengths. The extra length also carves out a separate generator alcove just aft of the main engine. A proper workshop can be fitted in the forward cabin; documented examples have workbenches and parts stowage there. Engine access is genuinely good for routine maintenance.', 'Typically fitted with: Northern Lights or Fischer Panda generator, autopilot (Simrad or Robertson), chart plotter, VHF/SSB, watermaker. AGM battery banks common on refitted examples. Shore power, inverter/charger. Reverse-cycle AC added on tropical-use boats. Systems density is moderate for the era — older electronics need replacement but the wiring looms are accessible.', 'Three-cabin layout has a proper aft owner''s stateroom with ensuite, midship saloon with chart table and nav station, deck saloon, and a V-berth or workshop forward. Multiple under-berth lockers, lazarette, and cockpit lockers. Not as voluminous as an Amel 55 but well above average for a 48-footer.', 'With ~545 L fuel and a Perkins M90 burning ~5–6 L/hr at 6 knots, motoring range is roughly 550–650 nm. Water tankage of ~720 L gives ~10–14 days for two people without a watermaker; with one, unlimited. Diesel range is adequate for Patagonia channels but top up whenever possible.', 'Three cabins: aft owner''s stateroom with island berth and en suite (separate shower — a step up from the smaller 45/47); centre-cockpit passage area with nav station; bright deck saloon with L-shaped settee; forward cabin suited as workshop or guest space. Two heads. Headroom approximately 1.93 m throughout the saloon.', 'Heavy displacement, long waterline, and a skeg-hung rudder make this hull forgiving in breaking seas and controllable under storm canvas — the right platform for Southern Ocean latitudes. The centre cockpit keeps the crew away from the worst bow motion. Factory insulation is rudimentary; a diesel heater (Webasto or Espar) is essential for Patagonia. Budget seriously for cold-weather prep, but the underlying platform is sound.', 'The deck saloon''s large wrap-around windows flood the interior with light and, when opened, channel airflow below. Overhead hatches in saloon and cabins supplement ventilation. The raised coachroof creates useful shade in the cockpit. Most boats now carry reverse-cycle AC. Adequate for the tropics with good shade management; very comfortable with air conditioning.', 'Well-maintained examples from the late 1990s ask $275,000–$430,000 USD depending on refit depth, location, and keel type. Early 1990s boats with older systems can go below $250,000. Refit costs to bring a neglected boat to offshore readiness can add $80,000–$150,000. Budget $300,000–$400,000 for a well-found, passage-ready example.', 'Not available new (production ended 2002)', '$250,000–$430,000 USD (2023–2025 market)', 'Comfortably within the $1M budget at $300,000–$430,000 ready to sail, leaving meaningful margin for spares, insurance, and a refit. One of the best-value Oysters in the used market.', '~36 built over a decade; dedicated generator space aft of engine; proper separate shower in owner''s head; one of the first Oysters to combine the full deck-saloon layout with a centre cockpit at this size; last major Holman & Pye design for the brand before Rob Humphreys took over.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4,"dogs":3,"workshop":4,"storage":4,"tankage":4,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":4,"budget":1}'::jsonb, array['centre-cockpit', 'deck-saloon', 'cutter-rig', 'bluewater-proven']::text[], array['Only ~36 were ever built — your Oyster 485 will be the rarest boat in most anchorages from Ushuaia to Bora Bora.', 'The dedicated generator alcove and under-cockpit engine room with lift-out panels are a genuine treat after crawling into a production boat''s bilge with a headlamp.']::text[], array['1995 Oyster 485 (Discovery), Seattle WA — asked $349,000 USD, sold 2024; fully refitted with AGM banks, new transmission, and Raymarine autopilot', '1998 Oyster 485 (Pemaquid), shoal draft, in-mast furling, bow thruster, watermaker, Starlink — asked $295,000 USD', '1996 Oyster 485 Deck Saloon, new teak decks/sails/electronics (2017 refit) — sold; comparable examples ask $300,000–$380,000 in this condition']::text[], '[{"name":"Oyster Yachts — Oyster 485 Heritage Page","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/heritage-yachts/oyster-485/"},{"name":"Swiftsure Yachts — 1995 Oyster 485 Discovery listing","url":"https://swiftsureyachts.com/oyster-485-discovery/"},{"name":"Curtis Stokes Yacht Brokerage — 1998 Oyster 485 Pemaquid","url":"https://www.curtisstokes.net/center-cockpit-for-sale-oyster-48-pemaquid-2846376.html"},{"name":"Sailboat Guide — Oyster 485 specs and listings","url":"https://sailboat.guide/oyster/485"},{"name":"Listings Port — Oyster 485 specifications and review","url":"https://www.listingsport.com/sailboats/oyster/485"}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, array['Proven Oyster build quality — GRP layup, lead ballast, and over-engineered hardware outlast comparable production cruisers of the era', 'Dedicated engine room under the cockpit with generous lift-out panels and a separate generator alcove — engine work is genuinely accessible', 'Cutter rig with self-tacking staysail makes light-weather and heavy-weather sail handling manageable for two people', 'Strong used-market value retention; a well-maintained 485 holds price better than mass-market contemporaries', 'Generous tankage (700+ L water, 500+ L fuel) and space for a watermaker provide real long-range independence']::text[], array['Holman & Pye era boats used mild steel keel bolts — mandate a thorough survey including extraction or ultrasonic testing before purchase', 'In-mast furling mainsail (on so-equipped boats) loses full-batten sail shape; expect flat, draftless mainsail performance in light airs', 'Only ~36 hulls built means OEM Oyster parts for 1990s-specific fittings depend heavily on the owner network and Oyster Service UK', 'Minimal factory insulation makes Patagonia cruising a significant refit project — budget for diesel heating and condensation management']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Oyster Yachts (builder heritage page)","note":"Describes the 485 as ''easily handled by a couple'' with a ''dedicated generator space just aft of the engine'' — a rare feature at this length in the 1990s.","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/heritage-yachts/oyster-485/"}]'::jsonb, 'Modern Classic', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped","keelRudder":"Fin keel with lead bulb; skeg-hung rudder","complexity":"Moderate — 1990s systems are simpler than modern yachts but older electrics and plumbing need periodic renewal. Generator adds complexity but provides independence.","maintain":"Annual haul-out essential; inspect keel bolts and chainplates every 5 years. Perkins M90 is a robust workhorse with wide parts support. Heat exchangers are a wear item — inspect sacrificial anodes regularly. Teak decks (common refit item) need routine maintenance or eventual replacement.","partsText":"Perkins/Caterpillar diesel parts are globally available. Lewmar winch parts are straightforward worldwide. Older Oyster-specific hardware (cleats, traveller cars, mast fittings) may require Oyster Service UK or creative substitution. Northern Lights and Onan generator parts available in most cruising hubs.","problems":"Mild steel keel bolts corroding unseen; stainless chainplate crevice corrosion; aging electrical systems (wire insulation brittleness after 25–30 years); heat exchanger failure from neglected anodes; teak deck delamination; in-mast furling systems requiring specialist maintenance.","sentiment":"Oyster 485 owners are a loyal and vocal community. The consensus: these boats reward attentive owners with decades of reliable offshore service. Build quality is consistently praised; the age of most examples makes a thorough pre-purchase survey non-negotiable.","communities":[{"name":"Oyster Owners section — Oyster Yachts website","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/owners/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Oyster 435–485 range thread","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f47/oyster-435-485-range-any-bad-models-209210.html"}],"risks":["Keel bolt corrosion (mild steel, 1990s spec) — survey must include keel bolt extraction or ultrasonic testing","Chainplate crevice corrosion hidden behind interior headliner panels","Osmotic blistering in GRP hull if not regularly barrier-coated","Electrical system fatigue — wire insulation cracking after 25–30 years; full rewire may be needed on neglected boats","In-mast furling system wear — swivel bearings and extrusion slides degrade; budget for rebuild or conversion to slab reefing"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":3,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('oyster53', 'Oyster 53', 'Oyster Marine (UK) / McDell Marine (NZ build)', 'Humphreys Yacht Design', '#1a3a5c', '2000–2008', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + deck saloon', '53''10" (16.41 m)', '45''7" (13.89 m)', '15''3" (4.65 m)', '6''0" (1.83 m shoal)', '7''4" (2.24 m deep)', '47,399 lb (21,500 kg)', '14,235 lb (6,457 kg)', '~30%', '1,201 sq ft (111.6 m²) — 100% foretriangle; full genoa ~1,615 sq ft', 'not published', 'Yanmar 4LH diesel (100 hp standard; 88 or 110 hp on some hulls)', 'shaft drive, folding or feathering prop', '3–4 (4th cabin optionally built as dedicated workshop at build time)', 'Lead bulb fin keel — standard deep (2.24 m) or shoal option (1.83 m); both cast lead', 'Protected centre cockpit with raised deck-saloon coachroof providing full windward shelter; ergonomically designed seats (Loughborough University collaboration) long enough to lie on, wavy coamings for multiple positions; all control lines led aft to electric winches at helm; aft helm station semi-exposed but tucked behind coachroof; bimini and sprayhood standard on most boats', '225 US gal (851 L)', '198 US gal (750 L)', 16.41, 45.6, 15.25, 47399, 1.83, '~19.3', '~233', 851, 750, 100, 350000, 650000, 'tight', 2, 'Two-handed offshore passage-making; couples liveaboard cruising; extended bluewater circuits demanding comfort, range, and safety in rough conditions', 'The raised deck-saloon coachroof is the defining feature: it acts as a permanent windbreak for the centre cockpit, keeping the crew dramatically drier and warmer than aft-cockpit designs. The helm sits aft of the cockpit and is more exposed, but the cockpit crew working sheets and sails has excellent shelter. A bimini over the cockpit completes the envelope. For Patagonian channels and the Southern Ocean approaches, this layout is meaningfully safer and more comfortable than conventional aft-cockpit boats — you can work the boat for hours in cold, wet conditions without soaking the off-watch. The main gripe is that the helm station itself has limited protection in a beam sea; a proper sprayhood extension or helm tent is worth fitting.', 'Masthead cutter (removable inner forestay); sloop option available. Full-batten main standard; in-mast furling popular (fitted to ~75% of production). Shorter mast option available for ICW bridge clearance. Both configurations are proved offshore.', 'Purpose-built for two-up offshore work. All lines led aft, electric winches standard, and the in-mast furling main means a single crew member can reef without leaving the cockpit. The cutter rig gives a versatile sail wardrobe: staysail alone works in 40+ knots, main and jib for moderate conditions, full canvas in light air. The 53''s D/L of ~233 and proven hull make it an honest performer rather than a light-air flier — expect 7 knots in 16 knots true; 200 nm days are realistic. One caution: in-mast furling sacrifices sail shape at the top of the wind range; owners planning a lot of trade-wind sailing often add a cruising chute or code zero.', 'The fourth cabin aft can be specified at build as a dedicated engine room and workshop — this is the configuration to seek on the used market. When fitted, it gives standing headroom access to the Yanmar and all systems, a proper workbench, and spares stowage. Boats without this build option have engine access via panels in the aft cabin, adequate but not luxurious. The generator (7.5 kW Westerbeke common) is typically in its own compartment. Overall one of the better engine-access arrangements among production 50-footers, but only outstanding when the workshop option was specified.', 'Typical fit includes an autopilot (Autohelm/Simrad), chartplotter, AIS, full nav suite at the nav station. Many boats have been updated with lithium banks, inverter/chargers, watermakers (Spectra or Katadyn), SSB, and satellite comms. Electrical systems are 24 V on most boats. The Oyster build standard is high but the boats are now 17–25 years old — budget for a full systems audit and likely rewiring on any purchase.', 'A 47,000 lb GRP cruiser has the mass to carry serious stores. Lockers under the saloon sole, settees, and V-berth are generous. With the four-cabin layout there is dedicated stowage in each cabin plus the nav area. Chain locker, sail locker, and cockpit lazarettes provide deck-level storage. Passage provisioning for 60+ days is practical. The one frustration owners cite is that the raised-saloon interior chops the accommodation into more discrete zones, so it takes a passage or two to learn where everything lives.', 'With 851 L of fuel and a 100 hp Yanmar burning roughly 8–10 L/hr at passage speed, motoring range is approximately 800–1,000 nm under power alone — enough to cross the Doldrums or transit the Panama Canal zone without re-fuelling anxiety. Combined with 750 L of water and a watermaker, this is a genuinely self-sufficient passage-maker. The Patagonia-to-Caribbean route suits it well: the fuel depth covers the calms, and the cutter rig handles the variables.', 'Three or four cabins depending on build spec. Typical layout: aft owner''s cabin with centerline double and ensuite head; raised deck saloon with U-shaped settee and nav station; galley (narrow walkthrough on starboard between master and saloon — functional, not palatial); two guest cabins forward sharing or with separate head; optional fourth cabin aft configured as workshop. Eight berths total in full accommodation version. Interior joinery available in cherry, American white oak, teak, or maple — finish quality is genuinely yacht-club calibre.', 'The centre-cockpit / deck-saloon architecture is well-suited to cold cruising. Crew shelter is better than most production cruisers of this era. GRP construction is unaffected by cold. The Yanmar diesel is proven in cold climates. You will want to add a diesel heater (Eberspächer or Webasto) if not already fitted — most boats cruising high latitudes will have one. Rigging and sail handling are conventional and manageable in gloves. The shoal-draft keel option helps in Patagonian anchorages, but the draft difference (6''0" vs 7''4") is modest — you are still a deep-keeled boat. Companionway sealing and window integrity are the key survey items for Southern Ocean preparation.', 'The raised deck saloon creates excellent natural ventilation — the elevated windows catch wind that flows over a lower deck, and hatches in the coachroof are common on these boats. The centre cockpit benefits from shade via bimini and is naturally cooler than a flush deck. The main tropical challenge is the narrow galley — cooking in heat requires good ventilation, and many owners add fans or upgrade the galley ventilation. Air conditioning is retro-fittable. Overall, this is a more comfortable tropical boat than its cold-weather bias suggests.', 'Used market (2025) runs roughly $350k–$650k USD depending on year, spec, and refit state. UK-listed boats in GBP often show £300k–£400k. Well-maintained examples with the workshop option, updated electronics, and a watermaker sit toward the upper half of the range. Budget another $50k–$100k to bring any boat to passage-ready standard (rigging, sails, systems audit, safety gear, dinghy/outboard).', '~$1.4M–$1.6M USD (new, circa 2003–2006; ~AUD 2.1M equipped at launch)', '$350,000–$650,000 USD (2024–2025 market)', 'A tightly fitted choice within your $1M budget. A well-specced example at $550k–$650k leaves $350k–$450k for refit, systems, and safety gear — workable but not lavish. The boats are old enough (17–25 years) that budgeting aggressively for systems renewal is essential. The upside: Oyster residuals are strong, so you are unlikely to lose value if you buy carefully.', 'Described by owners as a ''first class British train'' at sea — quiet, stable, and refined in rough conditions. Completed multiple world rallies and extended bluewater circuits. NZ-built examples (McDell Marine) have an especially strong reputation for hull integrity. The Boating NZ 2025 article noted ''minimal structural work'' required on a 20-year-old example, which is exceptional for a production GRP boat.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":4,"tropical":4,"budget":2}'::jsonb, array['deck-saloon', 'centre-cockpit', 'bluewater', 'cutter']::text[], array['The cockpit was ergonomically designed with Loughborough University — seats long enough to sleep on, with wavy coamings for every lounging position.', 'In a 2006 SAIL Magazine test, the 53 was compared to riding first class on a British train — composed and quiet through rough seas that had the crew expecting chaos below.']::text[], array['S/Y Venture (2007): £365,000 GBP (~$462k USD), VAT paid, Lefkas Greece — Oyster Yachts brokerage', 'S/Y Seeadler (2000): €450,000 (~$486k USD), Lignano Italy — Denison Yacht Sales', 'Unnamed 2000 hull: $545,000 USD, Bahamas — Wellington Yacht Partners']::text[], '[{"name":"SAIL Magazine — Oyster 53 full test (2006)","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/oyster-53/"},{"name":"Oyster Yachts — Heritage Oyster 53 page","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/heritage-yachts/oyster-53/"},{"name":"Waterline Boats — Owner''s Insights: Oyster 53","url":"https://waterlineboats.com/a-boat-owners-insights-oyster-53/"},{"name":"Boating New Zealand — Oyster 53 Bluewater Benchmark (Jun 2025)","url":"https://www.boatingnz.co.nz/2025/06/oyster-53-bluewater-benchmark-with-a-kiwi-backstory/"},{"name":"Denison Yacht Sales — S/Y Seeadler listing","url":"https://www.denisonyachtsales.com/yachts-for-sale/seeadler-53-oyster"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Sailing aboard the Oyster 53 Glass Slipper","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sdi5yIzBHV0","note":"Walkaround and sailing footage of a well-maintained Oyster 53"},{"name":"Oyster 53 — Big Waves, High Winds, Strait of Bonifacio","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=roLIEIjsd18","note":"Force 9.5, 40–50 knot conditions — real offshore capability on display"},{"name":"Day Sail before an Oyster 53 Tour (Dec 2024)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jSyto6COA4w","note":"Recent interior and deck tour with sailing footage"},{"name":"Oyster 53 Moondance — Owner video (Jan 2020)","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8h1kPtYYGqc","note":"Owner perspective on liveaboard cruising"}]'::jsonb, array['Centre-cockpit / deck-saloon layout gives substantially better crew protection than aft-cockpit designs — critical for Patagonia passages', '851 L fuel and 750 L water gives genuine passage-making autonomy without re-fuelling anxiety', 'Yanmar diesel with optional dedicated workshop cabin means serious engine and systems access — far above average for production 50-footers', 'Proven hulls: 20+ year old examples show minimal structural deterioration; Oyster build quality and residual values are among the best in class', 'Cutter rig with all lines aft and electric winches makes short-handed passage-making genuinely manageable for two people']::text[], array['Helm station is more exposed than the cockpit — in beam-sea conditions or cold climates, the skipper gets wet while the crew stays dry', 'In-mast furling (fitted to most boats) degrades sail shape — trade-wind sailing performance suffers unless a code zero or cruising chute is added', 'Workshop cabin must be specified at build; boats without it have adequate but not exceptional engine access — check carefully before buying', 'Boats are 17–25 years old: budget $50k–$100k beyond purchase price for systems renewal, rigging, and safety gear before offshore departure']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"SAIL Magazine (Tom Dove, 2006 offshore test)","note":"Praised the 53''s refined seakeeping and offshore capability; described the sailing experience as ''first class on a British train''","url":"https://sailmagazine.com/boats/oyster-53/"},{"who":"Boating New Zealand (Jun 2025)","note":"Noted ''minimal structural work'' required on a 20-year-old NZ-built example, citing consistent 200 nm/day passage performance and strong residual values"}]'::jsonb, 'Offshore proven', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped aluminium spar; professionally serviced at haulout intervals","keelRudder":"Lead bulb fin keel with stainless keel bolts; skeg-hung rudder on most hulls. Keel bolt inspection at haulout is routine but important on boats this age","complexity":"Medium-high. Oyster specification includes electric winches, autopilot, full electronics suite, watermaker, generator on most boats — all require maintenance competence. The cutter rig adds one more forestay to manage. Not a boat for someone new to offshore sailing systems.","maintain":"GRP hull maintenance is low. Systems maintenance is moderate-to-high given age and complexity of fit. The Oyster Owner community is active and shares knowledge freely. Parts are generally available but some original Oyster proprietary hardware (hatches, deck fittings) can be slow to source. Finding a good Yanmar dealer is easy worldwide.","partsText":"Yanmar diesels are globally supported — parts and service available in every cruising area. Lewmar and Harken deck hardware is universal. Some original Oyster deck fittings and window systems may require sourcing through Oyster Yachts directly or specialist marine chandlers. Electronics (often 2000s-era Simrad/Autohelm) will likely be replaced on refit anyway.","problems":"The most commonly reported issues on older Oysters relate to: (1) aging electrical systems — wiring from the early 2000s benefits from full audit/renewal; (2) window sealant degradation on 20+ year old boats — the distinctive deck-saloon windows must seal well offshore; (3) in-mast furling mechanism wear — inspect carefully; (4) engine mounts and shaft seals as standard age-related items. No widespread reports of structural defects, osmosis, or keel failures specific to the Humphreys 53.","sentiment":"Strongly positive among owners. The Oyster 53 Humphreys is regarded as one of the most capable offshore production cruisers of its era. Owners who have done serious miles on them — world rallies, Southern Ocean passages, Atlantic circuits — consistently describe them as composed, safe, and genuinely comfortable at sea. The main sentiment caveat is that buyers must go in with eyes open about the age of the boats and the systems renewal budget required.","communities":[{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Oyster section","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f46/"},{"name":"Oyster Owners Association (OOA)","url":"https://www.oysterownersassociation.com/"}],"risks":["Aging electrical systems (early 2000s wiring) — full audit and likely partial rewire should be budgeted","Window sealant integrity — the large deck-saloon windows are the boat''s signature but must be inspected and resealed if in doubt","In-mast furling wear — inspect drum, foil, and reefing lines carefully; a failed system at sea is a serious problem","Workshop cabin not guaranteed — confirm at purchase whether the 4th cabin is workshop-spec; retrofitting is expensive","Keel bolt condition on 20+ year old boats — standard offshore survey requirement but worth specialist ultrasonic testing"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":4,"community":4}}'::jsonb),
  ('oyster54', 'Oyster 54', 'Oyster Marine (UK)', 'Humphreys Yacht Design', '#1B4F8A', '2008–2013 (Oyster 54); successor 545 built 2013–2018', 'GRP', 'Centre-cockpit cruiser', 'Center + deck saloon', '53''11" (16.43 m)', '46''3" (14.10 m)', '15''7" (4.75 m)', '6''0" (1.83 m — shoal keel)', '7''10" (2.40 m — deep keel)', '46,893 lb (21,315 kg)', '15,562 lb deep keel / 17,900 lb shoal keel', '~33%', '1,658 ft² (154 m²)', '70''6" (21.5 m)', 'Yanmar 4JH4-HTBE 110 hp diesel', 'Shaft drive, fixed prop', '3 cabins, 2 heads', 'Deep fin keel (standard) or shoal keel option; centerboard variant also listed', 'Large centre cockpit, seats 5–6, folding table for 6–8, pedestal helm, high coamings, deck saloon overhead provides some aft shelter', '224 gal (850 L)', '198 gal (750 L)', 16.43, 46.25, 15.58, 46893, 1.83, '~20.4', '~212', 850, 750, 110, 650000, 1050000, 'tight', 2, 'Two-up offshore passagemaking with liveaboard comfort; Oyster''s flagship mid-size cruiser of its era, built to go anywhere and come home intact', 'Centre cockpit with high coamings and the deck saloon structure just forward offers meaningful protection — crew work from a relatively sheltered station. Not a fully enclosed pilothouse, so spray and cold air still reach the helm in hard conditions. Dodger and bimini add to protection but that''s owner-added kit. For Patagonia you will want a serious enclosure; the bones are there to rig one.', 'Masthead sloop; in-mast furling mainsail standard (fully battened mainsail offered as owner option); 125% roller-furling genoa; electric halyard and sheet winches standard; carbon rig and asymmetric chute available', 'Designed squarely for two-handed passagemaking. Electric winches, in-mast furling, and all lines led to the cockpit mean a couple can reef or sail change without leaving the helm area. The boat is heavy (21,300 kg) so it does not punch above its weight in light air, but it tracks steadily and responds predictably. In 30 knots under two reefs Yachting World described it as composed and confidence-inspiring. Wheel diameter noted as slightly oversized, limiting cockpit access.', 'Dedicated engine access through the small third cabin (often called the ''utility cabin''). The Yanmar 4JH4-HTBE is a common, well-supported engine with parts available globally. Engine room is accessible but not a stand-up workshop by any measure — typical of boats this size. Electrical and systems panels are extensive; some owners note the main breaker panel is awkwardly placed beneath the navigator''s seat.', 'Full bluewater fit: watermaker standard or pre-plumbed option, inverter/charger, solar and wind generation wiring prepared, bow thruster option, electric anchor windlass, comprehensive electronics suite (Raymarine or Garmin depending on year), AIS, SSB/satellite comms ready', 'Exceptional for the size. Three cabins each with dedicated hanging lockers and under-berth stowage; galley with deep lockers and dedicated dry-goods space; cockpit lazarette; anchor locker forward. One notable gap: no dedicated sail locker — Yachting World criticised this, and a cruising chute or storm sail must share space below.', '850 L fuel at 6 knots motoring yields roughly 1,200–1,400 nm under engine alone, assuming modest consumption at cruise rpm. 750 L water plus a standard watermaker extends independence indefinitely on passages. Tankage is a genuine strength — Patagonia''s fuel scarcity demands this range.', 'Owner''s aft stateroom with centerline double, hanging lockers, and full-size shower. Generous U-shaped galley amidships. Saloon with starboard dinette and port curved settee, seats 8 at table. Forward double cabin with en suite head. Small third cabin (port midship) usable as crew quarters or fitted as utility/workshop. 2 heads each with separate shower stall.', 'GRP construction is fine for cold; the boat is heavy enough to handle Southern Ocean chop without feeling fragile. The cockpit is manageable for oilskin-clad crew, and a properly built enclosure can seal it entirely. Keel-stepped mast (standard) is robust. Main gaps: no pilothouse, so watch-standing in Patagonia requires real cold-weather kit; interior insulation is a standard coastal UK spec that will need augmenting for serious cold-weather passages.', 'Deck saloon design with large opening hatches and portlights moves air well. Multiple opening hatches per cabin. The fan and ventilation provisions are adequate for the tropics but not exceptional — an owner heading to the Pacific should add a waterproof Dorade and cockpit fan. Teak decks (standard on 54) absorb heat; synthetic teak (545 option) is cooler. White hull helps.', 'Used Oyster 54s (2008–2013): roughly $650k–$900k USD depending on year, keel, and refit state. Oyster 545s (2013–2018) push $800k–$1.1M. At the top of your $1M outfitted budget you are buying a good early example and will have little left for upgrades. A well-found one under $800k is achievable but requires scrutiny.', '~£795,000–£925,000 ex-VAT when new (2008–2014 pricing)', '$650,000–$1,050,000 USD (2025 market)', 'Tight. A clean, well-equipped Oyster 54 can be found under $850k, leaving $150k for outfitting — tight but workable if the boat is already offshore-ready. A neglected example needing refit work will blow the budget. Inspect rigging, sails, and electronics hard; an Oyster survey and sea trial is non-negotiable.', '21 hulls built (Oyster 54); succeeded by near-identical Oyster 545. Hull construction outsourced to McDell Marine (New Zealand) for early examples, finished by Oyster in Southampton. Oyster went into administration in 2018 but was rescued and relaunched — parts and support restored.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3.5,"workshop":4,"storage":4.5,"tankage":5,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":4,"budget":2}'::jsonb, array['centre-cockpit', 'deck-saloon', 'bluewater', 'UK-built']::text[], array['Oyster 54 hull #1 was delivered to Sir Robin Knox-Johnston, who sailed it solo across the Atlantic within months of delivery', 'The 545''s flush deck hatches were inspired directly by Oyster''s larger superyacht range — the 54-footer got the same hardware as boats twice its price']::text[], array['2010 Oyster 54, deep keel, Premià de Mar Spain — listed ~$817k USD (YachtWorld, 2024)', '2015 Oyster 545, shoal keel, Barcelona — £610,000 (~$770k USD) via Oyster Brokerage', '2016 Oyster 545, Antigua — AUS$895,000 (~$575k USD) — bottom of market, southern hemisphere listing']::text[], '[{"name":"Oyster Yachts — Oyster 54 heritage page","url":"https://oysteryachts.com/heritage-yachts/oyster-54/"},{"name":"Yachting World — Oyster 475 and 545 boat test","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/oyster-475-and-545-boat-test"},{"name":"Yachting World — Oyster 54 liveaboard test","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/oyster-54-liveaboard-test"},{"name":"Cruising World — Oyster 54 bluewater passagemaker review","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/oyster-54-serious-bluewater-passagemaker/"},{"name":"SailboatData — Oyster 54 Humphreys","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/oyster-54-humphreys/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Oyster Yachts — Oyster 545 walkaround","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNRkl0nS3zM","note":"Factory walkaround of the 545 (same hull as the 54) covering cockpit, saloon, and owner''s cabin"},{"name":"Sailing Mareda — Life aboard Oyster 54","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5sGhT8Wy7UQ","note":"Owner couple passage-making aboard their Oyster 54; useful for real-world impressions of the layout and offshore behaviour"}]'::jsonb, array['Legendary Oyster build quality — GRP laminate and joinery to near-superyacht standards; these boats hold up on long passages', '850 L fuel / 750 L water is best-in-class tankage for the size; gives genuine independence in remote anchorages and fuel-scarce regions', 'All-electric sail handling (electric winches, furling main) makes two-up passagemaking genuinely manageable for a fit couple', 'Three-cabin layout with two full heads gives flexibility for guests, crew, or converting the third cabin to a utility/workshop space', 'Strong resale value and active Oyster community (Oyster Owners Association, factory refit support) means you are not alone when things break']::text[], array['Budget is tight: a clean, well-found example absorbs most of a $1M budget with limited margin for upgrades or unexpected refit', 'No dedicated sail locker — stowing a cruising chute, storm jib, and extra sails requires creative below-decks compromise', 'Mast height (70''6") prevents ICW transit and limits some marina berthing; not relevant for the planned route but worth knowing', 'Centre cockpit is spacious but not deeply recessed — in Patagonia you will want a full enclosure which is owner-fitted, not factory']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yachting World (sea trial, 2013)","note":"Praised the 545 as ''the thinking bluewater sailor''s choice at this size'' — the galley in particular described as the best the reviewer had seen on a production boat","url":"https://www.yachtingworld.com/reviews/boat-tests/oyster-475-and-545-boat-test"},{"who":"Cruising World (sea trial, Narragansett Bay)","note":"Called the Oyster 54 ''very responsive for such a big boat'' and praised the conservative hull giving offshore confidence","url":"https://www.cruisingworld.com/sailboats/oyster-54-serious-bluewater-passagemaker/"}]'::jsonb, 'Oyster flagship', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped aluminum mast — robust, preferred for offshore; mast removal requires a crane but stepping integrity is excellent","keelRudder":"Fin keel (deep or shoal), skeg-hung rudder — proven offshore combination; skeg protects rudder from debris and grounding damage","complexity":"High. Full bluewater systems suite means watermaker, inverter, chart plotter network, electric winches, furling systems, and optional bow thruster all need maintenance. Owner-mechanic capability strongly recommended.","maintain":"Oyster builds to a high standard so failure rates are lower than average, but complexity means more to maintain. Yanmar engine is a strength — parts and dealers worldwide. UK-sourced hardware (Lewmar, Selden, Navtec) is available globally through chandleries. Oyster''s administration and relaunch (2018) did not strand parts supply.","partsText":"Yanmar 4JH4 parts: excellent global availability. Selden spars: worldwide dealer network. Lewmar winches and hatches: standard availability. Oyster-proprietary items (upholstery, woodwork, custom hardware): best sourced from Oyster''s relaunched factory in Southampton or their licensed repairers. The Oyster Owners Association maintains a brokerage-and-refit contact list.","problems":"Main reported issues: (1) main power panel located awkwardly under navigator''s seat — an ergonomic nuisance, not a safety issue; (2) wet locker undersized for offshore crew — owners add deck storage bags; (3) early in-mast furling mainsails (pre-545) had furling line routing issues in some builds — inspect and replace if worn; (4) teak decks on original 54 eventually require recaulking or replacement (budget $15k–$30k); (5) Oyster''s 2018 administration created brief warranty uncertainty — now resolved, but pre-purchase due diligence on warranty claims is wise.","sentiment":"Strongly positive in bluewater cruising circles. Oyster owners are vocal and loyal; the brand is associated with successful circumnavigations and long-distance passages. Criticism is reserved for price (high even used) and complexity. No community of owners reporting structural or systemic failures.","communities":[{"name":"Oyster Owners Association","url":"https://www.oysterownersassociation.com/"},{"name":"Cruisers Forum — Oyster Yachts","url":"https://www.cruisersforum.com/forums/f14/"},{"name":"Sailing Anarchy — Cruising Anarchy board","url":"https://forums.sailinganarchy.com/"}],"risks":["Budget overrun: buying at the top of market leaves little for the unavoidable post-purchase work (sails, electronics, safety gear, enclosure)","Teak deck condition: original 54 teak decks can be a $20k–$30k liability if neglected — check caulking seams carefully","In-mast furling reliability offshore: a jammed furling main in 35 knots is a genuine problem; inspect the system and carry a plan B","Oyster administration legacy: verify any existing warranty claims were resolved before purchase; some pre-2018 buyers had open warranty items that were not honoured during administration"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":2,"parts":4,"community":5}}'::jsonb),
  ('moody54', 'Moody 54', 'A.H. Moody & Son / Marine Projects (Plymouth), UK', 'Bill Dixon', '#345a72', '2000–2004 (~55 built)', 'GRP (balsa-cored hull, Kevlar-reinforced underbody)', 'Centre-cockpit bluewater cruiser', 'Centre cockpit', '54''10" (16.72 m)', '46''1" (14.02 m)', '15''11" (4.85 m)', '5''11" (1.80 m shoal)', '7''6" (2.28 m fin)', '20.06 t / ~44,200 lb', '~6.8 t (lead/antimony)', '~34%', '~157 m² / 1,690 ft² (working)', '~22.75 m / 74''6"', 'Yanmar 4JH2-UT(B)E 100 hp turbo diesel', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads (7 berths)', 'Fin keel with vestigial bulb (or optional shoal); partially balanced spade rudder on a short skeg; lead/antimony ballast; 10 hp Sleipner bow thruster standard', 'Deep, well-protected centre cockpit with wrap-around glass windscreen; twin-cabin aft layout; sprayhood/bimini; hydraulic drop-down boarding platform aft', '682 L / 180 gal', '995 L / 263 gal', 16.72, 46.1, 15.92, 44200, 1.8, '~16.6', '~201', 682, 995, 100, 240000, 420000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want a big, comfortable, easily-handled British centre-cockpit world cruiser with a private aft stateroom and generous tankage — proper bluewater capability without the price or the systems density of a flagship like Oyster or Amel.', 'Strong. The deep centre cockpit sits well inboard behind a fixed wrap-around glass windscreen that genuinely shelters the watch from spray and wind; a sprayhood and bimini close it down further. High topsides, substantial bulwarks and good handrails make the side decks secure. No inside steering, so cold-passage watchkeeping is still done in the open (but very sheltered) cockpit.', 'Selden keel-stepped masthead cutter on a triple aft-swept-spreader spar. In-mast furling main is standard, with a self-tacking staysail and a furling Yankee/genoa — so almost everything is set, reefed and stowed from the cockpit. All lines lead aft under the windscreen to electric primary winches.', 'Genuinely two-person friendly. Furling on every sail, a self-tacking staysail, electric primary winches and a standard bow thruster mean little foredeck work and easy short-tacking. The hull stands up well to full sail; testers noted only a hint of weather helm once it is pressed past ~25 knots over the deck, easily managed by feathering or reefing the main.', 'The 100 hp Yanmar sits under the cockpit/saloon sole with reasonable all-round access through sole boards; the big aft lazarette and under-berth spaces in the aft stateroom give useful machinery and stowage room. Behind-joinery production fit-out rather than a walk-in engine room, but better access than most production 50-footers of the era.', 'Sensible, mainstream systems for the period: Yanmar shaft drive, Sleipner bow thruster, electric winches, calorifier hot water, and — on cruising-equipped boats — a genset, watermaker, hot-air (Webasto/Eberspächer) heating, A/C, solar/wind and full electronics. Mostly off-the-shelf brands, so serviceable worldwide.', 'Generous. High topsides and a 54-foot hull yield voluminous lockers, deep bilges, a large lazarette aft and abundant stowage in the aft stateroom and forward cabin — easily enough for a couple provisioning for long passages.', '682 L of fuel gives a comfortable ~800–1,000+ nm motoring reserve depending on revs, and the 995 L water tankage is large for the size — add a watermaker and the boat is well set up for ocean legs and remote anchorages.', 'Three private cabins sleeping seven: a full-beam owner''s stateroom aft with en-suite heads and a separate shower stall, a forward cabin with a centreline double, and a versatile mid cabin (twin berths or convertible to an office). Large C-shaped galley by the companionway, a proper chart table, and a richly finished teak saloon — a true liveaboard interior.', 'Good. The hull is stiff, immensely strong (Kevlar-reinforced underbody) and well-ballasted, the deep glass-screened cockpit is very sheltered, and hot-air heating is common on cruising boats. Watch-outs: no inside steering means open-cockpit watches in the cold, and the balsa-cored topsides plus teak decks need care to keep moisture out in a wet, cold climate.', 'Very good. Opening hatches and ports plus the big cockpit give good airflow; the bimini and windscreen shade the crew; tankage is large and a watermaker is easily fitted. The hydraulic transom platform and protected cockpit make tropical anchorage life easy, and most cruising boats carry A/C and refrigeration.', '$240k–$420k (used)', 'Originally ~£300k–£400k (~$400k+) new in the early 2000s', 'Used roughly $240k–$420k depending on year, keel, refit state and equipment (most boats in Europe)', 'Comfortably under the $1M budget — a well-equipped, ARC-ready Moody 54 lands in the mid-to-high $200k to low-$400k range, leaving real margin for a refit and the watermaker/heating a high-latitude-plus-tropics plan needs.', 'Marketed as A.H. Moody''s flagship cruiser of its era and built by Marine Projects (Plymouth, later Princess Yachts). A capable ocean boat — e.g. ''Blue Pearl'' completed an Atlantic crossing — and the centre-cockpit ancestor of the later, unrelated Hanse-built Moody DS54 deck-saloon flagship.', '{"protection":4.5,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":3.5,"storage":4.5,"tankage":4.5,"highlat":3.5,"tropical":4.5,"budget":4.5}'::jsonb, array['British centre cockpit', 'Push-button cutter', 'Private aft stateroom', 'Value bluewater 50-footer']::text[], array['Designed by Bill Dixon and built by Marine Projects — the same Plymouth yard that became Princess Yachts — so the hull shares a pedigree with British motoryacht building.', 'The fixed wrap-around glass windscreen gives the centre cockpit an almost pilothouse feel without losing the open-cockpit sailing experience.', 'A hydraulic fold-down transom turns the flat stern into a boarding/bathing platform — unusually yacht-like for a 2000-era cruiser.']::text[], array['2003 Moody 54 — US$309,970 (Ancasta, Barcelona, Spain)', '2003 Moody 54 — US$325,751 (GT Yachtbrokers, Spain)', '2003-era Moody 54 range US$239,000–US$508,000 (Boatshop24 listings)']::text[], '[{"name":"Moody Owners Association — Moody 54 archive","url":"https://www.moodyowners.org/Moody_Archives/87_boat.htm"},{"name":"Moody Owners Association — Moody 54 specification","url":"https://moodyowners.org/Moody_Archives/87_spec.htm"},{"name":"SailboatData — Moody 54","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/moody-54/"},{"name":"Sailboat-Cruising — Moody 54 specs & KPIs","url":"https://www.sailboat-cruising.com/Moody-54-sailboat.html"},{"name":"Yacht and Boat — Moody 54 review","url":"https://www.yachtandboat.com.au/moody-54-review/"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Four great centre-cockpit Moody yachts","url":"https://uk.boats.com/reviews/four-great-centre-cockpit-moody-yachts/","note":"boats.com overview of the Dixon centre-cockpit range"},{"name":"Moody 376 CC tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VGOmWoQj-tc","note":"Smaller-sibling walkthrough showing the Dixon centre-cockpit layout idiom"}]'::jsonb, array['Big, easily-handled centre-cockpit cutter — furling everything, self-tacking staysail, electric winches and a standard bow thruster make it a real two-person boat.', 'Stiff, immensely strong GRP hull with a Kevlar-reinforced underbody and a deep, glass-screened, well-sheltered cockpit.', 'Private full-beam aft owner''s stateroom with en-suite and separate shower, plus a richly finished teak liveaboard interior.', 'Generous tankage (682 L fuel / 995 L water) and abundant stowage for long passages.', 'Excellent value: a proven bluewater 54-footer for a fraction of an Oyster or Amel, with mostly mainstream, serviceable systems.']::text[], array['No inside steering — cold high-latitude watches are still stood in the open (if very sheltered) cockpit.', 'Balsa-cored topsides and teak decks demand diligent sealing/maintenance; deck-water ingress is the classic Moody worry.', 'Some weather helm when pressed past ~25 knots; in-mast furling main trades a little upwind shape and adds a jam risk.', 'Production-density fit-out — good engine access for the class, but not a walk-in workshop boat.', 'Smaller, more builder/forum-centred owner community than Oyster/Amel, and the brand changed hands several times.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Yacht and Boat (review)","note":"A ''very normal'' but thoroughly capable bluewater cruiser designed to carry seven in comfort; impressed by the protected centre cockpit and easy short-handed rig, with weather helm only when over-pressed.","url":"https://www.yachtandboat.com.au/moody-54-review/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (Selden triple-spreader alloy)","keelRudder":"Bolted lead/antimony fin keel with vestigial bulb (shoal option) · partially-balanced spade rudder on a short skeg · balsa-cored hull with Kevlar-reinforced underbody","complexity":"Moderate — furling rig, electric winches and a bow thruster, plus the usual cruising stack (genset, watermaker, heating, A/C) on equipped boats. Mainstream brands keep it serviceable, but it is still a systems-laden 54-footer.","maintain":"Moderate — mostly off-the-shelf hardware (Yanmar, Selden, Sleipner, Lewmar) is easy to source and service; the main effort goes into the teak deck, balsa-cored deck/hull sealing, and the standard Moody check items (chainplate seals, keel-bolt area, rudder shaft seal).","partsText":"Good for the class — Yanmar, Selden and mainstream deck gear are supported worldwide, and the Moody Owners Association keeps brochures, specs and a knowledge base alive. Builder support ended when the marque moved to Hanse, so parts come from the component makers rather than a factory.","problems":"Moody-typical items rather than design faults: chainplate deck seals dry out and let water into the bulkheads/core (check for rot), the chain locker can drain salt water into the bilge and corrode keel-bolt heads over time, rudder-shaft seals can weep, and teak decks/balsa core need moisture management. In-mast furling mains should be checked for jamming.","sentiment":"Well regarded as a strong, comfortable, easily-handled value bluewater cruiser; owners cross oceans in them. Criticism is mostly about generic production-cruiser limits (no inside helm, teak-deck upkeep) and a little weather helm when pressed, not about seaworthiness.","communities":[{"name":"Moody Owners Association","url":"https://www.moodyowners.org/"},{"name":"Moody Owners Information Exchange (forum)","url":"https://www.moodyowners.info/"}],"risks":["Check chainplate deck seals and surrounding bulkheads/core for water ingress and rot","Inspect keel-bolt heads and bilge for chain-locker salt-water corrosion","Verify rudder-shaft seal and the in-mast furling main for weeping/jamming","Teak deck and balsa core condition drive the refit budget on older hulls"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":4,"community":3}}'::jsonb),
  ('moody47', 'Moody 47', 'Princess Yachts International (A.H. Moody marque), UK', 'Bill Dixon', '#3a6377', '2001–2004 (46 built)', 'GRP (balsa-cored)', 'Centre-cockpit bluewater cruiser', 'Centre cockpit', '47''8" (14.53 m)', '~38''9" (11.8 m)', '14''5" (4.40 m)', '5''3" (1.60 m shoal)', '6''9" (2.06 m fin)', '14,950 kg / ~32,900 lb (fin)', '4,700 kg (~31%)', '~31%', '~112 m² / 1,205 ft² (cutter Yankee + main + staysail)', '~21 m / 69''', 'Yanmar 4JH diesel ~75 hp', 'Shaft', '3 cabins / 2 heads (7 berths)', 'Fin keel (or optional shoal); skeg-/partial-skeg-supported spade rudder; bolted ballast; bow thruster common', 'Sheltered centre cockpit with sprayhood/bimini; full-beam aft owner''s stateroom with dual access; davits often fitted', '431 L / 114 gal', '772 L / 204 gal', 14.53, 38.75, 14.44, 32900, 1.6, '~16.5', '~211', 431, 772, 75, 180000, 320000, 'fit', 1, 'The couple who want the Moody 54''s easily-handled centre-cockpit cruising in a slightly smaller, more affordable, more manageable package — a proven ARC/ocean boat with a private aft cabin that two people can run comfortably.', 'Good. A deep, inboard centre cockpit behind a sprayhood and bimini shelters the watch well, with secure side decks, bulwarks and good handrails. Like its bigger sister there is no inside helm, so cold-passage watches are stood in the open (sheltered) cockpit.', 'Keel-stepped masthead rig (I 17.70 m, J 5.29 m) with in-mast furling main standard; available as a self-tacking-staysail cutter with a furling Yankee and an optional furling genoa, so the whole sail plan is handled from the cockpit. Lines led aft to powered/electric winches on many boats.', 'Easy for two. In-mast furling, furling headsails and a self-tacking staysail mean almost no foredeck work, and many boats carry electric/hydraulic winches and a bow thruster for push-button reefing and short-handed docking. A moderate-displacement hull that is forgiving and stable rather than sporty.', 'The ~75 hp Yanmar sits under the cockpit sole with sole-board access; the full-beam aft stateroom and lazarette provide useful machinery and stowage space behind joinery. Adequate access for the class, but a production fit-out rather than a dedicated engine room.', 'Conventional, well-proven cruising systems: Yanmar shaft drive, calorifier hot water, and — on ocean-equipped boats — genset, watermaker, Webasto hot-air heating, A/C, SSB/satcomms, AIS, solar/wind and stern davits. Mainstream components throughout, so serviceable on the milk run.', 'Good for a couple. Deep lockers, a usable lazarette, and generous stowage in the full-beam aft cabin and forward cabin make it practical for extended cruising, if naturally tighter than the 54.', '431 L of fuel gives roughly ~500–700 nm under power, and 772 L of water is generous for two; a watermaker (commonly fitted) closes the gap for long ocean passages and remote anchorages.', 'Three cabins and two heads sleeping seven: a full-beam aft owner''s stateroom (often with dual access), a forward cabin, and a mid/guest cabin, plus a comfortable saloon, a proper galley and a chart table. A genuine liveaboard layout for a couple, with room for guests on passage.', 'Fair-to-good. Moderate-displacement, well-ballasted and strongly built, with a sheltered cockpit and Webasto heating common on cruising boats — but no inside steering and balsa-cored GRP with teak decks mean cold, wet climates demand good heating and diligent moisture management. Better suited to temperate and trade-wind cruising than serious ice/rock high-latitude work.', 'Very good. Opening hatches and ports give cross-ventilation, the bimini shades the cockpit, water tankage is generous, and most boats carry refrigeration, A/C and a watermaker. Davits, a swim ladder and a forgiving hull make it an easy, comfortable trade-wind and Caribbean cruiser.', '$180k–$320k (used)', 'Originally ~£250k–£300k new in the early 2000s', 'Used roughly $180k–$320k (≈£150k–£250k) depending on year, keel, equipment and refit state', 'Well inside the $1M budget — typically the high-$100k to low-$300k range — leaving plenty of headroom to add the watermaker, heating and electronics a high-latitude-plus-tropics plan needs. The most affordable way into a modern Dixon centre-cockpit Moody.', 'The 2001–2004 Bill Dixon Moody 47 (built by Princess Yachts International, 46 hulls) is distinct from the earlier 1980s Moody 47. A proven ocean cruiser — examples have completed multiple ARC transatlantics and tens of thousands of bluewater miles.', '{"protection":4,"handling":4.5,"dogs":3,"workshop":3,"storage":3.5,"tankage":3.5,"highlat":3,"tropical":4.5,"budget":5}'::jsonb, array['British centre cockpit', 'Push-button cutter', 'ARC-proven', 'Affordable bluewater 47']::text[], array['Two different Moody 47s exist — the 1980s boat and this 2001–2004 Bill Dixon design — so always check the year before comparing specs.', 'Built by Princess Yachts International, the marque''s owner at the time, sharing the Plymouth production lineage of the bigger Moody 54.', 'A favourite ARC and milk-run boat: equipped examples have racked up multiple Atlantic crossings and 25,000+ ocean miles.']::text[], array['2001 Moody 47 — £195,000 / ~US$245,000 (Apollo Duck, West Scotland)', '2002 Moody 47 — US$197,998 (YachtWorld brokerage listing)', '2000–2004 Moody 47 range US$200,000–US$500,000 (boats.com listings)']::text[], '[{"name":"Moody Owners Association — Moody 47 archive","url":"https://www.moodyowners.org/Moody_Archives/m47_boat.htm"},{"name":"SailboatData — Moody 47","url":"https://sailboatdata.com/sailboat/moody-47/"},{"name":"Grabau International — 2003 Moody 47 listing","url":"https://www.grabauinternational.com/news/2003-moody-47-now-sold/"},{"name":"Sailboat Guide — Moody 47","url":"https://sailboat.guide/moody/47"},{"name":"Apollo Duck — Moody 47 brokerage listings","url":"https://www.apolloduck.com/boat/moody-47-for-sale/717254"}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"Four great centre-cockpit Moody yachts","url":"https://uk.boats.com/reviews/four-great-centre-cockpit-moody-yachts/","note":"boats.com overview covering the Dixon centre-cockpit range"},{"name":"Moody 376 CC tour","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VGOmWoQj-tc","note":"Smaller-sibling walkthrough of the Dixon centre-cockpit idiom"}]'::jsonb, array['Easily-handled centre-cockpit cutter — in-mast furling, furling headsails and a self-tacking staysail make it a true two-person boat.', 'Proven ocean cruiser: equipped examples have completed multiple ARC transatlantics and 25,000+ miles.', 'Full-beam aft owner''s stateroom and a comfortable three-cabin liveaboard layout in a manageable 47-footer.', 'Mainstream, serviceable systems (Yanmar, Selden, Lewmar) and a strong used-value proposition — the cheapest route into a modern Dixon Moody.', 'Moderate-displacement, well-ballasted, forgiving hull that is stable and sea-kindly.']::text[], array['No inside steering — cold watches are stood in the open (sheltered) cockpit.', 'Balsa-cored GRP and teak decks need diligent sealing; deck-water ingress is the classic Moody check item.', 'Smaller fuel/water tankage than the 54 — a watermaker is effectively mandatory for long ocean legs.', 'In-mast furling main trades a little upwind shape and adds a jam risk; check it on survey.', 'Confusable with the 1980s Moody 47, and a smaller, builder/forum-centred owner community than Oyster/Amel.']::text[], array[]::text[], '[{"who":"Grabau International (brokerage)","note":"Described the 2003 boat as a ''Bill Dixon designed Moody 47 centre-cockpit bluewater cruising yacht'' with two completed ARC crossings and 25,000+ nm of proven ocean miles.","url":"https://www.grabauinternational.com/news/2003-moody-47-now-sold/"}]'::jsonb, 'Expert-reviewed', '{"mastStep":"Keel-stepped (Selden alloy)","keelRudder":"Bolted fin keel (shoal option) · spade rudder on a partial skeg · balsa-cored GRP hull","complexity":"Moderate — furling rig and electric/hydraulic winches plus the usual cruising stack (genset, watermaker, heating, A/C) on equipped boats; mainstream brands keep it serviceable but it is still a fully-found cruising 47.","maintain":"Moderate — off-the-shelf hardware (Yanmar, Selden, Lewmar) is easy to source and service; effort concentrates on teak-deck/balsa-core sealing and the standard Moody check items (chainplate seals, keel-bolt area, rudder-shaft seal).","partsText":"Good for the class — Yanmar, Selden and mainstream deck gear are supported worldwide, and the Moody Owners Association maintains brochures, specs and an active forum. No factory support since the marque moved to Hanse; parts come from the component makers.","problems":"Moody-typical maintenance rather than design faults: chainplate deck seals can dry out and admit water to the bulkheads/core, chain-locker drainage can corrode keel-bolt heads over time, rudder-shaft seals can weep, and teak decks plus balsa core need moisture control. Verify the in-mast furling main runs freely.","sentiment":"Liked as a comfortable, capable, easily-handled value cruiser that two people can take across oceans; criticism centres on generic production-cruiser limits (no inside helm, teak-deck upkeep) rather than seaworthiness.","communities":[{"name":"Moody Owners Association","url":"https://www.moodyowners.org/"},{"name":"Moody Owners Information Exchange (forum)","url":"https://www.moodyowners.info/"}],"risks":["Confirm which Moody 47 it is (2001–2004 Dixon model, not the 1980s boat)","Check chainplate deck seals and surrounding bulkheads/core for water ingress","Inspect keel-bolt heads/bilge for chain-locker salt-water corrosion and the rudder-shaft seal","Teak deck and balsa core condition drive the refit budget"],"scores":{"maintain":3,"simplicity":3,"parts":4,"community":3}}'::jsonb)
on conflict (id) do update set
  name = excluded.name,
  builder = excluded.builder,
  designer = excluded.designer,
  color = excluded.color,
  years = excluded.years,
  material = excluded.material,
  category = excluded.category,
